{"title_page": "Tyler Walker (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tyler Walker\n| image          = Tyler Walker.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Walker in Nottingham Forest kit, 2016\n| fullname       = Tyler J. Andrew Walker<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/image/201920/general-news/efl-squad-numbering-06.09.2019.pdf |title=Notification of shirt numbers: Lincoln City |publisher=English Football League |page=38 |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1996|10|17}}\n| birth_place    = [[Nottingham]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.79|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FootballSquads - Port Vale - 2016/17 |url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/2016-2017/flone/portv.htm |website=www.footballsquads.co.uk |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub    = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubnumber     = 34\n| youthyears1    = 2006\u20132015\n| youthclubs1    = [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-21s Squad and Academy|Nottingham Forest]]\n| years1         = 2015\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| caps1 = 39\n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2016\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 6\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 8\n| goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2017\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 6\n| goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2018\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 44 <!--LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| goals6 = 22\n| years7 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] (loan)\n| caps7 = 29\n| goals7 = 14\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| club-update    = 6 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Tyler J. Andrew Walker''' (born 17 October 1996) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|NottingF}} club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. He is the son of former [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Des Walker]].\n\nAn [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] international, he made his first-team debut for hometown club Nottingham Forest in March 2015. He has played on loan at [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]], [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]], and was named on the [[EFL League Two]] [[PFA Team of the Year]] for the 2018\u201319 season whilst with Mansfield.\n\n==Club career==\n===Nottingham Forest===\n====2014\u201315 season====\nWalker made his professional debut for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] as a substitute for [[Chris Burke (footballer)|Chris Burke]] in the 92nd minute of a 2\u20130 win over [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 18 March 2015.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Forest 2-0 Rotherham |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735742 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=18 March 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150830/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735742 |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Walker's first professional goal followed on 7 April in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at [[Griffin Park]] after he entered the game as a first-half substitute, on only his fourth first-team appearance.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Brentford 2-2 Forest |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735919 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412095614/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735919 |archivedate=12 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He signed a four-year contract with Forest in June 2015.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Tyler Walker: Nottingham Forest Deal for Des Walker's Son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32983671 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOwing much to a shortage of strikers and manager [[Dougie Freedman]]'s willingness to give youth an opportunity, Walker played a number of games at the beginning of Forest's [[2015\u201316 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season. This included a start in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], a 4\u20133 defeat by [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] at the [[City Ground]] on 11 August; a game in which he scored his second goal in professional football.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Forest 3-4 Walsall |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/forest-v-walsall-match-report-2494759.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=11 August 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\nOn 24 March, Walker joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] on loan until the end of the [[2015\u201316 Burton Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season, where he would link-up with former Forest striker and Burton manager [[Nigel Clough]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Walker joins Burton |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/tyler-walker-joins-burton-albion-on-loan-3023196.aspx#I0QKqSJrkzirdGHU.99 |publisher=Nottingham Forest FC |date=24 March 2016 |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> Walker made his Burton debut four days later as a half-time substitute in a 2\u20130 defeat at [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Millwall 2-0 Burton Albion |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35858790 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 March 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> In 'The Brewers' following game on 2 April, he came off the bench to score an injury-time equaliser in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at the [[Pirelli Stadium]].<ref>{{citeweb |title= Burton Albion 1-1 Bury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35902401 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 April 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> He returned to Forest at the end of the season having made six appearances for Burton Albion, scoring one goal.\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nSpeaking in August 2016, new Forest manager [[Philippe Montanier]] stated that he was unable to assess Walker due to an injury that left him unable to play a part in pre-season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Montanier hoping young Reds can emerge victorious from Lions' Den|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/ambitious-montanier-hoping-young-reds-can-emerge-from-lions-den-with-place-in-efl-cup-third-round/story-29643605-detail/story.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Nottingham Post|date=22 August 2016}}</ref> On 31 August, Walker signed on loan with [[EFL League Two]] side [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] for the remainder of the [[2016\u201317 Stevenage F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Walker makes loan move |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/nottingham-forest-tyler-walker-stevenage-loan-3283546.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=31 August 2016 |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> He made his debut in a 6\u20131 win over [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] at [[Broadhall Way]] on 2 September; he scored a brace in the match, the first of which was an overhead kick from close range \u2013 this performance earned him a place on the EFL team of the week.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hannah |first1=Alex |title=Sky Bet EFL: Team of the Week |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2016/september/sky-bet-efl-team-of-the-week/ |accessdate=9 October 2019 |work=www.efl.com |date=5 September 2016 |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report |url=http://www.stevenagefc.com/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?MatchId=3925541 |publisher=Stevenage F.C. |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> On 4 October, Walker scored on his debut in the [[EFL Trophy]] in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion's]] U-23 side.<ref>{{Citeweb |title=Match Report: Stevenage 2 Brighton & Hove Albion 2 |url=http://mobile.stevenagefc.com/news/article/2016-17/match-report-stevenage-2-brighton-hove-albion-2-3347156.aspx |publisher=Stevenage F.C. |date=4 October 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref> Having scored four goals in his first six games for 'The Boro', Walker missed a home game against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] on 8 October after picking up a \"freak injury\" in training.<ref>{{Citeweb |title=Nottingham Forest striker Tyler Walker's Stevenage progress halted by 'freak injury' |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/nottingham-forest-striker-tyler-walker-s-stevenage-progress-halted-by-freak-injury/story-29794160-detail/story.html |publisher=Nottingham Post |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He eventually made his return from injury as a substitute in a 4\u20132 home defeat to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] on 31 December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stevenage 2-4 Colchester United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38424465|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=31 December 2016}}</ref> Speaking after the match, manager [[Darren Sarll]] admitted that he \"forgot just how good\" Walker was.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Storey|first1=Matt|title=Sarll 'forgot how good' Tyler Walker is|url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/i-forgot-how-good-he-was-darren-sarll-discusses-nottingham-forest-striker-tyler-walker-s-return/story-30033707-detail/story.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Hertfordshire Mercury|date=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nWalker's loan spell with Stevenage ended earlier than planned, as Forest recalled the player on 13 January with the intention of securing him with a loan move to a League One club.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Loan Players Return |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/nottingham-forest-loan-transfer-tyler-walker-3516519.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=13 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ly\"/> Four days after his recall from Stevenage, Walker joined League One side [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on loan until the end of the [[2016\u201317 Port Vale F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref name=\"tws\">{{cite news|title=Tyler Walker: Port Vale sign Nottingham Forest striker on half-season loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38655357|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=17 January 2017}}</ref> He scored the opening goal on his debut with a \"superb 20-yard strike\" for 'The Valiants', before also going on to win a penalty in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at [[Vale Park]] on 20 January.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Port Vale 2-2 Bury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38605791 |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 20 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ly\">{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale: Tyler Walker impressed with Valiants after debut|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-tyler-walker-impressed-with-valiants-after-impressive-debut/story-30077193-detail/story.html|accessdate=23 January 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=23 January 2017|language=en}}</ref> Walker's poor luck with injuries continued, however, as he sustained a knee ligament injury the following month which caretaker-manager [[Michael Brown (footballer, born 1977)|Michael Brown]] said would keep him out of action for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale 1, Bristol Rovers 1: Walker could be out for the season|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-1-bristol-rovers-1-tyler-walker-could-be-out-for-the-season/story-30146129-detail/story.html|accessdate=12 March 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=18 February 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale lose three players to long-term injury, manager reveals|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-lose-three-players-to-long-term-injury-manager-reveals/story-30258026-detail/story.html|accessdate=8 April 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=8 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nAhead of the [[2017\u201318 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season Forest manager [[Mark Warburton]], who had been appointed as Montanier's permanent successor in March 2017, suggested that Walker would be involved with the first-team, claiming that he had \"benefited from being in and around the first team squad here this summer\" and that \"other players need to go out on loan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Grant will return to Notts County but Walker will get the chance to impress with Nottingham Forest |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/transfer-news/grant-return-notts-county-walker-219523 |publisher=Nottingham Post |author=Paul Taylor |date=5 August 2017}}</ref> On 23 August, Walker came off the bench to score the winning goal in extra-time of a 3\u20132 victory over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] at [[St James' Park]] in the second round of the EFL Cup. After the game Warburton confirmed in a post-match interview that Walker would remain at Forest for the season. He said: \"We've had a host of clubs queuing up for Tyler Walker's services but he'll stay with us because of the reasons you've seen tonight. He's worked tirelessly to recover from injury, had a brilliant pre-season and that resulted in the quality of performance you've seen this evening.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Joy on the Tyne |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2017/august/joy-on-the-tyne/ |publisher=Nottingham Forest Football Club Official Website |author=Unknown author |date=23 August 2017}}</ref> On 4 November, he scored the first brace of his senior career in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], earning himself a mention in the EFL team of the week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nottingham Forest 4-0 Queens Park Rangers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41785602|accessdate=5 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=4 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Team of the Week: 3rd-5th November 2017 |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2017/november/team-of-the-week-3rd-5th-november-2017/ |accessdate=8 October 2019 |work=www.efl.com |date=6 November 2017 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 28 November, Walker signed a new contract at Forest, due to expire in 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theleaguepaper.com/featured/9550/nottingham-forest-youngster-tyler-walker-signs-new-contract/|title=Nottingham Forest youngster Tyler Walker signs new contract|date=28 November 2017|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=theleaguepaper.com|publisher=The League Paper}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2018, Walker joined fellow Championship side [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on loan for the rest of the [[2017\u201318 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walker joins Bolton on loan|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2018/january/walker-joins-bolton-on-loan/|accessdate=10 May 2018|work=nottinghamforest.co.uk|date=31 January 2018|language=en-gb}}</ref> He made his Wanderers d\u00e9but in their 1\u20130 victory over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], starting the match and lasting 58 minutes before being substituted; he was replaced by fellow Forest loanee [[Zach Clough]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Championship: Bolton Wanderers 1-0 Bristol City - Live|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/42613795|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=2 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> However he featured just five times for the \"Trotters\" as manager [[Phil Parkinson]] instead demoted both Walker and Clough to playing for the [[Bolton Wanderers F.C. Reserves and Academy|youth team]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clapson|first1=Sarah|title=Bolton boss explains why on-loan Forest duo were dropped to Under-23s|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/bolton-wanderers-boss-explains-loan-1413326|accessdate=14 May 2018|work=Nottingham Post|date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nOn 29 June 2018, Walker joined League Two side [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44659782|title=Mansfield Town: Craig Davies, Otis Khan and Tyler Walker all join the Stags|date=29 June 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> On 4 August, he scored 12 minutes into his debut for the \"Stags\" in a 3\u20130 win over [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] at [[Field Mill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mansfield Town 3-0 Newport County: Assistant referee stretchered off |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989421 |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2018}}</ref> He scored a first-half hat-trick ten days later as Mansfield recorded a 6\u20131 home victory over [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in the first round of the [[EFL Cup]]; manager [[David Flitcroft]] said that Walker was \"pure class\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cusack |first1=Richard |title='Pure class' Tyler Walker's hat-trick sees Stags through |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/pure-class-tyler-walker-hits-1900198 |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=Nottingham Post |date=15 August 2018}}</ref> He scored his 15th goal of the season during a 2\u20131 Boxing day victory over [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], taking Mansfield into the automatic promotion places.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Barry |title=Walker focused on Mansfield and not events at Forest |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/tyler-walker-mansfield-town-forest-2365034 |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=27 December 2018}}</ref> His scoring tally resulted in speculation that Forest manager [[Aitor Karanka]] would recall him in the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Birtles |first1=Garry |title=Is Tyler Walker giving Forest boss Karanka food for thought? |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/sport-opinion/tyler-walker-giving-nottingham-forest-2367415 |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=28 December 2018}}</ref> He was named on League Two's [[PFA Team of the Year]] for the [[2018\u201319 Mansfield Town F.C. season|2018\u201319]] campaign, alongside Mansfield teammate [[Krystian Pearce]].<ref name=\"pfa\">{{cite news |title=League Two: Lincoln and Bury dominate PFA selection of team of 2018-19 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48035839 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> He was named as man of the match in the play-off semi-final first-leg against [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], but had his penalty saved in the shootout at the end of the second leg as Mansfield were eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leach |first1=Tom |title=Tyler Walker named in FIFA's team of the season |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forests-tyler-walker-named-2856573 |accessdate=13 May 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Clapson |first1=Sarah |title=Tyler Walker 'distraught' at costly penalty miss |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forest-loanee-tyler-walker-2860582 |accessdate=13 May 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\nOn 2 August 2019, Walker joined League One side [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on loan for the [[2019\u201320 Lincoln City F.C. season|2019\u201320]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imps secure signing of Tyler Walker|url=https://www.weareimps.com/news/2019/august/190802-walker-signs/|publisher=[[Lincoln City F.C.]] |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tyler Walker: Lincoln City sign Nottingham Forest striker on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49208363 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Manager [[Danny Cowley]] said that \"he's been on our wish list forever.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whiley |first1=Mark |title=Imps clinch signing of highly-rated Forest striker Tyler Walker |url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/lincoln-city-clinch-signing-highly-3165769 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=lincolnshirelive |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> After scoring 16 goals in 34 games for the \"Imps\", Walker was recalled to parent club Nottingham Forest by manager [[Sabri Lamouchi]] on 30 January.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whiley |first1=Mark |title=City lose top scorer as Walker returns to Forest |url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/i-am-sorry-that-lincoln-3796413 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=lincolnshirelive |date=30 January 2020}}</ref> He was then restricted to appearances from the substitutes bench at Forest, though did manage to score against league leaders [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 8 February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tonge |first1=Jake |title=Feature: Have Nottingham Forest really made the right call with Tyler Walker following impressive Imps form? {{!}} Football League World |url=https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/feature-have-nottingham-forest-really-made-the-right-call-with-tyler-walker-following-impressive-imps-form/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=footballleagueworld.co.uk |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> He was cited as being the \"next in line\" by star striker [[Lewis Grabban]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clapson |first1=Sarah |title=Lewis Grabban on who will be 'next in line' as Reds' talisman |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forest-ace-identifies-who-3918205 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Nottingham Post |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 5 September 2015, Walker made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] and scored a brace in a 5\u20130 win over the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Two for Tyler on 20 Debut |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/two-for-tyler-on-20s-debut-2673931.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=7 September 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nWalker is a pacey and athletic [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yousif|first1=Layth|title=FEATURE: Tyler Walker looks forward to achieving goals with Stevenage|url=http://www.thecomet.net/sport/football/feature_tyler_walker_looks_forward_to_achieving_goals_with_stevenage_1_4682702|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=The Comet|date=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalker is the son of former Forest and [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Des Walker]]<ref>{{citeweb |title=Tyler Walker: Nottingham Forest forward needs support - Jason Lee |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34186594 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |title=Des Walker says son Tyler has much more talent than he did |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34354711 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> and elder brother of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] striker [[Lewis Walker (footballer)|Lewis Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Youngsters Rowan and Walker sign pro deals |url=https://www.qpr.co.uk/news/under-23s-news/youngsters-rowan-and-walker-sign-pro-deals/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |work=qpr.co.uk |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 6 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2014|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|7||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"15/16\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2015|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|14||0||0||0||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"16/17\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2016|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"17/18\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2017|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|12||3||1||0||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||4\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"18/19\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2018|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"19/20\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2019|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|6||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!39!!5!!1!!0!!4!!2!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!44!!7\n|-\n|[[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n|[[2015\u201316 Burton Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"15/16\"/>\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|6||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||6||1\n|-\n|[[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] (loan)\n|[[2016\u201317 Stevenage F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"16/17\"/>\n|[[EFL League Two|League Two]]\n|8||3||0||0||0||0||1{{efn|name=flt|Appearance(s) in the [[EFL Trophy]]}}||1||9||4\n|-\n|[[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] (loan)\n|[[2016\u201317 Port Vale F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"16/17\"/>\n|League One\n|6||2||0||0||0||0||0||0||6||2\n|-\n|[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] (loan)\n|[[2017\u201318 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"17/18\"/>\n|Championship\n|5||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0\n|-\n|[[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] (loan)\n|[[2018\u201319 Mansfield Town F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"18/19\"/>\n|League Two\n|44||22||2||0||2||3||4{{efn|2 appearances and 1 goal in the EFL Trophy and 2 appearances in the play-offs}}||1||52||26\n|-\n|[[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] (loan)\n|[[2019\u201320 Lincoln City F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"19/20\"/>\n|League One\n|29||14||2||1||1||0||2{{efn|name=flt}}||1||34||16\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!137!!47!!5!!1!!7!!5!!7!!3!!156!!56\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n;Individual\n*[[EFL League Two]] [[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[2018\u201319 Mansfield Town F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"pfa\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerway}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players?p=357056 England profile] at The FA\n\n{{Nottingham Forest F.C. squad}}\n{{2018\u201319 EFL League Two PFA Team of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Tyler}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:People educated at West Bridgford School]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stevenage F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tyler Walker\n| image          = Tyler Walker.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Walker in Nottingham Forest kit, 2016\n| fullname       = Tyler J. Andrew Walker<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/image/201920/general-news/efl-squad-numbering-06.09.2019.pdf |title=Notification of shirt numbers: Lincoln City |publisher=English Football League |page=38 |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1996|10|17}}\n| birth_place    = [[Nottingham]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.79|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FootballSquads - Port Vale - 2016/17 |url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/2016-2017/flone/portv.htm |website=www.footballsquads.co.uk |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub    = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubnumber     = 34\n| youthyears1    = 2006\u20132015\n| youthclubs1    = [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-21s Squad and Academy|Nottingham Forest]]\n| years1         = 2015\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| caps1 = 39\n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2016\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 6\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 8\n| goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2017\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 6\n| goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2018\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 44 <!--LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| goals6 = 22\n| years7 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] (loan)\n| caps7 = 29\n| goals7 = 14\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| club-update    = 6 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Tyler J. Andrew Walker''' (born 17 October 1996) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|NottingF}} club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. He is the son of former [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Des Walker]].\n\nAn [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] international, he made his first-team debut for hometown club Nottingham Forest in March 2015. He has played on loan at [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]], [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]], and was named on the [[EFL League Two]] [[PFA Team of the Year]] for the 2018\u201319 season whilst with Mansfield.\n\n==Club career==\n===Nottingham Forest===\n====2014\u201315 season====\nWalker made his professional debut for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] as a substitute for [[Chris Burke (footballer)|Chris Burke]] in the 92nd minute of a 2\u20130 win over [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 18 March 2015.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Forest 2-0 Rotherham |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735742 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=18 March 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150830/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735742 |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Walker's first professional goal followed on 7 April in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at [[Griffin Park]] after he entered the game as a first-half substitute, on only his fourth first-team appearance.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Brentford 2-2 Forest |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735919 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412095614/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3735919 |archivedate=12 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He signed a four-year contract with Forest in June 2015.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Tyler Walker: Nottingham Forest Deal for Des Walker's Son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32983671 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOwing much to a shortage of strikers and manager [[Dougie Freedman]]'s willingness to give youth an opportunity, Walker played a number of games at the beginning of Forest's [[2015\u201316 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season. This included a start in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], a 4\u20133 defeat by [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] at the [[City Ground]] on 11 August; a game in which he scored his second goal in professional football.<ref>{{citeweb |title=Forest 3-4 Walsall |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/forest-v-walsall-match-report-2494759.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=11 August 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\nOn 24 March, Walker joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] on loan until the end of the [[2015\u201316 Burton Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season, where he would link-up with former Forest striker and Burton manager [[Nigel Clough]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Walker joins Burton |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/tyler-walker-joins-burton-albion-on-loan-3023196.aspx#I0QKqSJrkzirdGHU.99 |publisher=Nottingham Forest FC |date=24 March 2016 |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> Walker made his Burton debut four days later as a half-time substitute in a 2\u20130 defeat at [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Millwall 2-0 Burton Albion |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35858790 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 March 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> In 'The Brewers' following game on 2 April, he came off the bench to score an injury-time equaliser in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at the [[Pirelli Stadium]].<ref>{{citeweb |title= Burton Albion 1-1 Bury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35902401 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 April 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> He returned to Forest at the end of the season having made six appearances for Burton Albion, scoring one goal.\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nSpeaking in August 2016, new Forest manager [[Philippe Montanier]] stated that he was unable to assess Walker due to an injury that left him unable to play a part in pre-season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Montanier hoping young Reds can emerge victorious from Lions' Den|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/ambitious-montanier-hoping-young-reds-can-emerge-from-lions-den-with-place-in-efl-cup-third-round/story-29643605-detail/story.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Nottingham Post|date=22 August 2016}}</ref> On 31 August, Walker signed on loan with [[EFL League Two]] side [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] for the remainder of the [[2016\u201317 Stevenage F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Walker makes loan move |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/nottingham-forest-tyler-walker-stevenage-loan-3283546.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=31 August 2016 |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> He made his debut in a 6\u20131 win over [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] at [[Broadhall Way]] on 2 September; he scored a brace in the match, the first of which was an overhead kick from close range \u2013 this performance earned him a place on the EFL team of the week.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hannah |first1=Alex |title=Sky Bet EFL: Team of the Week |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2016/september/sky-bet-efl-team-of-the-week/ |accessdate=9 October 2019 |work=www.efl.com |date=5 September 2016 |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report |url=http://www.stevenagefc.com/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?MatchId=3925541 |publisher=Stevenage F.C. |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> On 4 October, Walker scored on his debut in the [[EFL Trophy]] in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion's]] U-23 side.<ref>{{Citeweb |title=Match Report: Stevenage 2 Brighton & Hove Albion 2 |url=http://mobile.stevenagefc.com/news/article/2016-17/match-report-stevenage-2-brighton-hove-albion-2-3347156.aspx |publisher=Stevenage F.C. |date=4 October 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref> Having scored four goals in his first six games for 'The Boro', Walker missed a home game against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] on 8 October after picking up a \"freak injury\" in training.<ref>{{Citeweb |title=Nottingham Forest striker Tyler Walker's Stevenage progress halted by 'freak injury' |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/nottingham-forest-striker-tyler-walker-s-stevenage-progress-halted-by-freak-injury/story-29794160-detail/story.html |publisher=Nottingham Post |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He eventually made his return from injury as a substitute in a 4\u20132 home defeat to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] on 31 December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stevenage 2-4 Colchester United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38424465|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=31 December 2016}}</ref> Speaking after the match, manager [[Darren Sarll]] admitted that he \"forgot just how good\" Walker was.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Storey|first1=Matt|title=Sarll 'forgot how good' Tyler Walker is|url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/i-forgot-how-good-he-was-darren-sarll-discusses-nottingham-forest-striker-tyler-walker-s-return/story-30033707-detail/story.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Hertfordshire Mercury|date=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nWalker's loan spell with Stevenage ended earlier than planned, as Forest recalled the player on 13 January with the intention of securing him with a loan move to a League One club.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Loan Players Return |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/nottingham-forest-loan-transfer-tyler-walker-3516519.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=13 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ly\"/> Four days after his recall from Stevenage, Walker joined League One side [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on loan until the end of the [[2016\u201317 Port Vale F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref name=\"tws\">{{cite news|title=Tyler Walker: Port Vale sign Nottingham Forest striker on half-season loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38655357|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=17 January 2017}}</ref> He scored the opening goal on his debut with a \"superb 20-yard strike\" for 'The Valiants', before also going on to win a penalty in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at [[Vale Park]] on 20 January.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Port Vale 2-2 Bury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38605791 |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 20 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ly\">{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale: Tyler Walker impressed with Valiants after debut|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-tyler-walker-impressed-with-valiants-after-impressive-debut/story-30077193-detail/story.html|accessdate=23 January 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=23 January 2017|language=en}}</ref> Walker's poor luck with injuries continued, however, as he sustained a knee ligament injury the following month which caretaker-manager [[Michael Brown (footballer, born 1977)|Michael Brown]] said would keep him out of action for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale 1, Bristol Rovers 1: Walker could be out for the season|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-1-bristol-rovers-1-tyler-walker-could-be-out-for-the-season/story-30146129-detail/story.html|accessdate=12 March 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=18 February 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Port Vale lose three players to long-term injury, manager reveals|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/port-vale-lose-three-players-to-long-term-injury-manager-reveals/story-30258026-detail/story.html|accessdate=8 April 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=8 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nAhead of the [[2017\u201318 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season Forest manager [[Mark Warburton]], who had been appointed as Montanier's permanent successor in March 2017, suggested that Walker would be involved with the first-team, claiming that he had \"benefited from being in and around the first team squad here this summer\" and that \"other players need to go out on loan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Grant will return to Notts County but Walker will get the chance to impress with Nottingham Forest |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/transfer-news/grant-return-notts-county-walker-219523 |publisher=Nottingham Post |author=Paul Taylor |date=5 August 2017}}</ref> On 23 August, Walker came off the bench to score the winning goal in extra-time of a 3\u20132 victory over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] at [[St James' Park]] in the second round of the EFL Cup. After the game Warburton confirmed in a post-match interview that Walker would remain at Forest for the season. He said: \"We've had a host of clubs queuing up for Tyler Walker's services but he'll stay with us because of the reasons you've seen tonight. He's worked tirelessly to recover from injury, had a brilliant pre-season and that resulted in the quality of performance you've seen this evening.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Joy on the Tyne |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2017/august/joy-on-the-tyne/ |publisher=Nottingham Forest Football Club Official Website |author=Unknown author |date=23 August 2017}}</ref> On 4 November, he scored the first brace of his senior career in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], earning himself a mention in the EFL team of the week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nottingham Forest 4-0 Queens Park Rangers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41785602|accessdate=5 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=4 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Team of the Week: 3rd-5th November 2017 |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2017/november/team-of-the-week-3rd-5th-november-2017/ |accessdate=8 October 2019 |work=www.efl.com |date=6 November 2017 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 28 November, Walker signed a new contract at Forest, due to expire in 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theleaguepaper.com/featured/9550/nottingham-forest-youngster-tyler-walker-signs-new-contract/|title=Nottingham Forest youngster Tyler Walker signs new contract|date=28 November 2017|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=theleaguepaper.com|publisher=The League Paper}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2018, Walker joined fellow Championship side [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on loan for the rest of the [[2017\u201318 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walker joins Bolton on loan|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2018/january/walker-joins-bolton-on-loan/|accessdate=10 May 2018|work=nottinghamforest.co.uk|date=31 January 2018|language=en-gb}}</ref> He made his Wanderers d\u00e9but in their 1\u20130 victory over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], starting the match and lasting 58 minutes before being substituted; he was replaced by fellow Forest loanee [[Zach Clough]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Championship: Bolton Wanderers 1-0 Bristol City - Live|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/42613795|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=2 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> However he featured just five times for the \"Trotters\" as manager [[Phil Parkinson]] instead demoted both Walker and Clough to playing for the [[Bolton Wanderers F.C. Reserves and Academy|youth team]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clapson|first1=Sarah|title=Bolton boss explains why on-loan Forest duo were dropped to Under-23s|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/bolton-wanderers-boss-explains-loan-1413326|accessdate=14 May 2018|work=Nottingham Post|date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nOn 29 June 2018, Walker joined League Two side [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44659782|title=Mansfield Town: Craig Davies, Otis Khan and Tyler Walker all join the Stags|date=29 June 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> On 4 August, he scored 12 minutes into his debut for the \"Stags\" in a 3\u20130 win over [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] at [[Field Mill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mansfield Town 3-0 Newport County: Assistant referee stretchered off |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989421 |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2018}}</ref> He scored a first-half hat-trick ten days later as Mansfield recorded a 6\u20131 home victory over [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in the first round of the [[EFL Cup]]; manager [[David Flitcroft]] said that Walker was \"pure class\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cusack |first1=Richard |title='Pure class' Tyler Walker's hat-trick sees Stags through |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/pure-class-tyler-walker-hits-1900198 |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=Nottingham Post |date=15 August 2018}}</ref> He scored his 15th goal of the season during a 2\u20131 Boxing day victory over [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], taking Mansfield into the automatic promotion places.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Barry |title=Walker focused on Mansfield and not events at Forest |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/tyler-walker-mansfield-town-forest-2365034 |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=27 December 2018}}</ref> His scoring tally resulted in speculation that Forest manager [[Aitor Karanka]] would recall him in the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Birtles |first1=Garry |title=Is Tyler Walker giving Forest boss Karanka food for thought? |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/sport-opinion/tyler-walker-giving-nottingham-forest-2367415 |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=28 December 2018}}</ref> He was named on League Two's [[PFA Team of the Year]] for the [[2018\u201319 Mansfield Town F.C. season|2018\u201319]] campaign, alongside Mansfield teammate [[Krystian Pearce]].<ref name=\"pfa\">{{cite news |title=League Two: Lincoln and Bury dominate PFA selection of team of 2018-19 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48035839 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> He was named as man of the match in the play-off semi-final first-leg against [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], but had his penalty saved in the shootout at the end of the second leg as Mansfield were eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leach |first1=Tom |title=Tyler Walker named in FIFA's team of the season |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forests-tyler-walker-named-2856573 |accessdate=13 May 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Clapson |first1=Sarah |title=Tyler Walker 'distraught' at costly penalty miss |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forest-loanee-tyler-walker-2860582 |accessdate=13 May 2019 |work=Nottingham Post |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\nOn 2 August 2019, Walker joined League One side [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on loan for the [[2019\u201320 Lincoln City F.C. season|2019\u201320]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imps secure signing of Tyler Walker|url=https://www.weareimps.com/news/2019/august/190802-walker-signs/|publisher=[[Lincoln City F.C.]] |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tyler Walker: Lincoln City sign Nottingham Forest striker on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49208363 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Manager [[Danny Cowley]] said that \"he\u2019s been on our wish list forever.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whiley |first1=Mark |title=Imps clinch signing of highly-rated Forest striker Tyler Walker |url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/lincoln-city-clinch-signing-highly-3165769 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=lincolnshirelive |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> After scoring 16 goals in 34 games for the \"Imps\", Walker was recalled to parent club Nottingham Forest by manager [[Sabri Lamouchi]] on 30 January.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whiley |first1=Mark |title=City lose top scorer as Walker returns to Forest |url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/i-am-sorry-that-lincoln-3796413 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=lincolnshirelive |date=30 January 2020}}</ref> He was then restricted to appearances from the substitutes bench at Forest, though did manage to score against league leaders [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 8 February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tonge |first1=Jake |title=Feature: Have Nottingham Forest really made the right call with Tyler Walker following impressive Imps form? {{!}} Football League World |url=https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/feature-have-nottingham-forest-really-made-the-right-call-with-tyler-walker-following-impressive-imps-form/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=footballleagueworld.co.uk |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> He was cited as being the \"next in line\" by star striker [[Lewis Grabban]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clapson |first1=Sarah |title=Lewis Grabban on who will be 'next in line' as Reds' talisman |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/nottingham-forest-ace-identifies-who-3918205 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Nottingham Post |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 5 September 2015, Walker made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] and scored a brace in a 5\u20130 win over the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{citeweb |title=Two for Tyler on 20 Debut |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/two-for-tyler-on-20s-debut-2673931.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=7 September 2015 |accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nWalker is a pacey and athletic [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yousif|first1=Layth|title=FEATURE: Tyler Walker looks forward to achieving goals with Stevenage|url=http://www.thecomet.net/sport/football/feature_tyler_walker_looks_forward_to_achieving_goals_with_stevenage_1_4682702|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=The Comet|date=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalker is the son of former Forest and [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Des Walker]]<ref>{{citeweb |title=Tyler Walker: Nottingham Forest forward needs support - Jason Lee |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34186594 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |title=Des Walker says son Tyler has much more talent than he did |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34354711 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> and elder brother of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] striker [[Lewis Walker (footballer)|Lewis Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Youngsters Rowan and Walker sign pro deals |url=https://www.qpr.co.uk/news/under-23s-news/youngsters-rowan-and-walker-sign-pro-deals/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |work=qpr.co.uk |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 6 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2014|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|7||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"15/16\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2015|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|14||0||0||0||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"16/17\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2016|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"17/18\">{{Soccerbase season|id=78132|season=2017|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n