[[2018\u201319 Mansfield Town F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"pfa\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerway}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players?p=357056 England profile] at The FA\n\n{{Nottingham Forest F.C. squad}}\n{{2018\u201319 EFL League Two PFA Team of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Tyler}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:People educated at West Bridgford School]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stevenage F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2019\u201320 season:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tyler_Walker_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "The Lovely Bones (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2009 film based on Alice Sebold's 2002 novel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Lovely Bones\n| image          = Lovely bones ver2.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Jackson]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Carolynne Cunningham]]\n* [[Fran Walsh]]\n* Peter Jackson\n* Aimee Peyronnet\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Fran Walsh\n* [[Philippa Boyens]]\n* Peter Jackson\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Lovely Bones]]''|[[Alice Sebold]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* [[Rachel Weisz]]\n* [[Susan Sarandon]]\n* [[Stanley Tucci]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]]\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Brian Eno]]\n| cinematography = [[Andrew Lesnie]]\n| editing        = [[Jabez Olssen]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DreamWorks Pictures]]\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[WingNut Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|11|24|Royal premiere|2009|12|11|United States|2009|12|26|New Zealand|2010|01|29|United Kingdom}}<!--WP:FILMRELEASE-->\n| runtime        = 135 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 135:22--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lovely-bones-2010-2 | title=''THE LOVELY BONES'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 24, 2009 | accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n* New Zealand<ref name=\"lumiere\"/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $65 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n| gross          = $93.6 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Lovely Bones''''' is a 2009 [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]] [[thriller film|thriller]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Peter Jackson]], and starring [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Rachel Weisz]], [[Susan Sarandon]], [[Stanley Tucci]], [[Michael Imperioli]], and [[Saoirse Ronan]]. The screenplay by [[Fran Walsh]], [[Philippa Boyens]], and Jackson was based on [[Alice Sebold]]\u2019s award-winning and bestselling [[The Lovely Bones|2002 novel of the same name]]. It follows a girl who is murdered and watches over her family from \"the in-between\", and is torn between seeking vengeance on her killer and allowing her family to heal.\n\nAn international co-production between the United States, the United Kingdom, and New Zealand,<ref name=\"lumiere\">{{cite web|title=Lovely Bones (EN)|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=34455|website=Lumiere|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> the film was produced by [[Carolynne Cunningham]], Walsh, Jackson, and Aimee Peyronnet, with [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tessa Ross]], Ken Kamins, and James Wilson as executive producers. [[Principal photography]] began in October 2007 in [[New Zealand]] and [[Pennsylvania]]. The film's score was composed by [[Brian Eno]].\n\n''The Lovely Bones'' was first released on December 26, 2009 in New Zealand, and then internationally in January 2010. The film's North American release date was changed multiple times, with a limited release on December 11, 2009, and a wider release on January 15, 2010.<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lovelybones.htm |title=THE LOVELY BONES |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> It was released to mainly mixed reviews from critics; the story and its message were generally criticized, with praise mainly aimed at the visual effects, Peter Jackson's direction, and the performances of Ronan and Tucci. In the film's opening weekend, in limited release, it grossed $116,616, despite only having been screened in three theaters, placing it at 30th place on the box office chart.<ref name=\"bom\"/> ''The Lovely Bones'' grossed over $44 million in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lovelybones.htm |title=The Lovely Bones (2009) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> The film also received numerous accolades, with Tucci being nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nIn 1973, 14-year-old high school freshman Susie Salmon dreams of becoming a photographer. One day, Ray, a boy she has a crush on, asks her out. As Susie walks home through a cornfield, she runs into her neighbor, George Harvey, who coaxes her into an underground \"kid's hideout\" he has built. Inside, Susie grows uncomfortable and attempts to leave; George grabs her and the scene fades until she is seen rushing past her alarmed classmate Ruth Connors, seemingly fleeing Harvey's den.\n\nThe Salmons become worried when Susie fails to return home from school. Her father, Jack, searches for her, while her mother, Abigail, waits for the police. In town, Susie sees Jack, who does not respond to her when she calls. Susie runs home to find Harvey soaking in a bathtub. After seeing the bloody bathroom and her bracelet hanging on the sink faucet, Susie realizes she never escaped the underground den and Harvey murdered her. Screaming, she is pulled into the \"[[Limbo|In-Between]]\", that is neither Heaven nor Earth. From there, Susie watches over her loved ones, and resists her new afterlife friend Holly's urging her to let go.\n\nInvestigating Susie's disappearance with Detective Fenerman, Jack believes Susie was murdered by someone she knew. He researches neighbors and eventually suspects Harvey is the killer. Fenerman is unable to find proof, as Harvey has carefully concealed the evidence. Susie's sister, Lindsey, agrees with Jack's suspicions, but their casework takes a toll on Abigail. Abigail's alcoholic mother, Lynn, moves into the house. Feeling alienated from her husband, Abigail goes to California. Susie, in her afterlife, learns that Harvey, who has targeted Lindsey as his next victim, has murdered six other girls, including Holly, and that he stuffed Susie's body into a large safe in his basement.\n\nOne night, Jack, carrying a baseball bat, trails Harvey into the cornfield. However, Jack accidentally stumbles across a teen couple. The boy, thinking they will be assaulted, nearly bludgeons Jack to death as Harvey watches nearby. As Jack recuperates, Lindsey breaks into Harvey's house looking for evidence that he killed Susie. Upstairs, she finds a notebook containing a sketch of the underground den, a lock of Susie's hair, and news articles about Susie's disappearance. Harvey returns and almost catches Lindsey, but she escapes and rushes home to discover that her mother has returned. She gives the notebook to her grandmother, who contacts the police. Harvey has already fled his home &ndash; taking the safe containing Susie's body with him.\n\nSusie's afterlife begins expanding into a larger heaven, and she is greeted by Harvey's other victims&mdash;now showing nine, including Susie. She resists Holly urging her to enter Heaven along with the others, claiming she has one final thing to do. Meanwhile, Susie's classmates Ruth and Ray are present when Harvey drives up to dispose of the safe at a sinkhole dump site on the Conners' property. Susie returns to Earth and [[Spirit possession|enters Ruth's body]], causing Ruth to faint. Ray rushes to Ruth's aid only to realize she has become Susie. They kiss, completing Susie's last wish, and she returns to Heaven. Meanwhile, Harvey dumps the safe in the sinkhole, leaving it to disappear in the muddy water as he drives away.\n\nSometime later, Harvey meets a young woman outside a diner and offers her a ride, but she rebuffs him and leaves. A large icicle falls from an overhead branch, hitting Harvey's shoulder, causing him to fall backward over a steep cliff to his death. Time passes, and Susie sees that her family is healing, which Susie refers to as \"the lovely bones\" that grew around her absence. Susie finally enters Heaven, telling the audience: \"My name is Salmon, like the fish; first name Susie. I was 14 years old when I was murdered on December 6, 1973. I was here for a moment and then I was gone. I wish you all a long and happy life.\"\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]] as Susie Salmon, the main character and narrator.<ref name=\"weisz\"/> She is a 14-year-old girl who is killed by her neighbor. Ronan was 13 years old at the time of her casting and filming. Ronan and her family were originally reluctant for Ronan to accept the role because of the film's subject matter, but agreed after meeting with Jackson.<ref name=\"latimesronaninterview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-saoirse10-2009dec10,0,4409476.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |date=2009-12-10 |author=Yvonne Villarreal |title=Saoirse Ronan of 'The Lovely Bones' stays on balance |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n** Evelyn Lennon as Susie at age 3\n* [[Stanley Tucci]] as George Harvey, a [[serial killer]] who murders Susie.<ref name=\"tuccicasting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/tuccis-wife-advised-against-the-lovely-bones-role_1126072 |title=TUCCI'S WIFE ADVISED AGAINST THE LOVELY BONES ROLE |date=2009-12-17 |work=ContactMusic.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i9a352772046b5f1303dd04087e2800d2 |author=Gregg Goldstein |title=Tucci cracks DW's 'Bones' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |date=2007-07-23 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204150625/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i9a352772046b5f1303dd04087e2800d2 |archivedate=December 4, 2008 }}</ref> Tucci stated that he had researched his role by watching documentaries and reading books by [[offender profiling|criminal profiler]] [[John E. Douglas]] about catching serial killers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2009/12/03/the-lovely-bones-star-stanley-tucci-puts-a-psycho-on-his-resume/ |title=\"The Lovely Bones\" Star Stanley Tucci Puts a Psycho on His Resume |author=Michelle Kung |work=[[Wall Street Journal|WSJ.com]] |date=2009-12-03 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> Tucci stated that his wife, Kate, had strongly urged him not to accept his role in the film because she felt, after reading the novel, that the subject matter was \"too harrowing.\"<ref name=\"tuccicasting\"/>  \n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as Jack Salmon, Susie's father, who becomes obsessed with his daughter's murder case.<ref name=\"wahl\"/><ref name=\"smhinfo\"/> Wahlberg stated that his role in the film encouraged him to be a more cautious parent with his three children and to talk to them more about \"not talking to strangers.\"<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/> Before Wahlberg's casting, [[Ryan Gosling]] was set to play the role but dropped out of the film in October 2007, one month before filming.<ref name=\"yahoonews\">{{cite web |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6626424/the-lovely-bones-overcomes-rough-start/ |title=The Lovely Bones overcomes rough start |date=2009-12-28 |author=[[Reuters]] |work=[[Yahoo|Au.News.Yahoo.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814232953/http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6626424/the-lovely-bones-overcomes-rough-start |archivedate=August 14, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Gosling had gained weight and grown a beard for the role, but said, \"The age of the character versus my real age [of twenty-six] was always a concern of mine. Peter [Jackson] and I tried to make it work and ultimately it just didn't. I think the film is much better off with Mark Wahlberg in that role.\"<ref name=\"wahl\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117974450.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |title=Wahlberg steps into 'Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-10-21 |author=Michael Fleming, Tatiana Siegel |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN Movies\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/830/830921p1.html |title=Gosling Sets Bones Straight |work=[[IGN|IGN.com]] |date=2007-10-29  |author=Stax |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Gosling later admitted that the real reason for his firing was that he had arrived for filming 60&nbsp;lbs. overweight and sporting a beard, without having discussed the physical change with Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/ryan-gosling-admits-he-was-fired-from-the-lovely-b,48577/|title=Ryan Gosling admits he was fired from The Lovely Bones for being too fat|first=Sean|last=O'Neal|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Rachel Weisz]] as Abigail Salmon, Susie's mother. After Susie's murder, her mother despairs and abandons the family.<ref name=\"smhinfo\"/><ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/> Weisz stated that playing the character and the film and novel's \"uplifting theme\" made her look at life as a \"treasure\" and the film gave her a \"positive feeling\" rather than a \"depressed\" one.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/>\n* [[Susan Sarandon]] as Grandma Lynn, Susie's grandmother.<ref name=\"sarandoncasting2\"/><ref name=\"sarandon\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969278.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |author=Pamela McClintock |title=Sarandon joins 'Lovely Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-07-26 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> Sarandon stated that her character is like a \"comic relief\" and that her character deals with the pain of Susie's death by drinking, smoking and shooting guns.<ref name=\"sarandoncasting2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cinematical.com/2007/11/09/susan-sarandon-talks-about-her-lovely-bones/ |date=2007-11-09 |title=Susan Sarandon Talks About Her 'Lovely Bones' |author=Monika Bartyzel |work=Cinematical.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\"sarandon\"/><ref name=\"theatreinfo\"/>\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Lindsey Salmon, Susie's younger sister. She is the first to suspect that Harvey was involved in Susie's death.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/><ref name=\"othercasting\"/> Jackson cast McIver particularly because she was an unknown actress.<ref name=\"othercasting\"/> Mclver stated that she had read and been a fan of the novel before having been cast in the film.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.about.com/od/thelovelybones/a/lovely-bones-cast-interviews_2.htm |title=Behind the Scenes of 'The Lovely Bones' with Saoirse Ronan |author=Rebecca Murray |work=Movies.About.com |date=2009-12-24 |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as Detective Len Fenerman, the detective in charge of investigating Susie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i307ae22942b238f96219b37d982c253f |author=Borys Kit |title=Imperioli connected to \"Lovely Bones\" |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |date=2007-08-02 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000310/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i307ae22942b238f96219b37d982c253f |archivedate=October 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n* Christian Thomas Ashdale as Buckley Salmon, Susie's younger brother.<ref name=\"smhinfo\">{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones/2009/12/28/1261848638700.html |date=2009-12-26 |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Sandra Hall |work=SMH.au |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Reece Ritchie]] as Ray Singh, Susie's love interest and friend who is strongly affected by Susie's death.<ref name=\"ritchiecasting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2007/10/31/reece_ritchie_lovely_bones_feature.shtml |title=Lowestoft's Lovely Bones |work=[[BBC|BBC.co.uk]] |date=2007-11-02 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Saxton]] as Ronald Drake, one of the murder suspects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.mcall.com/2009-08-13/entertainment/4422961_1_rocks-bristol-bucks-county |date=2009-12-13 |title=Bucks-bred Charlie Saxton rocks in 'Bandslam' |author=Amy Longsdorf |work=Articles.Mcall.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Amanda Michalka|AJ Michalka]] as Clarissa,<ref name=\"michalkacast\"/> Susie's best friend. Michalka was better known as a musician prior to her casting.<ref name=\"michalkacast\">{{cite web |url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2007/09/24/pop-sensation-aj-michalka-cast-in-jacksons-lovely-bones/ |author=Shawn Adler |title=Pop Sensation AJ Michalka Cast In Jackson\u2019s \u2018Lovely Bones\u2019 |work=[[MTV]] |date=2007-09-24 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Carolyn Dando]] as Ruth Connors, a classmate of Susie's.<ref name=\"othercasting\"/><ref name=\"blackmagic\">{{cite news|title=Lindsey and Ruth roles cast for The Lovely Bones |work=Black Magic - NZ Film News |date=2007-08-28 |url=http://www.black-magic.co.nz/home/?p=535 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011214358/http://www.black-magic.co.nz/home/?p=535 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Jackson stated that, after he had searched all over the world for the role, he ultimately chose to cast Dando, a relatively unknown actress, who was working as a waitress before her casting.<ref name=\"othercasting\">{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/413551/1325290 |date=2007-08-28 |title=Jackson chooses Kiwi actresses  |work=TVNZ.co.nz |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Nikki SooHoo]] as Denise \"Holly\" Le Ang, Susie's best friend in Heaven and another of Harvey's victims.\n* [[Jake Abel]] as Brian Nelson\n* [[Tom McCarthy (director)|Thomas McCarthy]] as Principal Caden\n*[[Smiley (2012 film)|Andrew James Allen]]  as Samuel Heckler ,que aparece depois para ser o futuro para de Lindsey. \n\n==Production==\nIn May 2000, [[Film4 Productions]] acquired feature film rights to [[Alice Sebold]]'s novel ''[[The Lovely Bones]]'',<ref name=\"seaside\">{{cite news | author= | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117782048.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=FilmFour makes 'Lovely' buy for Seaside | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2000-05-31 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> when it was a half-written manuscript. Producer Aimee Peyronnet had sought to attract studio interest to the manuscript, and an insider informed Film4's deputy head of production, Jim Wilson, of the project.<ref name=\"remains\">{{cite news | author=Adam Dawtrey | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117874192.html?categoryid=1246&cs=1 | title='Bones' remains at C4 | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2002-10-13 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> The company attached [[Luc Besson]] and Peyronnet's production company Seaside to the project, two years before the novel's release.<ref name=\"seaside\" /> By February 2001, [[Lynne Ramsay]] was hired to direct and write the film adaptation of the novel.<ref>{{cite news | author=Jonathan Bing | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117793307.html?categoryid=1007&cs=1 | title=U.K.'s FilmFour pages quirky fare for pix | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2001-02-07 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>  In July 2002, [[Channel 4#Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel 4]] shut down Film4, causing [[Hollywood]] studios and producers to pursue acquisition of feature film rights to ''The Lovely Bones'', which had spent multiple weeks at the top of the [[New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]]. The film adaptation, which had been estimated at a budget of $15 million, remained with Channel 4 under its newly developed inhouse film unit, with Ramsay still contracted to write and direct. By October 2002, Ramsay was writing the script with fellow screenwriter Liana Dognini, with filming planned for summer 2003.<ref name=\"remains\" /> Author Sebold was invited by the producers to provide input on the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Nicole Panter | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117876022.html?categoryid=1411&cs=1 | title=Bestselling author goes incognito in La La Land | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2002-11-17 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nRamsay, who had read the novel in manuscript prior to publication, said in 2012 that her adaptation departed from it significantly. The scenes with Susie in heaven would have been depicted purely as her father's imagination. He would have become friends with Mr. Harvey, never suspecting him of having killed his daughter. \"I really didn't like the ''[[My Little Pony]]'', she's-in-heaven, everything's-O.K. aspect\", she told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2012.<ref name=\"Ramsay in NYT 2012\">{{cite news|last=Kois|first=Dan|title=Lynne Ramsay Is Back. Finally.|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/lynne-ramsay-is-back-finally/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115070046/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/lynne-ramsay-is-back-finally/|archivedate=January 15, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, the studio DreamWorks negotiated a [[first-look deal]] with producer Peyronnet,<ref>{{cite news | author=Marc Graser |author2=Jonathan Bing  | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117888916.html?categoryid=21&cs=1 | title=D'Works inks 'Bones' key | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2003-07-06 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> after DreamWorks co-founder [[Steven Spielberg]]  expressed interest in the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Nicole Laporte | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117894937.html?categoryid=21&cs=1 | title=Inside Move: Peyronnet digs up lit paydirt | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2003-11-02 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> DreamWorks did not acquire the rights to the novel, and Ramsay was eventually detached from the project as, she says, FilmFour wanted a version more faithful to the novel.<ref name=\"Ramsay in NYT 2012\" /> In April 2004, producers Peter Jackson, [[Fran Walsh]], and [[Philippa Boyens]] entered negotiations to develop the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117903728.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1 | title=Jackson team bones up on 'Lovely' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2004-04-22 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> Jackson described the book as \"a wonderfully emotional and powerful story. Like all the best fantasy, it has a solid grounding in the real world.\"<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite book | author = [[Brian Sibley]] | title = Peter Jackson: A Film-maker's Journey | publisher =Harper Collins | year =2006 | location =London | pages =555\u201357 | isbn = 0-00-717558-2}}</ref> By January 2005, Jackson and Walsh planned to independently purchase film rights and to seek studio financing after a script had been developed. The producers sought to begin adapting a [[spec script]] for ''The Lovely Bones'' in January 2006, with the goal of script completion and budget estimation by the following May.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117916471.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=Putting his own bucks into 'Bones' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2005-01-17 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nJackson explained he enjoyed the novel because he found it \"curiously optimistic\" and uplifting because of the narrator's sense of humor, adding there was a difference between its tone and subject matter. He felt very few films dealt with the loss of a loved one.<ref name=inbetween>{{cite news|author=Scott Bowles|title='Lovely Bones' was lovely to make|work=[[USA Today]]|date=2009-04-19|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2009-04-19-bones-jackson_N.htm|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref> Jackson foresaw the most challenging element in the novel to adapt was the portrayal of Susie, the protagonist, in her heaven, and making it \"ethereal and emotional but not hokey.\"<ref name=\"biography\"/> Saoirse Ronan explained Jackson chose to depict the afterlife as depending on Susie's emotions. \"Whenever Susie feels happy, Heaven is sunny and there's birds and everything. Whenever it\u2019s not so great, it's raining or she\u2019s in the middle of an ocean.\"<ref>{{cite news | author = Silas Lesnick | title = Saoirse Ronan on The Lovely Bones | work = IESB | date = 2008-01-08 | url = http://www.iesb.net/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4073&Itemid=99 | accessdate=2008-01-10}}</ref> Jackson described the book's description of \"heaven\" as being an \"In-Between\" rather than a true heaven and said he was not trying to paint a definitive picture of Heaven itself.<ref name=inbetween/> \"[W]hen Jackson created Susie's heaven, in a 1973 world, he went through the ''[[The Partridge Family|Partridge Family]]'' television show archives as a reference.\"<ref name=\"promtion\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote = \"[I] basically [added] more violence and suffering, [the audience] wanted far more violence [...] They just weren't satisfied [...] We got a lot of people telling us that they were disappointed with this death scene, as they wanted to see [the character] in agony and suffer a lot more, we had to create a whole suffering death scene just to give people the satisfaction they needed.\"\n | source = \u2014Jackson to [[Reuters]] on re-shooting Harvey's death scene, November 2009<ref name=\"reshotdeathscene\"/>\n | width = 235px\n | align = right\n}}\n\nA 120-page draft of the script was written by September 2006.<ref name=\"quint\">{{cite news | author = Eric Vespe | title = Quint and Peter Jackson, Part II: THE LOVELY BONES!!! | publisher = [[Ain't It Cool News]] | date = 2006-09-13 | url = http://www.aintitcool.com/?q=node/30037 | accessdate=2007-06-13}}</ref> In April 2007, the script was completed by Jackson, Walsh and Boyens; Jackson intended  to direct. The three producers began seeking a studio partner to finance the film adaptation. Besides the major studios, smaller companies including [[United Artists]] were also contacted. [[New Line Cinema]] was excluded from negotiations because of Jackson's legal dispute with the studio over royalties from his [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Pamela McClintock | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117964049.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title='Bones' up for bidding | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2007-04-30 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> Jackson sought a beginning $65 million budget for ''The Lovely Bones'', also requesting from studios what kind of promotional commitments and suggestions they would make for the film adaptation.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming |author2=Pamela McClintock  | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117964180.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=High-priced directors pitch projects | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nBy May, four studios remained interested in the project: DreamWorks, [[Warner Bros.]], [[Sony Pictures Entertainment|Sony]], and [[Universal Studios|Universal]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Borys Kit | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i0c726bd1e68cd8aaf73440675df95cb6 | title=Project auctions: One hot, one not | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=2007-05-03 | accessdate=2007-06-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070604175253/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i0c726bd1e68cd8aaf73440675df95cb6 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-04}}</ref> ''The Lovely Bones'' was sold to DreamWorks for $70 million.<ref>{{cite news | author= | url=http://www.variety.com/blog/1400000340/post/740010074.html | title=Jackson Sells, Mann/DiCaprio Doesn't | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-05-29 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Paramount Pictures received the rights to distribute the film worldwide. Production began in October 2007 in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania and New Zealand.<ref name=\"weisz\">{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming, Pamela McClintock |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117966754.html?categoryId=13&cs=1 |title=Weisz to star in 'Lovely Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-06-12 | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news | last = Fleming | first =  Michael| title = Ryan Gosling set for 'Lovely Bones' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-06-27 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967749.html?categoryId=13&cs=1 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Shooting in parts of [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware]], [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester]] and [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery]] counties, including [[Hatfield, Pennsylvania|Hatfield]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Domizio |first=Tony Di |url=http://www.thereporteronline.com/articles/2007/11/02/past%20stories/20053111.txt |title=Hooray for Hatfield |publisher=Thereporteronline.com |date=2007-11-02 |accessdate=2010-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310073033/http://www.thereporteronline.com/articles/2007/11/02/past%20stories/20053111.txt |archivedate=March 10, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Ridley Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Ridley Township]], [[Phoenixville, Pennsylvania|Phoenixville]], [[Royersford, Pennsylvania|Royersford]], [[Malvern, Pennsylvania|Malvern]] and [[East Fallowfield Township, Chester County, Pennsylvania|East Fallowfield]],<ref name=\"East Fallowfield PD press release\">{{cite press release |title=Intermittent Road Closures-Movie Production |publisher=East Fallowfield Township Police Department |date=2007-11-02 |url=http://eastfallowfield.org/cms/images/pdfs/11-2pdpr.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2007-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215163329/http://eastfallowfield.org/cms/images/pdfs/11-2pdpr.pdf |archivedate=December 15, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> lasted a few weeks, and most of the studio shooting was done in New Zealand.<ref name=\"quint\"/>\n\nIn December 2008, [[Brian Eno]] signed on to compose the film's score. Fran Walsh, a big fan of his work, suggested him to Jackson.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tom Cardy|title=Eno signs up to write music for Lovely Bones|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|date=2008-12-20|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/4798626a1860.html|accessdate=2008-12-21}}</ref> Jackson had called Eno to request use of two of his early tracks to evoke atmosphere for the 1970s scenes in the film. When Eno asked if he could compose the whole score, Jackson was surprised, since he had heard Eno did not like working on films. For the film's ending, Eno uncovered a demo he had done in 1973 and reunited with the vocalist to create a proper version for the film, commenting: \"That song from 1973 was finally finished in 2008!\"<ref name=empire>{{cite news|title=News Etc.|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|date=June 2009|pages=26\u201330}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2009, Jackson stated that he re-shot new footage of Harvey's death scene after test audiences said it was not violent enough and wanted to \"see more of Harvey in pain.\"<ref name=\"yahoonews\"/><ref name=\"reshotdeathscene\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/nov/17/peter-jackson-lovely-bones |title=Peter Jackson: Lovely Bones test audience demanded more violence |author=Ben Child |date=2009-11-17 |work=[[Guardian.co.uk]] |accessdate=2009-12-26 |location=London}}</ref> Jackson said it was important to him that the movie receive a [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|PG-13 rating]] so that the film could appeal to the widest possible audience, despite the necessarily violent nature of some scenes.<ref name=\"yahoonews\"/>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Strategy===\n[[File:PeterJacksonCCJuly09.jpg|thumb|left|Jackson at 2009 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con film festival]]. At the festival Jackson discussed ''The Lovely Bones'' and screened a clip from it.]]\n''The Lovely Bones'' was originally scheduled for release<!--in the US? internationally?--> on March 13, 2009, but it was delayed to December 11, 2009, as the studio became interested in releasing the film for \"awards season,\" which gave Jackson an opportunity to make some effects shots larger in scope.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=39450 |title=G.I. Joe, The Lovely Bones Release Dates |work=ComingSoon.net |date=2007-11-19 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film then received a limited theater release on December 11, 2009, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2630&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Princess and the Frog' Leaps to the Top |date=2009-12-14 |author=Brandon Grey |work=[[Box Office Mojo|BoxOfficeMoJo.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film was originally set to have a wider United States theater release on December 25, 2009 ([[Christmas Day]]),<ref name=\"releasedatechange\"/> as part of a campaign to build its momentum into January 2010.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-bones24-2009dec24,0,4575927.story |title=Young women targeted for 'Lovely Bones' marketing push |date=2009-12-24 |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |author=Claudia Eller, Ben Fritz |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref> In early December it was confirmed that the United States release date had been pushed back by three weeks to January 15, 2010.<ref name=\"releasedatechange\"/><ref name=\"jan10release\">{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/12/paramount-nixes-plan-to-expand-the-lovely-bones-for-christmas.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |title=Paramount nixes plan to expand 'The Lovely Bones' for Christmas |author=Ben Fritz, Claudia Eller |date=209-12-23 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Paramount and DreamWorks did not give a reason for the change of the release date.<ref name=\"releasedatechange\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehdroom.com/news/Peter_Jacksons_The_Lovely_Bones_Pushed_to_January/6040 |title=Peter Jackson's The Lovely Bones Pushed to January |date=2009-12-07 |work=TheDRRoom.com |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film premiered in [[New Zealand]] on December 26, 2009, and was released in the United Kingdom on January 29 and in other countries in January 2010.<!--Jan 15? see paragraph 3 of intro-->\n\nAccording to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]],'' Paramount invested $70 million in production and an additional $85 million in worldwide marketing and distribution.<ref name=\"jan10release\"/> In December 2009, the ''Los Angeles Times'' described the marketing and promotion of ''The Lovely Bones'' as having been a \"heavy advertising campaign.\"<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> In late July 2009, as part of the promotion, Jackson talked about the film and screened a 4{{frac|1|2}} minute clip at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] film festival.<ref name=\"promtion\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2009/07/24/comiccon-peter-jackson-lovely-bones-hobbit/|title=Peter Jackson at Comic-Con: 'Hobbit' talk and a peek at 'Lovely Bones'|first=Nicole |last=Sperling|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\nAs part of marketing for the film, in August 2009, people were allowed to enter a contest<!--necessary?  which required registering at Morefm.co.nz,--> to win a trip to [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], for the film's New Zealand [[film premiere|premiere]] on December 14, 2009.<ref name=\"filmcontest1\"/> The offer included, if the winner lived outside of Wellington, one night's accommodation and a [[voucher]] for flight or petrol to Wellington.<ref name=\"filmcontest1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.morefm.co.nz/Portals/0/PDF/TheLovelyBonesPromotionTermsConditionsFINAL.pdf |author=MediaWorks |title=MORE FM \u2018THE LOVELY BONES\u2019 PROMOTION TERMS & CONDITIONS |date=2009-08-04 |work=MoreFM.co.nz |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> A  teaser trailer was released in August 2009, days before the film's official trailer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmstalker.co.uk/archives/2009/08/the_lovely_bones_teaser_footag.html |work=FilmStaker.uk |title=The Lovely Bones teaser footage online |author=Richard Brunton |date=2009-08-04 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> The official trailer debuted on the television series ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' and was released online shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"promtion\"/><ref>ComingSoon.net August 2009.</ref> In August 2009, Jackson offered a \"behind-the-scenes look\" at the film and discussed elements (mainly violence) in the film's plot line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://io9.com/5343938/peter-jackson-explains-how-to-make-murder-beautiful |date=2009-08-24 |title=Peter Jackson Explains How To Make Murder Beautiful |author=Meredith Woerner |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Los Angeles Times'' reported that Paramount had originally expected the film to appeal to a \"sophisticated, adult audience,\" but after poor revenue and average reviews, the studio decided to redirect the film to an audience in another age group.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> Surveys showed that the film was favored more by females aged 13\u201320 than by any other demographic. Paramount began to screen the movie \"aggressively for high school- and college-age girls\" during its three-screen limited release.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/>\n\n===Box office===\nOn December 11, 2009, the film was released on three screens in Los Angeles and New York. As of January 4, 2010, the film had grossed over $389,000 in the US.<ref name=\"bom\"/> Claudia Eller and Ben Fritz of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that it did poorly at the box office in the first few weeks of its release because of average reviews and negative [[Word of mouth|word-of-mouth]].<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> During its opening-weekend release on three screens, it earned over $116,616, an average of estimated $38,872 per-theater revenue.<ref name=\"bom\"/> The film's revenue placed it at thirtieth place on the box office chart.<ref name=\"bom\"/> In the film's second and third weeks of release, the film saw a decrease; in the fourth week, it had a 54.3-percent increase.<ref name=\"filmsboxofficeweekend\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=lovelybones.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo|BoxOfficeMoJo.com]] |title=THE LOVELY BONES (2009): Weekend Box Office Results |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhen put into [[wide release]] on January 15, 2010,<ref name=\"theatreinfo\">{{cite web |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6612462/lovely-bones-is-jacksons-new-territory/ |title=Lovely Bones is Jackson's new territory |author=Paula Bustamante |date=2009-12-22 |work=[[Yahoo|Au.News.Yahoo.com]] |accessdate=December 28, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> it grossed $17,005,133 that weekend, ranking number three at the domestic box office. By the end of its run, ''The Lovely Bones'' had made $44,114,232 domestically, and $49,507,108 overseas, for a worldwide total of $93,621,340.\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released in the US on [[DVD]] and two-disc [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] April 20, 2010 and in the United Kingdom on June 11, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Submitted by Terminal on Fri, 02/19/2010 - 10:18pm. |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36026/the-lovely-bones-dvd-blu-ray-art |title=The Lovely Bones DVD / Blu-ray Art |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=2010-02-19 |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref><!--June 28 UK release? see Talk-->\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nAlthough Ronan and Tucci were praised for their performances, ''The Lovely Bones'' received mixed reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newser.com/story/75915/lovely-bones-hits-and-misses.html |title=Lovely Bones, Hits and Misses. |publisher=Newser.com |date=2009-12-11 |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 32%, based on 243 reviews, with an average rating of 4.98/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"It's stuffed full of Peter Jackson's typically dazzling imagery, but ''The Lovely Bones'' suffers from abrupt shifts between horrific violence and cloying sentimentality.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1189344-lovely_bones/ |title=The Lovely Bones Movie Reviews, Pictures |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes|RottenTomatoes.com]] |accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the film a score of 42 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/lovelybones |title=Lovely Bones, The (2009): Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Ian Freer]] of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave the film 4/5 stars.<ref name=\"empirereview\"/> Freer emphasized the \"bold, daring original filmmaking, with arguably more emotional and intellectual meat to chew on than either the Rings trilogy or [[King Kong (2005 film)|Kong]].\"<ref name=\"empirereview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10800 |author=Ian Freer |title=Review of The Lovely Bones |date=2009-12-12 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Freer noted that, like ''The Lord of the Rings,'' the film \"does a fantastic job with revered, complex source material\" and that, since it is \"as terrific on terra firma as it is audacious in its astral plane\", it is \"doubtful\" that there would be a \"more imaginative\" and \"courageous film\" in 2010.<ref name=\"empirereview\"/>\n\n[[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' wrote that \"through [Peter] Jackson's art\" and Ronan's \"magic\" the \"obscenity of child murder has been invested with immense gravity and grace\" and \"like the story of Susie's life after death, that's a miracle.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1942819_1942818_1942815,00.html#ixzz0ZXSrmAS5 |author=Richard Corliss |title='The Lovely Bones' Review: Dead Girl's Love Story |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 |date=2009-12-10}}</ref> Peter Travers of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' felt that the film was \"conveyed\" in a \"remarkable performance\" by Ronan and described Tucci as being \"magnificent as a man of uncontrollable impulses\" to \"help Jackson cut a path to a humanity that supersedes life and death.\"<ref name=\"rsreview\"/> Travers praised Jackson for building \"jolting suspense.\" Despite praising the film, however, Travers noted that while the book \"never flinched,\" the film does, and while the \"business is being transacted\" by Jackson with a \"Lord of the Rings fantasy\" the film \"attunes himself to a family tragedy.\"<ref name=\"rsreview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/19045705/review/31298547/lovely_bones |date=2009-12-10 |title=Lovely Bones |author=Peter Travers |work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n\nClaudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film 2/4 stars, remarking that while \"[Peter] Jackson gets the thriller scenes right\", the \"conceit of Susie trapped in a [[DayGlo]] world between the one she left and her final resting place, imparting lessons on coping with death, feels preachy.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2009-12-11-lovelybones11_ST_N.htm |author=Claudia Puig |title='The Lovely Bones' breaks between page and screen |work=[[USA Today|USAToday.com]] |date=2009-12-12 |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Puig also described the film as having \"clashing tones\" that veer from \"lightheartedness to heavy-handedness.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Puig also criticized the film's [[computer-generated image]]ry, describing it as being \"cheesy\" and felt that it broke \"no ground.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Kirt Honeycutt, of ''[[the Hollywood Reporter]]'', described the film as telling \"a fundamentally different story\" which is \"one that is not without its tension, humor and compelling details\", but that \"it's also a simpler, more button-pushing tale that misses the joy and heartbreak of the original.\"<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones-film-review-1004048230.story |author=Kirt Honeycutt |date=2009-11-24 |title=The Lovely Bones -- Film Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110062724/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones-film-review-1004048230.story |archivedate=January 10, 2010 }}</ref> Honeycutt also described Jackson as having transformed Sebold's \"startling, unique novel about the aftermath of a terrible murder\" into a story that's more \"focused on crime and punishment.\"<ref name=\"thr\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote = \"[Alice] Sebold's book would've had a tough leap to the multiplex no matter who guided it. But [Peter] Jackson is too enamored with the idea of mixing heaven and the heebie-jeebies, so he's made the skeevy equivalent of a [[Mitch Albom]] book with some pulp fiction pressed between its covers.\"\n | source = '''Joe Neumaier, New York ''Daily News'''''<ref name=\"nydnreview\"/>\n | width = 325px\n | align = left\n}}\n\n[[Stephanie Zacharek]], of ''[[Salon.com]]'', viewed the film as being \"an expensive-looking mess that fails to capture the mood, and the poetry, of its source material\" because \"good actors fighting a poorly conceived script, under the guidance of a director who can no longer make the distinction between imaginativeness and computer-generated effects.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/ent/movies/review/2009/12/10/the_lovely_bones/index.html |title=The Lovely Bones Movie Review |work=[[Salon.com]] |author=Stephanie Zacharek |date=2009-12-10 |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Todd McCarthy, of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', felt that Jackson had undermined the \"solid work from a good cast\" with \"show-offy celestial evocations\" that \"severely disrupt the emotional connections with the characters.\"<ref name=\"varietyreview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941671.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&query=the+lovely+bones |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Todd McCarthy |date=2009-11-24 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> McCarthy stated that he felt that the film, overall, was a \"significant artistic disappointment.\"<ref name=\"varietyreview\"/> Joe Neumaier, of ''[[New York Daily News]]'', described Jackson as having \"siphoned out all the soulfulness\" that made the author's \"combination thriller/afterlife fantasy a best-seller\" and that the film was \"a gumball-colored potboiler that's more squalid than truly mournful.\"<ref name=\"nydnreview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2009/12/11/2009-12-11_the_lovely_bones_.html |date=2009-12-11 |work=[[New York Daily News|NYDailyNews.com]] |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Joe Neumaier |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Neumaier also wrote that the film and Jackson \"wasted\" a \"good cast.\"<ref name=\"nydnreview\"/> [[Roger Ebert]] of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 1.5 stars out of 4, calling it \"deplorable\", and criticizing the apparent message that Susie's murder eventually made her happier. He was also critical of the film's portrayal of Heaven, which he compared to \"a happy gathering of new [[Facebook]] friends\". However, he praised the acting, stating that  \"this whole film is Jackson's fault\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100113/REVIEWS/100119992|date=2010-01-13|title=The Lovely Bones|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[British Board of Film Classification]] (BBFC), the rating given to ''The Lovely Bones'' received 24 objections, more than any other movie in 2010. The BBFC report states, \"Many found the film to be a shocking and upsetting experience. The scene in which young Susie is entrapped by the killer, and the subsequent sequence in which the killer soaks in a bath after the murder, were compared by some complainants to scenes in '18' rated horror films.\" The BBFC rated the movie a 12A, and many complained that the movie was upsetting for a younger audience. Nevertheless, the BBFC defended its rating: \"The Lovely Bones lacked any explicit detail of the murder and any sexual elements were downplayed. The audience\u2019s sympathies remain entirely with the family and the film had many positive messages about life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/14062011/35/most-complained-film-2010-0.html|title=Yahoo Movies UK|website=uk.movies.yahoo.com|accessdate=September 16, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615122837/http://uk.movies.yahoo.com//14062011//35//most-complained-film-2010-0.html|archivedate=June 15, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_13754236\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-13754236 |title=Lovely Bones drew most complaints to UK ratings body |date=June 13, 2011 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/the-lovely-bones-most-complained-about-film/218625|title='The Lovely Bones' most complained about film - NME|date=June 14, 2011|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/jun/14/lovely-bones-most-complaints-bbfc | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ben | last=Child | title=The Lovely Bones attracts most complaints in 2010 | date=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/download/annual-reports/BBFC_AnnualReport_2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813204150/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/download/annual-reports/BBFC_AnnualReport_2010.pdf |archivedate=August 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n|[[7th Irish Film and Television Awards]]\n|Best Leading Actress \n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[63rd British Academy Film Awards]]<ref name=\"baftanoms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/nominations/?year=2009 |title=63RD BRITISH ACADEMY OF FILM AND TELEVISION AWARDS |date=2011-05-22 |author=BAFTA |work=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA.org]] |accessdate=2011-05-22}}</ref>\n|Best Actress in a Leading Role\n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Actor in a Supporting Role\n|rowspan=\"4\"| Stanley Tucci\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[82nd Academy Awards]]\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|-\n|[[67th Golden Globe Awards]]<ref name=\"ggnoms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/159 |title=THE 67TH ANNUAL GOLDEN GLOBE AWARDS NOMINATIONS |date=2009-12-15 |author=HFPA News |work=[[Golden Globes|GoldenGlobes.org]] |accessdate=2009-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215200927/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/159 |archivedate=December 15, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> \n|Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Motion Picture\n|-\n|[[16th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]<ref name=\"sag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/PR_091217 |title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 16th ANNUAL SCREEN ACTORS GUILD AWARDS |date=2009-12-17 |author=Screen Actor Guild Awards |work=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards|SAGAwards.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-17 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| [[36th Saturn Awards]] \n|Best Fantasy Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|Susan Sarandon\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Performance by a Younger Actor\n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Music\n|Brian Eno\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2009|2009 Washington DC Area Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref name=\"imdbawards\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0380510/awards |title=The Lovely Bones : Awards |work=[[IMDb|IMDb.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Art Direction\n|''The Lovely Bones''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards|2009 Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref name=\"imdbawards\"/>\n|rowpsan=\"2\"| Best Actress\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Saoirse Ronan\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Young Actor/Actress\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Art Direction\n|rowspan=\"3\"|''The Lovely Bones''\n|-\n|Best Cinematography\n|-\n|Best Visual Effects\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ghost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lovelybones.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0380510}}\n* {{mojo title|lovelybones}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1189344-lovely_bones}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-lovely-bones}}\n\n{{Peter Jackson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lovely Bones, The}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British crime drama films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Jackson]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Jackson]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Fran Walsh]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Philippa Boyens]]\n[[Category:Fiction narrated by a dead person]]\n[[Category:Films set in heaven]]\n[[Category:Films about grieving]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Films about spirit possession]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n[[Category:WingNut Films films]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2009 film based on Alice Sebold's 2002 novel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Lovely Bones\n| image          = Lovely bones ver2.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Jackson]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Carolynne Cunningham]]\n* [[Fran Walsh]]\n* Peter Jackson\n* Aimee Peyronnet\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Fran Walsh\n* [[Philippa Boyens]]\n* Peter Jackson\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Lovely Bones]]''|[[Alice Sebold]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* [[Rachel Weisz]]\n* [[Susan Sarandon]]\n* [[Stanley Tucci]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]]\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Brian Eno]]\n| cinematography = [[Andrew Lesnie]]\n| editing        = [[Jabez Olssen]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DreamWorks Pictures]]\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[WingNut Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|11|24|Royal premiere|2009|12|11|United States|2009|12|26|New Zealand|2010|01|29|United Kingdom}}<!--WP:FILMRELEASE-->\n| runtime        = 135 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 135:22--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lovely-bones-2010-2 | title=''THE LOVELY BONES'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 24, 2009 | accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n* New Zealand<ref name=\"lumiere\"/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $65 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n| gross          = $93.6 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Lovely Bones''''' is a 2009 [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]] [[thriller film|thriller]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Peter Jackson]], and starring [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Rachel Weisz]], [[Susan Sarandon]], [[Stanley Tucci]], [[Michael Imperioli]], and [[Saoirse Ronan]]. The screenplay by [[Fran Walsh]], [[Philippa Boyens]], and Jackson was based on [[Alice Sebold]]\u2019s award-winning and bestselling [[The Lovely Bones|2002 novel of the same name]]. It follows a girl who is murdered and watches over her family from \"the in-between\", and is torn between seeking vengeance on her killer and allowing her family to heal.\n\nAn international co-production between the United States, the United Kingdom, and New Zealand,<ref name=\"lumiere\">{{cite web|title=Lovely Bones (EN)|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=34455|website=Lumiere|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> the film was produced by [[Carolynne Cunningham]], Walsh, Jackson, and Aimee Peyronnet, with [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tessa Ross]], Ken Kamins, and James Wilson as executive producers. [[Principal photography]] began in October 2007 in [[New Zealand]] and [[Pennsylvania]]. The film's score was composed by [[Brian Eno]].\n\n''The Lovely Bones'' was first released on December 26, 2009 in New Zealand, and then internationally in January 2010. The film's North American release date was changed multiple times, with a limited release on December 11, 2009, and a wider release on January 15, 2010.<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lovelybones.htm |title=THE LOVELY BONES |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> It was released to mainly mixed reviews from critics; the story and its message were generally criticized, with praise mainly aimed at the visual effects, Peter Jackson's direction, and the performances of Ronan and Tucci. In the film's opening weekend, in limited release, it grossed $116,616, despite only having been screened in three theaters, placing it at 30th place on the box office chart.<ref name=\"bom\"/> ''The Lovely Bones'' grossed over $44 million in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lovelybones.htm |title=The Lovely Bones (2009) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> The film also received numerous accolades, with Tucci being nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nIn 1973, 14-year-old high school freshman Susie Salmon dreams of becoming a photographer. One day, Ray, a boy she has a crush on, asks her out. As Susie walks home through a cornfield, she runs into her neighbor, George Harvey, who coaxes her into an underground \"kid's hideout\" he has built. Inside, Susie grows uncomfortable and attempts to leave; George grabs her and the scene fades until she is seen rushing past her alarmed classmate Ruth Connors, seemingly fleeing Harvey's den.\n\nThe Salmons become worried when Susie fails to return home from school. Her father, Jack, searches for her, while her mother, Abigail, waits for the police. In town, Susie sees Jack, who does not respond to her when she calls. Susie runs home to find Harvey soaking in a bathtub. After seeing the bloody bathroom and her bracelet hanging on the sink faucet, Susie realizes she never escaped the underground den and Harvey murdered her. Screaming, she is pulled into the \"[[Limbo|In-Between]]\", that is neither Heaven nor Earth. From there, Susie watches over her loved ones, and resists her new afterlife friend Holly's urging her to let go.\n\nInvestigating Susie's disappearance with Detective Fenerman, Jack believes Susie was murdered by someone she knew. He researches neighbors and eventually suspects Harvey is the killer. Fenerman is unable to find proof, as Harvey has carefully concealed the evidence. Susie's sister, Lindsey, agrees with Jack's suspicions, but their casework takes a toll on Abigail. Abigail's alcoholic mother, Lynn, moves into the house. Feeling alienated from her husband, Abigail goes to California. Susie, in her afterlife, learns that Harvey, who has targeted Lindsey as his next victim, has murdered six other girls, including Holly, and that he stuffed Susie's body into a large safe in his basement.\n\nOne night, Jack, carrying a baseball bat, trails Harvey into the cornfield. However, Jack accidentally stumbles across a teen couple. The boy, thinking they will be assaulted, nearly bludgeons Jack to death as Harvey watches nearby. As Jack recuperates, Lindsey breaks into Harvey's house looking for evidence that he killed Susie. Upstairs, she finds a notebook containing a sketch of the underground den, a lock of Susie's hair, and news articles about Susie's disappearance. Harvey returns and almost catches Lindsey, but she escapes and rushes home to discover that her mother has returned. She gives the notebook to her grandmother, who contacts the police. Harvey has already fled his home &ndash; taking the safe containing Susie's body with him.\n\nSusie's afterlife begins expanding into a larger heaven, and she is greeted by Harvey's other victims&mdash;now showing nine, including Susie. She resists Holly urging her to enter Heaven along with the others, claiming she has one final thing to do. Meanwhile, Susie's classmates Ruth and Ray are present when Harvey drives up to dispose of the safe at a sinkhole dump site on the Conners' property. Susie returns to Earth and [[Spirit possession|enters Ruth's body]], causing Ruth to faint. Ray rushes to Ruth's aid only to realize she has become Susie. They kiss, completing Susie's last wish, and she returns to Heaven. Meanwhile, Harvey dumps the safe in the sinkhole, leaving it to disappear in the muddy water as he drives away.\n\nSometime later, Harvey meets a young woman outside a diner and offers her a ride, but she rebuffs him and leaves. A large icicle falls from an overhead branch, hitting Harvey's shoulder, causing him to fall backward over a steep cliff to his death. Time passes, and Susie sees that her family is healing, which Susie refers to as \"the lovely bones\" that grew around her absence. Susie finally enters Heaven, telling the audience: \"My name is Salmon, like the fish; first name Susie. I was 14 years old when I was murdered on December 6, 1973. I was here for a moment and then I was gone. I wish you all a long and happy life.\"\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]] as Susie Salmon, the main character and narrator.<ref name=\"weisz\"/> She is a 14-year-old girl who is killed by her neighbor. Ronan was 13 years old at the time of her casting and filming. Ronan and her family were originally reluctant for Ronan to accept the role because of the film's subject matter, but agreed after meeting with Jackson.<ref name=\"latimesronaninterview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-saoirse10-2009dec10,0,4409476.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |date=2009-12-10 |author=Yvonne Villarreal |title=Saoirse Ronan of 'The Lovely Bones' stays on balance |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n** Evelyn Lennon as Susie at age 3\n* [[Stanley Tucci]] as George Harvey, a [[serial killer]] who murders Susie.<ref name=\"tuccicasting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/tuccis-wife-advised-against-the-lovely-bones-role_1126072 |title=TUCCI'S WIFE ADVISED AGAINST THE LOVELY BONES ROLE |date=2009-12-17 |work=ContactMusic.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i9a352772046b5f1303dd04087e2800d2 |author=Gregg Goldstein |title=Tucci cracks DW's 'Bones' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |date=2007-07-23 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204150625/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i9a352772046b5f1303dd04087e2800d2 |archivedate=December 4, 2008 }}</ref> Tucci stated that he had researched his role by watching documentaries and reading books by [[offender profiling|criminal profiler]] [[John E. Douglas]] about catching serial killers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2009/12/03/the-lovely-bones-star-stanley-tucci-puts-a-psycho-on-his-resume/ |title=\"The Lovely Bones\" Star Stanley Tucci Puts a Psycho on His Resume |author=Michelle Kung |work=[[Wall Street Journal|WSJ.com]] |date=2009-12-03 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> Tucci stated that his wife, Kate, had strongly urged him not to accept his role in the film because she felt, after reading the novel, that the subject matter was \"too harrowing.\"<ref name=\"tuccicasting\"/>  \n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as Jack Salmon, Susie's father, who becomes obsessed with his daughter's murder case.<ref name=\"wahl\"/><ref name=\"smhinfo\"/> Wahlberg stated that his role in the film encouraged him to be a more cautious parent with his three children and to talk to them more about \"not talking to strangers.\"<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/> Before Wahlberg's casting, [[Ryan Gosling]] was set to play the role but dropped out of the film in October 2007, one month before filming.<ref name=\"yahoonews\">{{cite web |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6626424/the-lovely-bones-overcomes-rough-start/ |title=The Lovely Bones overcomes rough start |date=2009-12-28 |author=[[Reuters]] |work=[[Yahoo|Au.News.Yahoo.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814232953/http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6626424/the-lovely-bones-overcomes-rough-start |archivedate=August 14, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Gosling had gained weight and grown a beard for the role, but said, \"The age of the character versus my real age [of twenty-six] was always a concern of mine. Peter [Jackson] and I tried to make it work and ultimately it just didn't. I think the film is much better off with Mark Wahlberg in that role.\"<ref name=\"wahl\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117974450.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |title=Wahlberg steps into 'Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-10-21 |author=Michael Fleming, Tatiana Siegel |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN Movies\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/830/830921p1.html |title=Gosling Sets Bones Straight |work=[[IGN|IGN.com]] |date=2007-10-29  |author=Stax |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Gosling later admitted that the real reason for his firing was that he had arrived for filming 60&nbsp;lbs. overweight and sporting a beard, without having discussed the physical change with Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/ryan-gosling-admits-he-was-fired-from-the-lovely-b,48577/|title=Ryan Gosling admits he was fired from The Lovely Bones for being too fat|first=Sean|last=O'Neal|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Rachel Weisz]] as Abigail Salmon, Susie's mother. After Susie's murder, her mother despairs and abandons the family.<ref name=\"smhinfo\"/><ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/> Weisz stated that playing the character and the film and novel's \"uplifting theme\" made her look at life as a \"treasure\" and the film gave her a \"positive feeling\" rather than a \"depressed\" one.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/>\n* [[Susan Sarandon]] as Grandma Lynn, Susie's grandmother.<ref name=\"sarandoncasting2\"/><ref name=\"sarandon\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969278.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |author=Pamela McClintock |title=Sarandon joins 'Lovely Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-07-26 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> Sarandon stated that her character is like a \"comic relief\" and that her character deals with the pain of Susie's death by drinking, smoking and shooting guns.<ref name=\"sarandoncasting2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cinematical.com/2007/11/09/susan-sarandon-talks-about-her-lovely-bones/ |date=2007-11-09 |title=Susan Sarandon Talks About Her 'Lovely Bones' |author=Monika Bartyzel |work=Cinematical.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\"sarandon\"/><ref name=\"theatreinfo\"/>\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Lindsey Salmon, Susie's younger sister. She is the first to suspect that Harvey was involved in Susie's death.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\"/><ref name=\"othercasting\"/> Jackson cast McIver particularly because she was an unknown actress.<ref name=\"othercasting\"/> Mclver stated that she had read and been a fan of the novel before having been cast in the film.<ref name=\"about.cominterview\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.about.com/od/thelovelybones/a/lovely-bones-cast-interviews_2.htm |title=Behind the Scenes of 'The Lovely Bones' with Saoirse Ronan |author=Rebecca Murray |work=Movies.About.com |date=2009-12-24 |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as Detective Len Fenerman, the detective in charge of investigating Susie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i307ae22942b238f96219b37d982c253f |author=Borys Kit |title=Imperioli connected to \"Lovely Bones\" |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |date=2007-08-02 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000310/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i307ae22942b238f96219b37d982c253f |archivedate=October 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n* Christian Thomas Ashdale as Buckley Salmon, Susie's younger brother.<ref name=\"smhinfo\">{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones/2009/12/28/1261848638700.html |date=2009-12-26 |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Sandra Hall |work=SMH.au |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Reece Ritchie]] as Ray Singh, Susie's love interest and friend who is strongly affected by Susie's death.<ref name=\"ritchiecasting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2007/10/31/reece_ritchie_lovely_bones_feature.shtml |title=Lowestoft's Lovely Bones |work=[[BBC|BBC.co.uk]] |date=2007-11-02 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Saxton]] as Ronald Drake, one of the murder suspects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.mcall.com/2009-08-13/entertainment/4422961_1_rocks-bristol-bucks-county |date=2009-12-13 |title=Bucks-bred Charlie Saxton rocks in 'Bandslam' |author=Amy Longsdorf |work=Articles.Mcall.com |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Amanda Michalka|AJ Michalka]] as Clarissa,<ref name=\"michalkacast\"/> Susie's best friend. Michalka was better known as a musician prior to her casting.<ref name=\"michalkacast\">{{cite web |url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2007/09/24/pop-sensation-aj-michalka-cast-in-jacksons-lovely-bones/ |author=Shawn Adler |title=Pop Sensation AJ Michalka Cast In Jackson\u2019s \u2018Lovely Bones\u2019 |work=[[MTV]] |date=2007-09-24 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Carolyn Dando]] as Ruth Connors, a classmate of Susie's.<ref name=\"othercasting\"/><ref name=\"blackmagic\">{{cite news|title=Lindsey and Ruth roles cast for The Lovely Bones |work=Black Magic - NZ Film News |date=2007-08-28 |url=http://www.black-magic.co.nz/home/?p=535 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011214358/http://www.black-magic.co.nz/home/?p=535 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Jackson stated that, after he had searched all over the world for the role, he ultimately chose to cast Dando, a relatively unknown actress, who was working as a waitress before her casting.<ref name=\"othercasting\">{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/413551/1325290 |date=2007-08-28 |title=Jackson chooses Kiwi actresses  |work=TVNZ.co.nz |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n* [[Nikki SooHoo]] as Denise \"Holly\" Le Ang, Susie's best friend in Heaven and another of Harvey's victims.\n* [[Jake Abel]] as Brian Nelson\n* [[Tom McCarthy (director)|Thomas McCarthy]] as Principal Caden\n\n==Production==\nIn May 2000, [[Film4 Productions]] acquired feature film rights to [[Alice Sebold]]'s novel ''[[The Lovely Bones]]'',<ref name=\"seaside\">{{cite news | author= | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117782048.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=FilmFour makes 'Lovely' buy for Seaside | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2000-05-31 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> when it was a half-written manuscript. Producer Aimee Peyronnet had sought to attract studio interest to the manuscript, and an insider informed Film4's deputy head of production, Jim Wilson, of the project.<ref name=\"remains\">{{cite news | author=Adam Dawtrey | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117874192.html?categoryid=1246&cs=1 | title='Bones' remains at C4 | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2002-10-13 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> The company attached [[Luc Besson]] and Peyronnet's production company Seaside to the project, two years before the novel's release.<ref name=\"seaside\" /> By February 2001, [[Lynne Ramsay]] was hired to direct and write the film adaptation of the novel.<ref>{{cite news | author=Jonathan Bing | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117793307.html?categoryid=1007&cs=1 | title=U.K.'s FilmFour pages quirky fare for pix | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2001-02-07 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>  In July 2002, [[Channel 4#Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel 4]] shut down Film4, causing [[Hollywood]] studios and producers to pursue acquisition of feature film rights to ''The Lovely Bones'', which had spent multiple weeks at the top of the [[New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]]. The film adaptation, which had been estimated at a budget of $15 million, remained with Channel 4 under its newly developed inhouse film unit, with Ramsay still contracted to write and direct. By October 2002, Ramsay was writing the script with fellow screenwriter Liana Dognini, with filming planned for summer 2003.<ref name=\"remains\" /> Author Sebold was invited by the producers to provide input on the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Nicole Panter | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117876022.html?categoryid=1411&cs=1 | title=Bestselling author goes incognito in La La Land | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2002-11-17 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nRamsay, who had read the novel in manuscript prior to publication, said in 2012 that her adaptation departed from it significantly. The scenes with Susie in heaven would have been depicted purely as her father's imagination. He would have become friends with Mr. Harvey, never suspecting him of having killed his daughter. \"I really didn't like the ''[[My Little Pony]]'', she's-in-heaven, everything's-O.K. aspect\", she told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2012.<ref name=\"Ramsay in NYT 2012\">{{cite news|last=Kois|first=Dan|title=Lynne Ramsay Is Back. Finally.|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/lynne-ramsay-is-back-finally/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115070046/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/lynne-ramsay-is-back-finally/|archivedate=January 15, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, the studio DreamWorks negotiated a [[first-look deal]] with producer Peyronnet,<ref>{{cite news | author=Marc Graser |author2=Jonathan Bing  | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117888916.html?categoryid=21&cs=1 | title=D'Works inks 'Bones' key | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2003-07-06 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> after DreamWorks co-founder [[Steven Spielberg]]  expressed interest in the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Nicole Laporte | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117894937.html?categoryid=21&cs=1 | title=Inside Move: Peyronnet digs up lit paydirt | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2003-11-02 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> DreamWorks did not acquire the rights to the novel, and Ramsay was eventually detached from the project as, she says, FilmFour wanted a version more faithful to the novel.<ref name=\"Ramsay in NYT 2012\" /> In April 2004, producers Peter Jackson, [[Fran Walsh]], and [[Philippa Boyens]] entered negotiations to develop the project.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117903728.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1 | title=Jackson team bones up on 'Lovely' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2004-04-22 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> Jackson described the book as \"a wonderfully emotional and powerful story. Like all the best fantasy, it has a solid grounding in the real world.\"<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite book | author = [[Brian Sibley]] | title = Peter Jackson: A Film-maker's Journey | publisher =Harper Collins | year =2006 | location =London | pages =555\u201357 | isbn = 0-00-717558-2}}</ref> By January 2005, Jackson and Walsh planned to independently purchase film rights and to seek studio financing after a script had been developed. The producers sought to begin adapting a [[spec script]] for ''The Lovely Bones'' in January 2006, with the goal of script completion and budget estimation by the following May.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117916471.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=Putting his own bucks into 'Bones' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2005-01-17 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nJackson explained he enjoyed the novel because he found it \"curiously optimistic\" and uplifting because of the narrator's sense of humor, adding there was a difference between its tone and subject matter. He felt very few films dealt with the loss of a loved one.<ref name=inbetween>{{cite news|author=Scott Bowles|title='Lovely Bones' was lovely to make|work=[[USA Today]]|date=2009-04-19|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2009-04-19-bones-jackson_N.htm|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref> Jackson foresaw the most challenging element in the novel to adapt was the portrayal of Susie, the protagonist, in her heaven, and making it \"ethereal and emotional but not hokey.\"<ref name=\"biography\"/> Saoirse Ronan explained Jackson chose to depict the afterlife as depending on Susie's emotions. \"Whenever Susie feels happy, Heaven is sunny and there's birds and everything. Whenever it\u2019s not so great, it's raining or she\u2019s in the middle of an ocean.\"<ref>{{cite news | author = Silas Lesnick | title = Saoirse Ronan on The Lovely Bones | work = IESB | date = 2008-01-08 | url = http://www.iesb.net/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4073&Itemid=99 | accessdate=2008-01-10}}</ref> Jackson described the book's description of \"heaven\" as being an \"In-Between\" rather than a true heaven and said he was not trying to paint a definitive picture of Heaven itself.<ref name=inbetween/> \"[W]hen Jackson created Susie's heaven, in a 1973 world, he went through the ''[[The Partridge Family|Partridge Family]]'' television show archives as a reference.\"<ref name=\"promtion\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote = \"[I] basically [added] more violence and suffering, [the audience] wanted far more violence [...] They just weren't satisfied [...] We got a lot of people telling us that they were disappointed with this death scene, as they wanted to see [the character] in agony and suffer a lot more, we had to create a whole suffering death scene just to give people the satisfaction they needed.\"\n | source = \u2014Jackson to [[Reuters]] on re-shooting Harvey's death scene, November 2009<ref name=\"reshotdeathscene\"/>\n | width = 235px\n | align = right\n}}\n\nA 120-page draft of the script was written by September 2006.<ref name=\"quint\">{{cite news | author = Eric Vespe | title = Quint and Peter Jackson, Part II: THE LOVELY BONES!!! | publisher = [[Ain't It Cool News]] | date = 2006-09-13 | url = http://www.aintitcool.com/?q=node/30037 | accessdate=2007-06-13}}</ref> In April 2007, the script was completed by Jackson, Walsh and Boyens; Jackson intended  to direct. The three producers began seeking a studio partner to finance the film adaptation. Besides the major studios, smaller companies including [[United Artists]] were also contacted. [[New Line Cinema]] was excluded from negotiations because of Jackson's legal dispute with the studio over royalties from his [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Pamela McClintock | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117964049.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title='Bones' up for bidding | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2007-04-30 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref> Jackson sought a beginning $65 million budget for ''The Lovely Bones'', also requesting from studios what kind of promotional commitments and suggestions they would make for the film adaptation.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming |author2=Pamela McClintock  | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117964180.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title=High-priced directors pitch projects | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2007-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nBy May, four studios remained interested in the project: DreamWorks, [[Warner Bros.]], [[Sony Pictures Entertainment|Sony]], and [[Universal Studios|Universal]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Borys Kit | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i0c726bd1e68cd8aaf73440675df95cb6 | title=Project auctions: One hot, one not | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=2007-05-03 | accessdate=2007-06-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070604175253/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i0c726bd1e68cd8aaf73440675df95cb6 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-04}}</ref> ''The Lovely Bones'' was sold to DreamWorks for $70 million.<ref>{{cite news | author= | url=http://www.variety.com/blog/1400000340/post/740010074.html | title=Jackson Sells, Mann/DiCaprio Doesn't | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-05-29 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Paramount Pictures received the rights to distribute the film worldwide. Production began in October 2007 in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania and New Zealand.<ref name=\"weisz\">{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming, Pamela McClintock |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117966754.html?categoryId=13&cs=1 |title=Weisz to star in 'Lovely Bones' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-06-12 | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news | last = Fleming | first =  Michael| title = Ryan Gosling set for 'Lovely Bones' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |date=2007-06-27 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967749.html?categoryId=13&cs=1 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Shooting in parts of [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware]], [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester]] and [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery]] counties, including [[Hatfield, Pennsylvania|Hatfield]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Domizio |first=Tony Di |url=http://www.thereporteronline.com/articles/2007/11/02/past%20stories/20053111.txt |title=Hooray for Hatfield |publisher=Thereporteronline.com |date=2007-11-02 |accessdate=2010-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310073033/http://www.thereporteronline.com/articles/2007/11/02/past%20stories/20053111.txt |archivedate=March 10, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Ridley Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Ridley Township]], [[Phoenixville, Pennsylvania|Phoenixville]], [[Royersford, Pennsylvania|Royersford]], [[Malvern, Pennsylvania|Malvern]] and [[East Fallowfield Township, Chester County, Pennsylvania|East Fallowfield]],<ref name=\"East Fallowfield PD press release\">{{cite press release |title=Intermittent Road Closures-Movie Production |publisher=East Fallowfield Township Police Department |date=2007-11-02 |url=http://eastfallowfield.org/cms/images/pdfs/11-2pdpr.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2007-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215163329/http://eastfallowfield.org/cms/images/pdfs/11-2pdpr.pdf |archivedate=December 15, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> lasted a few weeks, and most of the studio shooting was done in New Zealand.<ref name=\"quint\"/>\n\nIn December 2008, [[Brian Eno]] signed on to compose the film's score. Fran Walsh, a big fan of his work, suggested him to Jackson.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tom Cardy|title=Eno signs up to write music for Lovely Bones|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|date=2008-12-20|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/4798626a1860.html|accessdate=2008-12-21}}</ref> Jackson had called Eno to request use of two of his early tracks to evoke atmosphere for the 1970s scenes in the film. When Eno asked if he could compose the whole score, Jackson was surprised, since he had heard Eno did not like working on films. For the film's ending, Eno uncovered a demo he had done in 1973 and reunited with the vocalist to create a proper version for the film, commenting: \"That song from 1973 was finally finished in 2008!\"<ref name=empire>{{cite news|title=News Etc.|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|date=June 2009|pages=26\u201330}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2009, Jackson stated that he re-shot new footage of Harvey's death scene after test audiences said it was not violent enough and wanted to \"see more of Harvey in pain.\"<ref name=\"yahoonews\"/><ref name=\"reshotdeathscene\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/nov/17/peter-jackson-lovely-bones |title=Peter Jackson: Lovely Bones test audience demanded more violence |author=Ben Child |date=2009-11-17 |work=[[Guardian.co.uk]] |accessdate=2009-12-26 |location=London}}</ref> Jackson said it was important to him that the movie receive a [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|PG-13 rating]] so that the film could appeal to the widest possible audience, despite the necessarily violent nature of some scenes.<ref name=\"yahoonews\"/>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Strategy===\n[[File:PeterJacksonCCJuly09.jpg|thumb|left|Jackson at 2009 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con film festival]]. At the festival Jackson discussed ''The Lovely Bones'' and screened a clip from it.]]\n''The Lovely Bones'' was originally scheduled for release<!--in the US? internationally?--> on March 13, 2009, but it was delayed to December 11, 2009, as the studio became interested in releasing the film for \"awards season,\" which gave Jackson an opportunity to make some effects shots larger in scope.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=39450 |title=G.I. Joe, The Lovely Bones Release Dates |work=ComingSoon.net |date=2007-11-19 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film then received a limited theater release on December 11, 2009, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2630&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Princess and the Frog' Leaps to the Top |date=2009-12-14 |author=Brandon Grey |work=[[Box Office Mojo|BoxOfficeMoJo.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film was originally set to have a wider United States theater release on December 25, 2009 ([[Christmas Day]]),<ref name=\"releasedatechange\"/> as part of a campaign to build its momentum into January 2010.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-bones24-2009dec24,0,4575927.story |title=Young women targeted for 'Lovely Bones' marketing push |date=2009-12-24 |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |author=Claudia Eller, Ben Fritz |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref> In early December it was confirmed that the United States release date had been pushed back by three weeks to January 15, 2010.<ref name=\"releasedatechange\"/><ref name=\"jan10release\">{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/12/paramount-nixes-plan-to-expand-the-lovely-bones-for-christmas.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times|LATimes.com]] |title=Paramount nixes plan to expand 'The Lovely Bones' for Christmas |author=Ben Fritz, Claudia Eller |date=209-12-23 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Paramount and DreamWorks did not give a reason for the change of the release date.<ref name=\"releasedatechange\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehdroom.com/news/Peter_Jacksons_The_Lovely_Bones_Pushed_to_January/6040 |title=Peter Jackson's The Lovely Bones Pushed to January |date=2009-12-07 |work=TheDRRoom.com |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The film premiered in [[New Zealand]] on December 26, 2009, and was released in the United Kingdom on January 29 and in other countries in January 2010.<!--Jan 15? see paragraph 3 of intro-->\n\nAccording to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]],'' Paramount invested $70 million in production and an additional $85 million in worldwide marketing and distribution.<ref name=\"jan10release\"/> In December 2009, the ''Los Angeles Times'' described the marketing and promotion of ''The Lovely Bones'' as having been a \"heavy advertising campaign.\"<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> In late July 2009, as part of the promotion, Jackson talked about the film and screened a 4{{frac|1|2}} minute clip at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] film festival.<ref name=\"promtion\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2009/07/24/comiccon-peter-jackson-lovely-bones-hobbit/|title=Peter Jackson at Comic-Con: 'Hobbit' talk and a peek at 'Lovely Bones'|first=Nicole |last=Sperling|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\nAs part of marketing for the film, in August 2009, people were allowed to enter a contest<!--necessary?  which required registering at Morefm.co.nz,--> to win a trip to [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], for the film's New Zealand [[film premiere|premiere]] on December 14, 2009.<ref name=\"filmcontest1\"/> The offer included, if the winner lived outside of Wellington, one night's accommodation and a [[voucher]] for flight or petrol to Wellington.<ref name=\"filmcontest1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.morefm.co.nz/Portals/0/PDF/TheLovelyBonesPromotionTermsConditionsFINAL.pdf |author=MediaWorks |title=MORE FM \u2018THE LOVELY BONES\u2019 PROMOTION TERMS & CONDITIONS |date=2009-08-04 |work=MoreFM.co.nz |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> A  teaser trailer was released in August 2009, days before the film's official trailer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmstalker.co.uk/archives/2009/08/the_lovely_bones_teaser_footag.html |work=FilmStaker.uk |title=The Lovely Bones teaser footage online |author=Richard Brunton |date=2009-08-04 |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> The official trailer debuted on the television series ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' and was released online shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"promtion\"/><ref>ComingSoon.net August 2009.</ref> In August 2009, Jackson offered a \"behind-the-scenes look\" at the film and discussed elements (mainly violence) in the film's plot line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://io9.com/5343938/peter-jackson-explains-how-to-make-murder-beautiful |date=2009-08-24 |title=Peter Jackson Explains How To Make Murder Beautiful |author=Meredith Woerner |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Los Angeles Times'' reported that Paramount had originally expected the film to appeal to a \"sophisticated, adult audience,\" but after poor revenue and average reviews, the studio decided to redirect the film to an audience in another age group.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> Surveys showed that the film was favored more by females aged 13\u201320 than by any other demographic. Paramount began to screen the movie \"aggressively for high school- and college-age girls\" during its three-screen limited release.<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/>\n\n===Box office===\nOn December 11, 2009, the film was released on three screens in Los Angeles and New York. As of January 4, 2010, the film had grossed over $389,000 in the US.<ref name=\"bom\"/> Claudia Eller and Ben Fritz of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that it did poorly at the box office in the first few weeks of its release because of average reviews and negative [[Word of mouth|word-of-mouth]].<ref name=\"latimespromtion\"/> During its opening-weekend release on three screens, it earned over $116,616, an average of estimated $38,872 per-theater revenue.<ref name=\"bom\"/> The film's revenue placed it at thirtieth place on the box office chart.<ref name=\"bom\"/> In the film's second and third weeks of release, the film saw a decrease; in the fourth week, it had a 54.3-percent increase.<ref name=\"filmsboxofficeweekend\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=lovelybones.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo|BoxOfficeMoJo.com]] |title=THE LOVELY BONES (2009): Weekend Box Office Results |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhen put into [[wide release]] on January 15, 2010,<ref name=\"theatreinfo\">{{cite web |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/entertainment/6612462/lovely-bones-is-jacksons-new-territory/ |title=Lovely Bones is Jackson's new territory |author=Paula Bustamante |date=2009-12-22 |work=[[Yahoo|Au.News.Yahoo.com]] |accessdate=December 28, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> it grossed $17,005,133 that weekend, ranking number three at the domestic box office. By the end of its run, ''The Lovely Bones'' had made $44,114,232 domestically, and $49,507,108 overseas, for a worldwide total of $93,621,340.\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released in the US on [[DVD]] and two-disc [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] April 20, 2010 and in the United Kingdom on June 11, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Submitted by Terminal on Fri, 02/19/2010 - 10:18pm. |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36026/the-lovely-bones-dvd-blu-ray-art |title=The Lovely Bones DVD / Blu-ray Art |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=2010-02-19 |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref><!--June 28 UK release? see Talk-->\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nAlthough Ronan and Tucci were praised for their performances, ''The Lovely Bones'' received mixed reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newser.com/story/75915/lovely-bones-hits-and-misses.html |title=Lovely Bones, Hits and Misses. |publisher=Newser.com |date=2009-12-11 |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 32%, based on 243 reviews, with an average rating of 4.98/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"It's stuffed full of Peter Jackson's typically dazzling imagery, but ''The Lovely Bones'' suffers from abrupt shifts between horrific violence and cloying sentimentality.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1189344-lovely_bones/ |title=The Lovely Bones Movie Reviews, Pictures |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes|RottenTomatoes.com]] |accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the film a score of 42 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/lovelybones |title=Lovely Bones, The (2009): Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Ian Freer]] of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave the film 4/5 stars.<ref name=\"empirereview\"/> Freer emphasized the \"bold, daring original filmmaking, with arguably more emotional and intellectual meat to chew on than either the Rings trilogy or [[King Kong (2005 film)|Kong]].\"<ref name=\"empirereview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10800 |author=Ian Freer |title=Review of The Lovely Bones |date=2009-12-12 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Freer noted that, like ''The Lord of the Rings,'' the film \"does a fantastic job with revered, complex source material\" and that, since it is \"as terrific on terra firma as it is audacious in its astral plane\", it is \"doubtful\" that there would be a \"more imaginative\" and \"courageous film\" in 2010.<ref name=\"empirereview\"/>\n\n[[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' wrote that \"through [Peter] Jackson's art\" and Ronan's \"magic\" the \"obscenity of child murder has been invested with immense gravity and grace\" and \"like the story of Susie's life after death, that's a miracle.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1942819_1942818_1942815,00.html#ixzz0ZXSrmAS5 |author=Richard Corliss |title='The Lovely Bones' Review: Dead Girl's Love Story |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 |date=2009-12-10}}</ref> Peter Travers of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' felt that the film was \"conveyed\" in a \"remarkable performance\" by Ronan and described Tucci as being \"magnificent as a man of uncontrollable impulses\" to \"help Jackson cut a path to a humanity that supersedes life and death.\"<ref name=\"rsreview\"/> Travers praised Jackson for building \"jolting suspense.\" Despite praising the film, however, Travers noted that while the book \"never flinched,\" the film does, and while the \"business is being transacted\" by Jackson with a \"Lord of the Rings fantasy\" the film \"attunes himself to a family tragedy.\"<ref name=\"rsreview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/19045705/review/31298547/lovely_bones |date=2009-12-10 |title=Lovely Bones |author=Peter Travers |work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n\nClaudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film 2/4 stars, remarking that while \"[Peter] Jackson gets the thriller scenes right\", the \"conceit of Susie trapped in a [[DayGlo]] world between the one she left and her final resting place, imparting lessons on coping with death, feels preachy.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2009-12-11-lovelybones11_ST_N.htm |author=Claudia Puig |title='The Lovely Bones' breaks between page and screen |work=[[USA Today|USAToday.com]] |date=2009-12-12 |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Puig also described the film as having \"clashing tones\" that veer from \"lightheartedness to heavy-handedness.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Puig also criticized the film's [[computer-generated image]]ry, describing it as being \"cheesy\" and felt that it broke \"no ground.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Kirt Honeycutt, of ''[[the Hollywood Reporter]]'', described the film as telling \"a fundamentally different story\" which is \"one that is not without its tension, humor and compelling details\", but that \"it's also a simpler, more button-pushing tale that misses the joy and heartbreak of the original.\"<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones-film-review-1004048230.story |author=Kirt Honeycutt |date=2009-11-24 |title=The Lovely Bones -- Film Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter|TheHollywoodReporter.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110062724/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film-reviews/the-lovely-bones-film-review-1004048230.story |archivedate=January 10, 2010 }}</ref> Honeycutt also described Jackson as having transformed Sebold's \"startling, unique novel about the aftermath of a terrible murder\" into a story that's more \"focused on crime and punishment.\"<ref name=\"thr\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote = \"[Alice] Sebold's book would've had a tough leap to the multiplex no matter who guided it. But [Peter] Jackson is too enamored with the idea of mixing heaven and the heebie-jeebies, so he's made the skeevy equivalent of a [[Mitch Albom]] book with some pulp fiction pressed between its covers.\"\n | source = '''Joe Neumaier, New York ''Daily News'''''<ref name=\"nydnreview\"/>\n | width = 325px\n | align = left\n}}\n\n[[Stephanie Zacharek]], of ''[[Salon.com]]'', viewed the film as being \"an expensive-looking mess that fails to capture the mood, and the poetry, of its source material\" because \"good actors fighting a poorly conceived script, under the guidance of a director who can no longer make the distinction between imaginativeness and computer-generated effects.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/ent/movies/review/2009/12/10/the_lovely_bones/index.html |title=The Lovely Bones Movie Review |work=[[Salon.com]] |author=Stephanie Zacharek |date=2009-12-10 |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Todd McCarthy, of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', felt that Jackson had undermined the \"solid work from a good cast\" with \"show-offy celestial evocations\" that \"severely disrupt the emotional connections with the characters.\"<ref name=\"varietyreview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941671.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&query=the+lovely+bones |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Todd McCarthy |date=2009-11-24 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> McCarthy stated that he felt that the film, overall, was a \"significant artistic disappointment.\"<ref name=\"varietyreview\"/> Joe Neumaier, of ''[[New York Daily News]]'', described Jackson as having \"siphoned out all the soulfulness\" that made the author's \"combination thriller/afterlife fantasy a best-seller\" and that the film was \"a gumball-colored potboiler that's more squalid than truly mournful.\"<ref name=\"nydnreview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2009/12/11/2009-12-11_the_lovely_bones_.html |date=2009-12-11 |work=[[New York Daily News|NYDailyNews.com]] |title=The Lovely Bones |author=Joe Neumaier |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Neumaier also wrote that the film and Jackson \"wasted\" a \"good cast.\"<ref name=\"nydnreview\"/> [[Roger Ebert]] of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 1.5 stars out of 4, calling it \"deplorable\", and criticizing the apparent message that Susie's murder eventually made her happier. He was also critical of the film's portrayal of Heaven, which he compared to \"a happy gathering of new [[Facebook]] friends\". However, he praised the acting, stating that  \"this whole film is Jackson's fault\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100113/REVIEWS/100119992|date=2010-01-13|title=The Lovely Bones|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[British Board of Film Classification]] (BBFC), the rating given to ''The Lovely Bones'' received 24 objections, more than any other movie in 2010. The BBFC report states, \"Many found the film to be a shocking and upsetting experience. The scene in which young Susie is entrapped by the killer, and the subsequent sequence in which the killer soaks in a bath after the murder, were compared by some complainants to scenes in '18' rated horror films.\" The BBFC rated the movie a 12A, and many complained that the movie was upsetting for a younger audience. Nevertheless, the BBFC defended its rating: \"The Lovely Bones lacked any explicit detail of the murder and any sexual elements were downplayed. The audience\u2019s sympathies remain entirely with the family and the film had many positive messages about life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/14062011/35/most-complained-film-2010-0.html|title=Yahoo Movies UK|website=uk.movies.yahoo.com|accessdate=September 16, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615122837/http://uk.movies.yahoo.com//14062011//35//most-complained-film-2010-0.html|archivedate=June 15, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_13754236\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-13754236 |title=Lovely Bones drew most complaints to UK ratings body |date=June 13, 2011 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/the-lovely-bones-most-complained-about-film/218625|title='The Lovely Bones' most complained about film - NME|date=June 14, 2011|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/jun/14/lovely-bones-most-complaints-bbfc | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ben | last=Child | title=The Lovely Bones attracts most complaints in 2010 | date=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/download/annual-reports/BBFC_AnnualReport_2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813204150/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/download/annual-reports/BBFC_AnnualReport_2010.pdf |archivedate=August 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n|[[7th Irish Film and Television Awards]]\n|Best Leading Actress \n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[63rd British Academy Film Awards]]<ref name=\"baftanoms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/nominations/?year=2009 |title=63RD BRITISH ACADEMY OF FILM AND TELEVISION AWARDS |date=2011-05-22 |author=BAFTA |work=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA.org]] |accessdate=2011-05-22}}</ref>\n|Best Actress in a Leading Role\n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Actor in a Supporting Role\n|rowspan=\"4\"| Stanley Tucci\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[82nd Academy Awards]]\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|-\n|[[67th Golden Globe Awards]]<ref name=\"ggnoms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/159 |title=THE 67TH ANNUAL GOLDEN GLOBE AWARDS NOMINATIONS |date=2009-12-15 |author=HFPA News |work=[[Golden Globes|GoldenGlobes.org]] |accessdate=2009-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215200927/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/159 |archivedate=December 15, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> \n|Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Motion Picture\n|-\n|[[16th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]<ref name=\"sag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/PR_091217 |title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 16th ANNUAL SCREEN ACTORS GUILD AWARDS |date=2009-12-17 |author=Screen Actor Guild Awards |work=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards|SAGAwards.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-17 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| [[36th Saturn Awards]] \n|Best Fantasy Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|Susan Sarandon\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Performance by a Younger Actor\n|Saoirse Ronan\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Music\n|Brian Eno\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2009|2009 Washington DC Area Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref name=\"imdbawards\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0380510/awards |title=The Lovely Bones : Awards |work=[[IMDb|IMDb.com]] |accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref>\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Art Direction\n|''The Lovely Bones''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards|2009 Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref name=\"imdbawards\"/>\n|rowpsan=\"2\"| Best Actress\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Saoirse Ronan\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Young Actor/Actress\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|Stanley Tucci\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Art Direction\n|rowspan=\"3\"|''The Lovely Bones''\n|-\n|Best Cinematography\n|-\n|Best Visual Effects\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ghost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lovelybones.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0380510}}\n* {{mojo title|lovelybones}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1189344-lovely_bones}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-lovely-bones}}\n\n{{Peter Jackson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lovely Bones, The}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British crime drama films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Jackson]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Jackson]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Fran Walsh]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Philippa Boyens]]\n[[Category:Fiction narrated by a dead person]]\n[[Category:Films set in heaven]]\n[[Category:Films about grieving]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Films about spirit possession]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n[[Category:WingNut Films films]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Kelly bublao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ator", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lovely_Bones_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Non-governmental organization", "text_new": "{{redirect|NGO}}\n{{short description|Organization independent of any government}}\n{{copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Pekka Haavisto - World NGO Day, Finland.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3| H.E. [[Pekka Haavisto]], Minister for International Development of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs in Finland]] at the first [[World NGO Day]], [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] in 2014]]\n[[File:Europe in a suitcase - UK.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[George Melashvili]], the head of the EGI, addresses the audience at the launch of the project \"''Europe in a Suitcase''\" implemented in cooperation of two NGOs - the [[Europe-Georgia Institute]] and the [[Friedrich Naumann Foundation]] aiming to increase cooperation between European politicians, journalists and representatives of civic sector and academia with their counterparts in [[Georgia (Country)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"egisutcase\">[https://egi.ge/en/archives/5187 Europe in a suitcase: Oliver Wardrop Discussions]</ref>.]]\n[[File:14-08-10-wikimania-gruppenfoto-01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|The group photo at Wikimania 2014 London. [[Wikimania]] is the official annual conference of the [[Wikimedia Foundation]], an [[United States|American]] non-profit and [[charitable organization]] headquartered in [[San Francisco]], [[California]],<ref name=\"Hanson2016\">{{cite book|author=Jarice Hanson|title=The Social Media Revolution: An Economic Encyclopedia of Friending, Following, Texting, and Connecting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ePEZDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA375|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-768-2|page=375}}</ref>  mostly known for participating in the [[Wikimedia movement]]. It owns the internet domain names of most movement projects and hosts sites like [[Wikipedia]].  ]]\n\n[[Organizations]] that are independent of any government's involvement<ref name=\":3\">{{citation|title=NGO|url=http://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/american/ngo|dictionary=Macmillan Dictionary}}</ref> are called '''Non-governmental organizations.''' These organizations are also known as '''NGOs''',<ref name=\":0\">The term ''NGO'' is so common and its expansion so rare that all dictionaries have an entry for the abbreviation, but many do not have one for the expansion, or they even explain it by using the abbreviation, e.g. [https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/nongovernmental-organization Collins English Dictionary]</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Claiborne|first1=N|year=2004|title=Presence of social workers in nongovernment organizations|journal=Soc Work|volume=49|issue=2|pages=207\u2013218|doi=10.1093/sw/49.2.207|pmid=15124961}}</ref> or '''non-government organizations.'''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Horowitz|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/world/europe/migrant-ship-monitor-mediterranean.html|title=Ship Monitoring Rescues of Migrants Refuses to Be Rescued|date=2017-08-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> NGOs are usually [[Nonprofit organization|non-profitable.]]<ref name=\":4\">Because many of the most famous NGOs are [[INGOs|International non-governmental organization]], many people believe NGOs are by definition international, but that is not the way the term is interpreted by NGOs, the media, governments, or international governmental organizations.\n(See the sources at the end of this sentence.)</ref> Many of them are active in the areas of humanitarian or social sciences. However, NGOs can also be [[lobby groups]] for corporations, such as the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usip.org/glossary/nongovernmental-organization-ngo|title=Nongovernmental Organization (NGO)|website=United States Institute of Peace}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Karns|series=|quote=|pages=|doi=|oclc=|isbn=|id=|location=|volume=|year=|first=Margaret P.|date=|edition=|language=|access-date=|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/nongovernmental-organization|title=Nongovernmental organization|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica|editor-first=|editor-last=|ref=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/ngo|title=NGO - meaning in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Oxford Dictionaries|NGO}}</ref>\n\nNGOs are a subgroup of all organizations founded by citizens, which include clubs and other [[club (organization)|associations]] that provide services, benefits, and premises only to members{{dubious |reason=NGO's usually give aid to other outsiders|date=February 2020}}. Sometimes the term is used as a synonym of \"[[civil society organization]]\" to refer to any association founded by citizens,<ref name=\"usstate\">\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20170122211029/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/fs/2017/266904.htm Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) in the United States]\" (fact sheet). January 20, 2017. Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor. U.S. Department of State. state.gov. Retrieved 2017-09-21.</ref> but this is not how the term is normally used in the media or [[everyday language]], as recorded by major dictionaries. \n\nThe explanation of the term by NGO.org (the non-governmental organizations associated with the [[United Nations]]) is ambivalent: \"[an NGO is] any non-profit, voluntary citizens' group which is organized on a local, national or international level,\" but then goes on to restrict the meaning in the sense used by most English speakers and the media: \"Task-oriented and driven by people with a common interest, NGOs perform a variety of service and humanitarian functions, bring citizen concerns to Governments, advocate and monitor policies and encourage political participation through provision of information.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.ngo.org/ngoinfo/define.html|title = Definition of NGO|website = ngo.org}}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Ref page last updated in 2000|?=yes|date=April 2020}}\n\nNGOs are usually funded by [[Donation|donations]], but some avoid formal funding altogether and are run primarily by [[Volunteering|volunteers]]. NGOs are highly diverse groups of organizations engaged in a wide range of activities, and take different forms in different parts of the world. Some may have charitable status, while others may be registered for tax exemption based on recognition of social purposes. Others may be fronts for political, religious, or other interests. Since the end of [[World War II]], NGOs have had an increasing role in [[international development]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| pages = 74\u201375 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref> particularly in the fields of humanitarian assistance and poverty alleviation.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| page = 74 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref>\n\n[[Russia]] had about 277,000 NGOs in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hobbled NGOs wary of Medvedev |date=May 7, 2008 |work=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-05-07/news/0805060608_1_civil-society-russian-authorities-russian-president-vladimir-putin}}</ref> [[India]] is estimated to have had around 2 million NGOs in 2009, just over one NGO per 600 Indians, and many times the number of primary schools and primary health centres in India.<ref>{{cite journal |title=India: More NGOs, than schools and health centres |website=OneWorld.net |date=July 7, 2010 |url=http://southasia.oneworld.net/todaysheadlines/india-more-ngos-than-schools-and-health-centres |accessdate=2011-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First official estimate: An NGO for every 400 people in India |work=The Indian Express |date=July 7, 2010 |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/first-official-estimate-an-ngo-for-every-400-people-in-india/643302/}}</ref> \n\nThe term \"NGO\" is not always used consistently. In some countries, the term NGO is applied to an organization that in another country would be called an [[Nonprofit organization|NPO]] (a non-profit organization), and vice versa. [[Political party|Political parties]] and [[Trade union|trade unions]] are considered NGOs only in some countries. There are many different classifications of NGOs in use. The most common focus is on \"orientation\" and \"level of operation\". An NGO's orientation refers to the type of activities it takes on. These activities might include human rights, environmental, improving health, or development work. An NGO's level of operation indicates the scale at which an organization works, such as local, regional, national, or international.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vakil |first=Anna |title=Confronting the classification problem: Toward a taxonomy of NGOs |journal=World Development |date=December 1997 |volume=25 |issue=12 |pages=2057\u20132070 |doi=10.1016/S0305-750X(97)00098-3}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"''non-governmental organization''\" was first coined in 1945, when the [[United Nations]] (UN) was created.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas |title=NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-938753-3 |page=3 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/ngos-9780199387533}}</ref> The UN, itself an [[intergovernmental organization]], made it possible for certain approved specialized international non-state agencies \u2014 ''i.e.'', non-governmental organizations \u2014 to be awarded observer status at its assemblies and some of its meetings. Later, the term became used more widely. Today, according to the UN, any kind of private organization that is independent of government control can be termed an \"NGO\", provided it is not-for-profit,  but not simply an opposition [[political party]].<ref>[https://www.apa.org/international/united-nations/acronyms.pdf UNITED NATIONS: DEFINITIONS AND TERMS]</ref>\n\nPublic surveys reveal that NGOs often enjoy a high degree of public trust, which can make them a useful \u2013 but not always sufficient \u2013 proxy for the concerns of society and stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iisd.org/business/ngo/roles.aspx |title=The rise and role of NGOs in sustainable development |publisher=Iisd.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\nNGO types can be understood by their orientation and their level of operation.\n\n=== By orientation ===\n\n* ''Charitable orientation'' often involves a top-down effort with little participation or input by beneficiaries. It includes NGOs with activities directed toward meeting the needs of the disadvantaged people/groups.\n* ''Service orientation'' includes NGOs with activities such as the provision of health, the family planning, or the education services. In these activities, the programme is held by the NGOs, and the people are expected to participate in it and to receive the service.\n* ''Participatory orientation'' is characterized by self-help projects where local people are involved particularly in the implementation of a project by contributing cash, tools, land, materials, labor, etc. In the classical community development project, participation begins with the definition of need and continues to the planning and the implementation stages.\n* ''Empowering orientation'' aims to help poor people develop a clearer understanding of the social, political and economic factors affecting their lives, and to strengthen their awareness of their own potential power to control their lives. There is maximum involvement of the beneficiaries with NGOs acting as facilitators.<ref name=\"Lawry 2009 29-30\">{{cite book |last=Lawry |first=Lynn |title=Guide to Nongovernmental Organizations for the Military |year=2009 |pages=29\u201330 |url=http://www.cdham.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Chapter-4.-NGO-Structure-Authority-and-Standards.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730130926/http://www.cdham.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Chapter-4.-NGO-Structure-Authority-and-Standards.pdf |archivedate=2013-07-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== By level of operation ===\n\n* ''Community-based organizations'' (CBOs) arise out of people's own initiatives. They can be responsible for raising the consciousness of the urban poor, helping them  understand their rights in accessing required services and providing such services.\n* ''City-wide organizations'' include organizations such as chambers of commerce and industry, coalitions of business, ethnic or educational groups, and associations of community organizations.\n*''State NGOs'' include state-level organizations, associations and groups. Some state NGOs also work under the guidance of National and International NGOs.\n* ''National NGOs'' include national organizations such as the [[YMCA]]s/[[YWCA]]s, [[professional association]]s and similar groups. Some have state and city branches and assist local NGOs.\n* ''International NGOs'' range from secular agencies such as [[Save the Children]], to religiously motivated groups. They can be responsible for funding local NGOs, institutions and projects and implementing projects.<ref name=\"Lawry 2009 29-30\" />\n\nApart from \"NGO\", there are alternative or overlapping terms in use, including: [[Voluntary sector|third-sector]] organization (TSO), [[non-profit organization]] (NPO), voluntary organization (VO), [[civil society]] organization (CSO), [[grassroots]] organization (GO), [[social movement organization]] (SMO), private voluntary organization (PVO), [[self-help]] organization (SHO) and [[non-state actors]] (NSAs).\n\nIn Portuguese, Spanish, French, Italian and other [[Romance languages]], the 'mirrored' abbreviation \"ONG\" is in use, which has the same meaning as \"NGO\" (for example ''Organisation non-nongovernmental'' in French, ''Organiza\u00e7\u00e3o N\u00e3o Governmental'' in Portuguese, ''Organizaci\u00f3n no gubernamental'' in Spanish, or ''Organizzazione non governativa'' in Italian).\n\nGovernmental-related organizations / non-governmental organizations are a heterogeneous group. As a result, a long list of additional acronyms has developed, including:\n* BINGO: 'Business-friendly international NGO' or 'Big international NGO'\n* SBO: 'Social Benefit Organization,' a positive, goal-oriented designation as a substitute for the negative, \"Non-\" designations\n* TANGO: 'Technical assistance NGO'\n* TSO: 'third-sector organization'\n* [[GONGO]]: 'government-organized non-governmental organization' or 'government-operated NGOs' (set up by governments to look like NGOs in order to qualify for outside aid or promote the interests of government)\n* DONGO: 'Donor-organized NGO'\n* [[International non-governmental organization|INGO]]: 'International NGO'\n* [[QUANGO]]: 'quasi-autonomous NGO,' or [[QUANGO]] refers to NGOs set up and funded by the government. The term is particularly prevalent within the UK (where there are more than 1,200 of them), the Republic of Ireland, and the Commonwealth. \n* National NGO: A non-governmental organization that exists only in one country. This term is rare due to the globalization of non-governmental organizations, which causes an NGO to exist in more than one country.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\">{{cite web |last=Willetts |first=Peter |title=What is a Non-Governmental Organization? |url=http://www.staff.city.ac.uk/p.willetts/CS-NTWKS/NGO-ART.HTM |encyclopedia=UNESCO Encyclopaedia of Life Support Systems |publisher=City University London |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Civil society|CSO]]: 'Civil Society Organization'\n* [[ENGO]]: 'Environmental NGO,' such as [[Greenpeace]] and [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]\n* NNGO: 'Northern NGO'\n* PANGO: 'Party NGO,' set up by parties and disguised as NGOs to serve their political matters.\n* SNGO: 'Southern NGO'\n* SCO: 'Social change organization'\n* TNGO: 'Transnational NGO.' The term emerged during the 1970s due to the increase of environmental and economic issues in the global community. TNGO includes non-governmental organizations that are not confined to only one country but exist in two or more countries.\n* GSO: [[Grassroots Support Organization]]\n* MANGO: 'Market advocacy NGO'\n* NGDO: 'Non-governmental development organization'\n* PVDO: 'Private voluntary development organisation'<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-governmental organizations and development|last=Lewis|first=David|last2=Kanji|first2=Nazneen|publisher=Routledge|year=2009|isbn=978-0-203-87707-4|location=2 Park Square, Milton Park, Abingdon, Oxon, OX14 4RN|pages=9\u201310|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[USAID]] refers to NGOs as ''private voluntary organizations''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usaid.gov/partnership-opportunities/ngo|title=Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs)|website=www.usaid.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-12|date=2017-09-25}}</ref> However, many scholars have argued that this definition is highly problematic as many NGOs are in fact state- or corporate-funded and -managed projects and have professional staff.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}\n\nNGOs exist for a variety of reasons, usually to further the political or social goals of their members or founders. Examples include improving the state of the [[natural environment]], encouraging the observance of [[human rights]], improving the welfare of the disadvantaged, or representing a corporate agenda. However, there are a huge number of such organizations and their goals cover a broad range of political and philosophical positions. This can also easily be applied to private schools and athletic organizations.\n\n=== Track II diplomacy ===\n{{Main article|Track II diplomacy}}\nTrack II dialogue, or Track II diplomacy, is transnational coordination that involves non-official members of the government including [[epistemic community|epistemic communities]] as well as former policy-makers or analysts. Track II diplomacy aims to get policymakers and policy analysts to come to a common solution through discussions by unofficial means. Unlike the Track, I diplomacy where government officials, diplomats, and elected leaders gather to talk about certain issues, Track II diplomacy consists of experts, scientists, professors and other figures that are not involved in government affairs. The members of Track II diplomacy can have more freedom to exchange ideas and come up with compromises on their own.\n\n== Activities ==\nThere are numerous classifications of NGOs. The typology the [[World Bank]] uses divides them into Operational and Advocacy.<ref name=\"definition\">[http://docs.lib.duke.edu/igo/guides/ngo/define.htm World Bank Criteria defining NGO] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621135344/http://docs.lib.duke.edu/igo/guides/ngo/define.htm |date=June 21, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nGenerally, NGOs act as implementers, catalysts, and partners. Firstly, NGOs act as implementers, because they mobilize resources in order to provide goods and services to people who are suffering, due to a man-made disaster or a natural disaster. Secondly, NGOs act as catalysts that drive change. They have the ability to \"''inspire, facilitate, or contribute to improved thinking and action to promote change''\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}. Lastly, NGOs often act as partners alongside other organizations in order to tackle problems and address human needs more effectively.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-Governmental Organizations and Development|last=Lewis|first=David|last2=Kanji|first2=Nazneen|publisher=Routledge|year=2009|isbn=978-0415454308|location=Oxon|pages=12\u201313|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nNGOs vary in their methods. Some act primarily as lobbyists, while others primarily conduct programs and activities. For instance, an NGO such as [[Oxfam]], concerned with poverty alleviation, may provide needy people with the equipment and skills to find food and clean [[drinking water]], whereas an NGO like the [[FFDA]] helps through investigation and documentation of human rights{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} violations and provides legal assistance to victims of human rights abuses. Others, such as the [[Afghanistan Information Management Services]], provide specialized technical products and services to support development activities implemented on the ground by other organizations.\n\n=== Operational ===\nOperational NGOs seek to \"achieve small-scale change directly through projects\".<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> They mobilize financial resources, materials, and volunteers to create localized programs. They hold large-scale [[fundraising]] events and may apply to governments and organizations for grants or contracts to raise money for projects. They often operate in a [[Hierarchy|hierarchical]] structure; the main headquarters being staffed by professionals who plan projects, create budgets, keep accounts, and report and communicate with operational fieldworkers who work directly on projects.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Operational NGOs deal with a wide range of issues but are most often associated with the delivery of services or environmental issues, emergency relief, and public welfare. Operational NGOs can be further categorized by the division into relief-oriented versus development-oriented organizations; according to whether they stress service delivery or participation; whether they are religious or secular; and whether they are more public- or private-oriented. Although operational NGOs can be community-based, many are national or international. The defining activity of operational NGOs is the implementation of projects.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Campaigning ===\nCampaigning NGOs seek to \"''achieve large-scale change promoted indirectly through influence of the political system''\".<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Campaigning NGOs need an efficient and effective group of professional members who are able to keep supporters informed, and motivated. They must plan and host demonstrations and events that will keep their cause in the media. They must maintain a large informed network of supporters who can be mobilized for events to garner media attention and influence policy changes. The defining activity of campaigning NGOs is holding demonstrations.<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Campaigning NGOs often deal with issues relating to human rights, women's rights, and children's rights. The primary purpose of an Advocacy NGO is to defend or promote a specific cause. As opposed to operational project management, these organizations typically try to raise awareness, acceptance, and knowledge by lobbying, press work and activist event.<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Both operational and campaigning ===\nIt is not uncommon for NGOs to make use of both activities. Many times, operational NGOs will use campaigning techniques if they continually face the same issues in the field that could be remedied through policy changes. At the same time, Campaigning NGOs, like human rights organizations often have programs that assist the individual victims they are trying to help through their advocacy work.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Public relations ===\nNon-governmental organizations need healthy relationships with the public to meet their goals. Foundations and charities use sophisticated public relations campaigns to raise funds and employ standard lobbying techniques with governments. Interest groups may be of political importance because of their ability to influence social and political outcomes. A [[Code of Ethics|code of ethics]] was established in 2002 by The World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wango.org/codeofethics.aspx|title=World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations - Code of Ethics and Conduct for NGOs|website=www.wango.org|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\n=== Project management ===\nThere is an increasing awareness that management techniques are crucial to project success in non-governmental organizations.<ref>[http://www.lse.ac.uk/collections/CCS/pdf/int-work-paper4.pdf 100 <!-- application/pdf, 102909 bytes [[Kibibyte|KiB] --> LSE.ac.uk], Mukasa, Sarah. ''Are expatriate staff necessary in international development NGOs? A case study of an international NGO in Uganda.'' Publication of the Centre for Civil Society at the London School of Economics. 2002, p. 11-13.</ref> Generally, private non-governmental organizations have either a community or environmental focus. They address varieties of issues such as religion, emergency aid, or humanitarian affairs. They mobilize public support and voluntary contributions for aid; they often have strong links with community groups in developing countries, and they often work in areas where government-to-government aid is not possible. NGOs are accepted as a part of the international relations landscape, and while they influence national and multilateral policy-making, increasingly they are more directly involved in local action.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Corporate structure ==\n\n=== Staffing ===\nSome NGOs are highly professionalized and rely mainly on paid staff. Others are based around voluntary labor and are less formalized. Not all people working for non-governmental organizations are [[Volunteering|volunteer]]s.\n\nMany NGOs are associated with the use of international staff working in developing countries, but there are many NGOs around the world that rely on local employees or volunteers. There is some dispute as to whether [[expatriate]]s should be sent to developing countries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Frequently this type of personnel is employed to satisfy a [[Donation|donor]] who wants to see the supported project managed by someone from an [[Developed country|industrialized country]]. However, the expertise of these employees or volunteers may be counterbalanced by a number of factors: the cost of [[Alien (law)|foreigners]] is typically higher, they have no [[grassroots democracy|grass-root connections]] in the country they are sent to, and local expertise is often undervalued.<ref name=\"definition\" />\n\nThe NGO sector is an essential employer in terms of numbers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} For example, by the end of 1995, [[Concern Worldwide|CONCERN worldwide]], an international Northern NGO working against poverty, employed 174 expatriates and just over 5,000 national staff working in ten developing countries in [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], and in [[Haiti]].\n\n=== Funding ===\nMajor sources of NGO funding include membership dues, the sale of [[Product (business)|goods]] and services, grants from international institutions or national governments, and private [[donation]]s. \n\nMany NGOs depend heavily on governments for their funding, even though the term \"non-governmental organization\" implies [[independence]] from governments, <ref name=\"global\" /> A quarter of the US$162 million income in 1998 of the [[Famine relief|famine-relief]] organization [[Oxfam]] was donated by the British government and the EU. The Christian relief and development organization [[World Vision United States]] collected US$55 million worth of goods in 1998 from the American government. Several EU-grants provide funds accessible to NGOs.\n\nGovernment funding of NGOs is controversial since, according to David Rieff, writing in ''[[The New Republic]]'', \"the whole point of humanitarian intervention was precise that NGOs and civil society had both a right and an obligation to respond with acts of aid and solidarity to people in need or being subjected to repression or want by the forces that controlled them, whatever the governments concerned might think about the matter.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tnr.com/article/world/75421/ng-uh-o?page=0,0 |title=NG-Uh-O \u2013 The trouble with humanitarianism |author=David Rieff |date=June 10, 2010 |newspaper=The New Republic}}</ref> Some NGOs, such as [[Greenpeace]] do not accept funding from governments or intergovernmental organizations.<ref name=\"HBS\">{{cite web |author=Sarah Jane Gilbert |url=http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/5797.html |title=Harvard Business School, HBS Cases: The Value of Environmental Activists |publisher=Hbswk.hbs.edu |date=2008-09-08 |accessdate=2011-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"GP Annual report 2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.greenpeace.org/raw/content/international/press/reports/international-annualreport-2008.pdf |title=Greenpeace Annual Report 2008 |publisher=Greenpeace.org |year=2008 |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref>\n\nSome NGOs require sizeable funds to operate. For instance, the budget of the [[American Association of Retired Persons]] (AARP) was over US$540 million in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/12687/edition_id/245/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Poll shows power of AIPAC drops slightly|date=1999-12-19|publisher=Jewish News Weekly of Northern California|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref> Funding large budgets demands significant fundraising efforts on the part of most NGOs. \n\n=== Overhead costs ===\n[[Overhead (business)|Overhead]] is the amount of money that is spent on running an NGO rather than on projects.<ref name=Overhead1>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundsforngos.org/budget-for-ngos/defining-terms-budget/ |title=Defining certain terms in a budget |publisher=Funds for NGOs |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> This includes office expenses,<ref name=Overhead1 /> salaries, banking and bookkeeping costs. What percentage of overall budget is spent on overhead is often used to judge an NGO with less than 4% being viewed as good.<ref name=Overhead1 /> The World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations states that ideally more than 86% should be spent on programs (less than 20% on overhead).<ref>{{cite web |title=Code of Ethics & Conduct for NGOs |url=http://www.wango.org/codeofethics/ComplianceManual.pdf |accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]] has specific guidelines on how high overhead can be to receive funding based on how the money is to be spent with overhead often needing to be less than 5\u20137%<ref>{{cite web |title=National NGOs Serving as PRs Excluded from the Global Fund's Policy on Percentage-Based Overhead Costs |url=http://www.aidspan.org/index.php?issue=174&article=2 |year=2012}}</ref>, while the [[World Bank]] typically allows 37%.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Gibbs | first1=Christopher| last2=Fumo|first2=Claudia |last3=Kuby|first3=Thomas |title=Nongovernmental organizations in World Bank supported projects : a review |year=1999 |publisher=World Bank |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-0-8213-4456-9 |page=21 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=77m7ExDp8DQC&pg=PA21 |edition=2nd}}</ref> A high percentage of overhead to total expenditures can make it more difficult to generate funds.<ref>{{cite book |last=Crowther |first=edited by G\u00fcler Aras, David |title=NGOs and social responsibility |year=2010 |publisher=Emerald |location=Bingley, UK |isbn=978-0-85724-295-2 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T9mgFMJQhCsC&pg=PA121 |edition=1st}}</ref> High overhead costs may also generate criticism with some claiming the certain NGOs with high overhead are being run simply to benefit the people working for them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kassahun |first=Samson |title=Social capital for synergistic partnership : development of poor localities in urban Ethiopia |year=2004 |publisher=Cuvillier |location=G\u00f6ttingen |isbn=978-3-86537-222-2 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TSjsfco0elIC&pg=PA153 |edition=1. Aufl.}}</ref>\n\nWhile overhead costs can be a legitimate concern, a sole focus on them can be counterproductive.<ref>Schmitz, Hans Peter and George E. Mitchell 2010. [http://hausercenter.org/iha/2010/03/09/navigating-effectiveness/ Navigating Effectiveness], Humanitarian&Development NGOs Domain Blog, The Hauser Center for Nonprofit Organizations, Harvard University (March 9)</ref> Research published by the Urban Institute and the Center for Social Innovation at Stanford University have shown how rating agencies create incentives for non-profits to lower and hide overhead costs, which may actually reduce organizational effectiveness by starving organizations of the infrastructure they need to effectively deliver services.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.urban.org/publications/311055.html | title=The Pros and Cons of Financial Efficiency Standards| date=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/the_ratings_game/ | title=The Ratings Game (SSIR)}}</ref> A more meaningful rating system would provide, in addition to financial data, a qualitative evaluation of an organization\u2019s transparency and governance:\n\n(1) an assessment of program effectiveness;\n\n(2) and an evaluation of feedback mechanisms designed for donors and beneficiaries;\n\nand (3) such a rating system would also allow rated organizations to respond to an evaluation done by a rating agency.<ref>Lowell, Stephanie, Brian Trelstad, and Bill Meehan. 2005. [http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/the_ratings_game/ The Ratings Game. Evaluating the three groups that rate the Charities]. Stanford Social Innovation Review: 39\u201345.</ref> More generally, the popular discourse of non-profit evaluation should move away from financial notions of organizational effectiveness and toward a more substantial understanding of programmatic impact.\n\n=== Monitoring and control ===\nIn the March 2000 report on United Nations Reform priorities, former UN Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]] wrote in favor of international humanitarian intervention, arguing that the international community has a \"right to protect\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/preventgenocide/rwanda/about/bgresponsibility.shtml |title=Background Information on the Responsibility to Protect \u2014 Outreach Programme on the Rwanda Genocide and the United Nations |publisher=Un.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> citizens of the world against ethnic cleansing, genocide, and crimes against humanity. Following that report, the Canadian government launched the Responsibility to Protect (R2P)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://responsibilitytoprotect.org/ |title=International Coalition for the Responsibility to Protect (ICRtoP) |publisher=Responsibilitytoprotect.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> project, outlining the issue of humanitarian intervention. While the R2P doctrine has wide applications, among the more controversial has been the Canadian government's use of R2P to justify its intervention and support of the coup in Haiti.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Engler |first1=Fenton |last2=Yves |first2=Anthony |title=Canada in Haiti: Waging War on the Poor Majority |year=2005 |publisher=RED Publishing |location=Vancouver, Winnipeg |isbn=978-1-55266-168-0 |page=120 |url=http://www.fernwoodpublishing.ca/Canada-in-Haiti-Yves-Engler-Anthony-Fenton/ |accessdate=2011-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006154741/http://www.fernwoodpublishing.ca/Canada-in-Haiti-Yves-Engler-Anthony-Fenton/ |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}</ref>\n\nYears after R2P, the [[World Federalist Movement]], an organization that supports \"the creation of democratic global structures accountable to the citizens of the world and call for the division of international authority among separate agencies\", has launched Responsibility to Protect \u2013 Engaging Civil Society (R2PCS). A collaboration between the WFM and the Canadian government, this project aims to bring NGOs into lockstep with the principles outlined under the original R2P project.\n\nThe governments of the countries an NGO works or is registered in may require reporting or other monitoring and oversight. Funders generally require reporting and assessment, such information is not necessarily publicly available. There may also be associations and watchdog organizations that research and publish details on the actions of NGOs working in particular geographic or program areas.{{Citation needed|date=September 2007}}\n\nIn recent years, many large corporations have increased their [[corporate social responsibility]] departments in an attempt to preempt NGO campaigns against certain corporate practices. As the logic goes, if corporations work ''with'' NGOs, NGOs will not work ''against'' corporations. Greater collaboration between corporations and NGOs creates inherent risks of [[Co-option|co-optation]] for the weaker partner, typically the non-profit involved.<ref>{{cite journal |year=2012 |title=Corporations and NGOs: When Accountability Leads to Co-optation |journal=Journal of Business Ethics |volume=106 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201321 |doi=10.1007/s10551-011-1057-9|last1=Baur |first1=Dorothea |last2=Schmitz |first2=Hans Peter |url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/312987/files/10551_2011_Article_1057.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, The United States Department of Defense Assistant Secretary of Defense (Health Affairs) [[S. Ward Casscells]] established an [[International Health]] Division under Force Health Protection & Readiness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ha.osd.mil/FHPR/default.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208135444/http://www.ha.osd.mil/fhpr/default.cfm |archivedate=2006-12-08 }}</ref> Part of International Health's mission is to communicate with NGOs in areas of mutual interest. Department of Defense Directive 3000.05,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/300005p.pdf |title=Department of Defense Directive 3000.05 |publisher=United States Department of Defense |date=September 16, 2009 |accessdate=2013-12-24 }}</ref> in 2005, requires DoD to regard stability-enhancing activities as a mission of importance equal to combat. In compliance with [[Geneva conventions|international law]], DoD has necessarily built a capacity to improve essential services in areas of conflict such as [[Iraq]], where the customary lead agencies ([[State Department]] and [[USAID]]) find it difficult to operate. Unlike the \"co-option\" strategy described for corporations, the OASD(HA) recognizes the neutrality of health as an essential service. International Health cultivates collaborative relationships with NGOs, albeit at arm's length, recognizing their traditional independence, expertise, and honest broker status. While the goals of DoD and NGOs may seem incongruent, the DoD's emphasis on stability and security to reduce and prevent conflict suggests, on careful analysis, important mutual interests.\n\n== History ==\nInternational non-governmental organizations have a history dating back to at least the late 18th century.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas |title=NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-938753-3 |page=23 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/ngos-9780199387533}}</ref><ref>Steve Charnovitz, \"Two Centuries of Participation: NGOs and International Governance, Michigan Journal of International Law, Winter 1997.</ref> It has been estimated that by 1914, there were 1083 NGOs.<ref>{{cite book |title=Subcontracting Peace \u2013 The Challenges of NGO Peacebuilding |editor1=Oliver P. Richmond |editor2=Henry F. Carey |publisher=Ashgate |year=2005 |page=21}}</ref> International NGOs were important in the [[abolitionism|anti-slavery movement]] and the movement for [[women's suffrage]] and reached a peak at the time of the [[World Disarmament Conference]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas Richard |title=The Possibilities of Transnational Activism: the Campaign for Disarmament between the Two World Wars |year=2007 |isbn=978-90-04-16258-7}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref> However, the phrase \"non-governmental organization\" only came into popular use with the establishment of the [[United Nations Organization]] in 1945 with provisions in Article 71 of [[Chapter 10 of the United Nations Charter]]<ref>[https://www.un.org/aboutun/charter/chapt10.htm Charter of the United Nations: Chapter X<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040322180234/http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter/chapt10.htm |date=March 22, 2004 }}</ref> for a consultative role for organizations which are neither governments nor member states\u2014see [[Consultative Status]] <ref>[http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1354066108089242 Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cReframing NGOs: The Identity of an International Relations Non-Starter.\u201d ''European Journal of International Relations'' 14 (2008) 2: 231\u2013258. ]</ref>. The definition of \"international NGO\" (INGO) is first given in resolution 288 (X) of ECOSOC on February 27, 1950: it is defined as \"any international organization that is not founded by an international treaty\". The vital role of NGOs and other \"major groups\" in [[sustainable development]] was recognized in Chapter 27<ref>{{cite web |author=United Nations Conference on Environment and Development |url=http://habitat.igc.org/agenda21/a21-27.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030217095008/http://habitat.igc.org/agenda21/a21-27.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-02-17 |title=Agenda 21 \u2013 Chapter 27: Strengthening the Role of Non-governmental Organizations: Partners for Sustainable Development, Earth Summit, 1992 |publisher=Habitat.igc.org |accessdate=2011-12-20 }}</ref> of [[Agenda 21]], leading to intense arrangements for a consultative relationship between the [[United Nations]] and non-governmental organizations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/documents/ecosoc/res/1996/eres1996-31.htm |title=1996/31. Consultative relationship between the United Nations and non-governmental organizations |publisher=Un.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-20}}</ref> It has been observed that the number of INGOs founded or dissolved matches the general \"state of the world\", rising in periods of growth and declining in periods of crisis.<ref>Boli, J. and Thomas, G. M. (1997) World Culture in the World Polity: A century of International Non-Governmental Organization. American Sociological Review. pp. 177</ref>\n\nThe rapid development of the non-governmental sector occurred in western countries as a result of the processes of restructuring of the [[welfare state]]. Further [[globalization]] of that process occurred after the fall of the communist system and was an important part of the [[Washington consensus]].<ref name=\"global\">Pawel Zaleski ''Global Non-governmental Administrative System: Geosociology of the Third Sector'', [in:] Gawin, Dariusz & Glinski, Piotr [ed.]: \"Civil Society in the Making\", IFiS Publishers, Warszawa 2006</ref>\n\nGlobalization during the 20th century gave rise to the importance of NGOs. Many problems could not be solved within a nation. [[Treaty|International treaties]] and international organizations such as the [[World Trade Organization]] were centred mainly on the interests of capitalist enterprises. In an attempt to counterbalance this trend, NGOs have developed to emphasize [[Humanitarianism|humanitarian issues]], [[developmental aid]], and [[sustainable development]]. A prominent example of this is the [[World Social Forum]], which is a rival convention to the [[World Economic Forum]] held annually in January in [[Davos, Switzerland|Davos]], [[Switzerland]]. The fifth World Social Forum in [[Porto Alegre]], [[Brazil]], in January 2005 was attended by representatives from more than 1,000 NGOs.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bartlett |first=Lauren |title=NGO Update |journal=Human Rights Brief |year=2005 |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> In terms of environmental issues and sustainable development, the [[Earth Summit]] in Rio in 1992 was the first to show the power of international NGOs, when about 2,400 representatives of NGOs came to play a central role in deliberations. Some have argued that in forums like these, NGOs take the place of what should belong to the popular movements of the poor. Whatever the case, NGO transnational networking is now extensive.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stone |first=Diane |title=Transfer Agents and Global Networks in the 'Transnationalisation' of Policy |journal=Journal of European Public Policy.austiniskewl |volume=11 |issue=3 |year=2004 |pages=545\u2013566 |doi=10.1080/13501760410001694291|url=http://wrap.warwick.ac.uk/1742/1/WRAP_Stone_JEPP_Transnational_Transfer.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Legal status ==\nThe legal form of NGOs is diverse and depends upon homegrown variations in each country's laws and practices. However, four main family groups of NGOs can be found worldwide:<ref>{{cite book |first=Grant B. |last=Stillman |year=2007 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=icRqqTdl_EIC |title=Global Standard NGOs: The Essential Elements of Good Practice |publisher=Grant B. Stillman |location=Geneva: Lulu |pages=13\u201314}}</ref>\n* Unincorporated and [[voluntary association]]\n* [[Trusts]], [[charities]], and [[Foundation (nonprofit organization)|foundations]]\n* Companies not just for profit\n* Entities formed or registered under special NGO or [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] laws\n\nThe [[Council of Europe]] in [[Strasbourg]] drafted the [[European Convention on the Recognition of the Legal Personality of International Non-Governmental Organizations]] in 1986, which sets a common legal basis for the existence and work of NGOs in Europe. Article 11 of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] protects the right to freedom of association, which is also a fundamental norm for NGOs.\n\n== Influence of NGOs upon world affairs ==\n\nService-delivery NGOs provide public goods and services that governments from developing countries are unable to provide to society, due to lack of resources. Service-delivery NGOs can serve as contractors or collaborate with democratized government agencies to reduce the cost associated with public goods. Capacity-building NGOs influence global affairs differently, in the sense that the incorporation of accountability measures in Southern NGOs affect \"culture, structure, projects and daily operations\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roberts |first1=Susan G. |last2=Jones III |first2=John P. |last3=Frohling |first3=Oliver |title=NGOs and the Globalization of Managerialism: A Research Framework |year=2005 |publisher=World Development |location=Great Britain |doi=10.1016/j.worldev.2005.07.004|page=1846|doi-broken-date=2020-03-25 }}</ref> Advocacy and public education NGOs affects global affairs in its ability to modify behaviour through the use of ideas. Communication is the weapon of choice used by advocacy and public-education NGOs in order to change people's actions and behaviours. They strategically construct messages to not only shape behaviour, but also socially mobilize communities in promoting social, political, or environmental changes. Movement NGOs mobilize the public and coordinate large-scale collective activities to significantly push forward the activism agenda.<ref>{{cite book|first1 =Jacob Mwathi|last1= Mati|first2= Fengshi|last2 = Wu|first3 = Bob|last3= Edwards|first4 = Sherine N. |last4 =El Taraboulsi|first5= David H. |last5 =Smith|date =2016|chapter =24: Social Movement Associations and Activist-Protest Volunteering|title = The Palgrave Handbook of Volunteering, Civic Participation, and Nonprofit Associations|publisher =Palgrave Macmillan|location = London|pages= 516\u2013538 |doi = 10.1007/978-1-137-26317-9_25|isbn= 978-1-137-26316-2}}</ref>\n\nIn the post-Cold War era, more NGOs based in developed countries have pursued international outreach and became involved in local and national level social resistance and become relevant to domestic policy change in the developing world.<ref>{Keck, Margaret, and Kathryn Sikkink, 1998. Activists beyond borders: Advocacy networks in international politics. Ithaca: Cornell University Press.}</ref> In for the cases where national governments are highly sensitive to external influences via non-state actors, specialized NGOs have been able to find the right partners (e.g., China), building up solid working networks, locating a policy niche and facilitating domestic changes. <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wu | first1 = Fengshi | year = 2005 | title = International Non-Governmental Actors in HIV/AIDS Prevention in China | url = | journal = Cell Research | volume = 15 | issue = 11\u201312| pages = 919\u2013922 | doi=10.1038/sj.cr.7290369| pmid = 16354570 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n==International Day==\n===World NGO Day===\n{{main article|World NGO Day}}\n[[File:World NGO Day Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|World NGO Day 2014 in [[Afghanistan]]|alt=World NGO Day 2014 in Afghanistan]]\n{{Quote box|quoted=true|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|salign=center|width=300px|align=left|quote=Today we celebrate the [[World NGO Day]], we celebrate the key civil society's contribution to public space and their unique ability to give voice to those who would have went [sic] otherwise unheard.|source= [[European Union External Action Service]], Official Statement by the [[Spokesperson]] of HR/VP [[Federica Mogherini]] on the occasion of the [[World NGO Day|WORLD NGO DAY]] 2017.- [[Bruxelles]], 27/02/2017 \u2013 ID: 170227_11 '.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eeas.europa.eu/headquarters/headquarters-homepage_en/21535/Statement%20on%20the%20occasion%20of%20the%20World%20NGO%20Day%202017 |title=Statement on the occasion of the World NGO Day 2017 |website=eeas.europa.eu |accessdate=2017-02-27}}</ref>}}\n[[World NGO Day]] is observed annually on 27 February. It was officially recognised and declared on 17 April 2010 by 12 countries of the IX [[Baltic Sea]] NGO Forum to the 8th Summit of the Baltic Sea States in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.3sektorius.lt/forumas/2010/?lng=en&id=5 | title=3sektorius}}</ref> The World NGO Day was internationally marked and recognised on 28 February 2014 in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] by [[Helen Clark]], Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] ([[UNDP]]) and Former [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] who congratulated with the [[World NGO Day]] and highlighted the importance of NGO sector for the [[UN]] through her speech.<ref name=\"unric.org\">{{cite web|url = http://www.unric.org/en/week-ahead-archives/29049-the-week-ahead-at-the-united-nations-the-european-perspective-0714-17-24-february-2014 |title = THE WEEK AHEAD AT THE UNITED NATIONS: THE EUROPEAN PERSPECTIVE (07/14): 17\u201324 February 2014 |publisher = United Nations|accessdate = 14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.finnbay.com/media/news/world-ngo-day-international-celebration-recognition/ | title=Site Unavailable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQwdcSsF0B8|title=Helen Clark on World NGO Day|last=United Nations Development Programme (UNDP)|date=27 February 2014|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\n[[Issa G. Shivji]] is one of Africa's leading experts on law and development issues as an author and academic. His criticism on NGOs is found in two essays: \"Silences in NGO discourse: The role and future of NGOs in Africa\" and \"Reflections on NGOs in Tanzania: What we are, what we are not and what we ought to be\". Shivji argues that despite the good intentions of NGO leaders and activists, he is critical of the \"objective effects of actions, regardless of their intentions\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Shivji |first=Issa G. |title=Silence in NGO discourse: the role and future of NGOs in Africa |year=2007 |publisher=Fahamu |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-9545637-5-2 |page=84}}</ref> Shivji argues also that the sudden rise of NGOs is part of a [[neoliberal]] paradigm, rather than pure altruistic motivations. He is critical of the current manifestations of NGOs wanting to change the world without understanding it, and that the [[Imperialism|imperial]] relationship continues today with the rise of NGOs.\n\nJames Pfeiffer, in his case study of NGO involvement in Mozambique, speaks to the negative effects that NGOs have had on areas of health within the country. He argues that over the last decade, NGOs in Mozambique have \"fragmented the local health system, undermined local control of health programs, and contributed to growing local social inequality\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nHe notes further that NGOs can be uncoordinated, creating parallel projects among different organizations, that pull health service workers away from their routine duties in order to serve the interests of the NGOs. This ultimately undermines local primary health care efforts and takes away the governments' ability to maintain agency over their own health sector.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | last1 = Pfeiffer | first1 = J | year = 2003 | title = International NGOs and primary health care in Mozambique: the need for a new model of collaboration | url = | journal = Social Science & Medicine | volume = 56 | issue = 4| pages = 725\u2013738 | doi=10.1016/s0277-9536(02)00068-0| pmid = 12560007 }}</ref> Pfeiffer suggested a new model of collaboration between the NGO and the DPS (the Mozambique Provincial Health Directorate). He mentioned the NGO should be 'formally held to standard and adherence within the host country', for example, reduce 'showcase' projects and parallel programs that prove to be unsustainable.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n[[Jessica Mathews]] wrote in [[Foreign Affairs]] in 1997: \"For all their strengths, NGOs are special interests. The best of them \u2026 often suffer from tunnel vision, judging every public act by how it affects their particular interest\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/52644/jessica-t-mathews/power-shift |title=Power Shift |journal=Foreign Affairs |issue=January/February 1997 |date=January\u2013February 1997 |author=Jessica T. Mathews |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Since NGOs do not have to worry about policy trade-offs, the overall impact of their cause might bring more harm to society.<ref>Bond, M. (2000) The Backlash against NGOs. [[Prospect (magazine)]].</ref>\n\n[[Vijay Prashad]] argues that from the 1970s \"The World Bank, under Robert McNamara, championed the NGO as an alternative to the state, leaving intact global and regional relations of power and production.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpa.org.au/amrarch/40vp.html |title=Mother Teresa: A Communist View |accessdate=2008-07-24 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724153535/http://www.cpa.org.au/amrarch/40vp.html |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}, Vijay Prashad, ''Australian Marxist Review'', No. 40 August 1998</ref>\n\nOthers argue that NGOs are often imperialist<ref>[http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ Abahlali baseMjondolo''Rethinking Public Participation from below] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322205607/http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ |date=2010-03-22 }}, 'Critical Dialogue', 2006</ref> in nature, that they sometimes operate in a [[racialized]] manner in [[third world]] countries, and that they fulfill a similar function to that of the clergy during the high colonial era. The philosopher [[Peter Hallward]] argues that they are an aristocratic form of politics.<ref>{{cite book|last = Hallward|first= Peter|title = Damming the Flood: Haiti and the Politics of Containment|date = April 2008|publisher = Verso|location =London |isbn= 9781844672349}}</ref> He also points to the fact that NGOs like [[Action Aid]] and [[Christian Aid]] \"effectively condoned the [2004 US backed] coup\" against an elected government in Haiti and argues that they are the \"humanitarian face of imperialism\".<ref>[http://www.tanbou.com/2011/PeterHallwardRespondsToBbcRadio4Program.htm Peter Hallward responds to BBC Radio 4 program on Haiti], ''Tanbou'', 11/01/2011</ref> Popular movements in the global South such as the [[Western Cape Anti-Eviction Campaign]] in [[South Africa]] have sometimes refused to work with NGOs arguing that this will compromise their autonomy.<ref>[http://abahlali.org/files/Oldfield%20&%20Stokke%20WCAEC%20Research%20Report.pdf Building unity in diversity: Social movement activism in the Western Cape Anti-Eviction Campaign], Sophie Oldfield & Kristian Stokke, 2004</ref><ref>[http://www.poormagazine.org/node/2718 Ashraf Cassiem: South African Resistance Against Evictions], Marlon Crump, ''Poor Magazine'', 2009</ref> It has also been argued that NGOs often disempower people by allowing funders to push for stability over social justice.<ref>[http://www.grocotts.co.za/content/are-ngos-enemies-sas-rural-folk-03-07-2013 Are NGOs enemies of SA's rural folk?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922094058/http://www.grocotts.co.za/content/are-NGOs-enemies-sas-rural-folk-03-07-2013 |date=2013-09-22 }}, Youlendree Appasamy, ''Grocott's Mail'', July 2013</ref>\n\nAnother criticism of NGOs is that they are being designed and used as extensions of the normal foreign-policy instruments of certain Western countries and groups of countries.<ref>[http://www.newleftproject.org/index.php/site/article_comments/ngo_the_guise_of_innocence \u2018NGO\u2019: The Guise of Innocence], by Jenny O'Connor, ''New Left Project'', 2012</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/19/fake-rock-plot-spy-russians |title = Britain admits 'fake rock' plot to spy on Russians|work = The Guardian|date =19 January 2012|last1 = Topping|first1 = Alexandra|last2 = Elder |first2 = Miriam}}</ref> Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] made this accusation at the 43rd [[Munich Conference on Security Policy]] in 2007, concluding that these NGOs \"are formally independent but they are purposefully financed and therefore under control\".<ref>{{cite speech |title=Speech and the Following Discussion at the Munich Conference on Security Policy |first=Vladimir |last=Putin |authorlink=Vladimir Putin |event=43rd Munich Conference on Security Policy |location=[[Munich]], [[Germany]] |date=February 10, 2007 |url=http://archive.kremlin.ru/eng/speeches/2007/02/10/0138_type82912type82914type82917type84779_118123.shtml |accessdate=February 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309232547/https://archive.kremlin.ru/eng/speeches/2007/02/10/0138_type82912type82914type82917type84779_118123.shtml |archivedate=March 9, 2012 }}</ref>\nAlso, Michael Bond wrote \"Most large NGOs, such as Oxfam, the Red Cross, Cafod and Action Aid, are striving to make their aid provision more sustainable. But some, mostly in the US, are still exporting the ideologies of their backers.\"<ref>Bond, Michael. \"The Backlash against NGOs.\" Prospect, April 2000, pp.321. Print.</ref>\n\nNGOs have also been accused of using white lies or misinformed advice to enact their campaigns, i.e., accusations that NGOs have been ignorant about critical issues because, as chief scientist at [[Greenpeace]] Doug Parr said, these organizations appear to have lost their efforts in being truly scientific and now seem to be more self-interested. Rather than operating through science to be rationally and effectively practical, NGOs have been accused of abusing the utilization of science to gain their own advantages. In the beginning, as Parr indicated, there was \"a tendency among our critics to say that science is the only decision-making tool \u2026 but political and commercial interests are using science as a cover for getting their way.\"<ref name = bond323>{{citation|last = Bond|first = Michael|title = The Backlash against NGOs|work = Prospect|date = April 2000|page =323|url = https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/thebacklashagainstngos}}</ref> At the same time, NGOs can appear to not be cooperative with other groups, according to the previous policy-maker for the German branch of [[Friends of the Earth]], Jens Katjek. \"If NGOs want the best for the environment\", he says, \"they have to learn to compromise.\"<ref name = bond323/>\n\nNGOs have also been questioned as being \"too much of a good thing\".<ref name = Werker>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| pages = 73\u201392 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref> Eric Werker and Faisal Ahmed bring up three potential critiques of the role of NGOs in developing nations: too many NGOs in a nation\u2014particularly one ruled by a warlord\u2014reduces the NGO's ability to establish a credible threat of removing humanitarian assistance since they can easily be replaced by another NGO; the frequent process of resource allocation and outsourcing to local organizations in international development projects results in high expenses for NGOs and rings into question how much of the resources and money actually goes to the intended beneficiaries at the end of the allocation process; and finally, NGO missions tend to be too paternalistic and expensive, though Werker and Ahmed propose that vouchers are a good way to overcome this obstacle.<ref name = Werker/>\n\n=== Challenges to legitimacy ===\nThe issue of the legitimacy of NGOs raises a series of important questions. Legitimacy is one of the most important assets possessed by an NGO and is gained due to them being perceived as an \"independent voice\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Weber | first1 = N. | last2 = Christopherson | first2 = T. | year = 2002 | title = The influence of non-governmental organizations on the creation of Natura 2000 during the European policy process | url = | journal = Forest Policy and Economics | volume = 4 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201312 | doi=10.1016/s1389-9341(01)00070-3}}</ref><ref name=\"2002aHD\">Edwards, M. and Hulme, D. (2002) NGO Performance and Accountability: Introduction and Overview. \"In Edwards, M. and Hulme, D., ed. 2002.\" The Earthscan Reader on NGO Management. UK: Earthscan Publications Ltd. Chapter 11.</ref> Their representation also emerges as an important question. Who bestows responsibilities to NGOs or INGOs and how do they gain the representation of citizens and civil society is still not scrutinized thoroughly. For instance, in the article, it is stated, \"To put the point starkly: are the citizens of countries of the South and their needs represented in global civil society, or are citizens as well as their needs constructed by practices of representation? And when we realize that INGOs hardly ever come face to face with the people whose interests and problems they represent, or that they are not accountable to the people they represent, matters become even more troublesome.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chandhoke | first1 = Neera | year = 2005 | title = How Global Is Global Civil Society? | url = | journal = Journal of World-Systems Research | volume = 11 | issue = 2| pages = 326\u2013327 | doi = 10.5195/JWSR.2005.388 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe origin of funding can have serious implications for the legitimacy of NGOs. NGOs have increased their numbers and range of activities to a level where they have become increasingly dependent on a limited number of donors.<ref name=\"1996HD\">Edwards, M. and Hulme, D. (1996) Too Close for comfort? The impact of official aid on Non-Governmental Organisations. \"World Development.\" 24(6), pp. 961\u2013973.</ref> Consequently, competition has increased for funding, as have the expectations of the donors, who may add conditions that threaten the independence of NGOs.<ref>, Ebrahim, A. (2003) Accountability in practice: Mechanisms for NGOs. \"World Development.\" 31(5), pp.813\u2013829.</ref> An over-dependence on official aid may dilute \"the willingness of NGOs to speak out on issues which are unpopular with governments\".<ref name=2002aHD /> Some commentators have also argued that the changes in NGO funding sources have ultimately altered their functions.<ref name=2002aHD /><ref>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/05/17/mckibbens-divestment-tour/ Brought to You by Wall Street], CORY MORNINGSTAR, ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2013.05.17</ref><ref>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/03/14/350-orgs-friends-on-wall-street/ The Climate Wealth Opportunists], CORY MORNINGSTAR, ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2014.03.14</ref>\n\nNGOs have also been challenged on the grounds that they do not necessarily represent the needs of the developing world, through diminishing the so-called \u201cSouthern Voice\u201d. Some postulate that the [[North\u2013South divide]] exists in the arena of NGOs.<ref name=\"linden\">Lindenberg, M. and Bryant, C. (2001) Going Global: Transforming Relief and Development NGOs. Bloomfield: Kumarian Press.</ref> They question the equality of the relationships between Northern and Southern parts of the same NGOs as well as the relationships between Southern and Northern NGOs working in partnerships. This suggests a division of labor may develop, with the North taking the lead in advocacy and resource mobilization whilst the South engages in service delivery in the developing world.<ref name=linden /> The potential implications of this may mean the needs of the developing world are not addressed appropriately as Northern NGOs do not properly consult or participate in partnerships, such that they assign unrepresentative priorities.<ref>, Jenkins, R. (2001) Corporate Codes of Conduct: Self-Regulation in a Global Economy. \"Technology, Business and Society Programme Paper Number 2.\" United Nations Research Institute for Social Development.</ref>\n\nNGOs are also said to damage the public sector in target countries, e.g. accusations that NGO mismanagement has resulted in the breakdown of public health care systems. Instead of promoting equity and alleviating poverty, NGOs have been under scrutiny for contributing to socioeconomic inequality and dis-empowering services in the public sector of third world countries.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=Patrick-Cockburn>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/03/25/how-ngos-failed-afghanistan/ How NGOs Failed Afghanistan], [[Patrick Cockburn]], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2014.03.25</ref>\n\nThe scale and variety of activities in which NGOs participate have grown rapidly since 1980, particularly since 1990.<ref>Avina, J. (1993) The Evolutionary Life Cycles if Non-Governmental Development Organisations. \"Public Administration and Development.\" 13(5), pp. 453\u2013474.</ref> This has presented NGOs with a need to balance the pressures of centralization and decentralization. By centralizing NGOs, particularly those that operate at an international level, they can assign a common theme or set of goals. Conversely, it may also be advantageous to decentralize to increase the chances of an NGO responding more flexibly and effectively to localized issues by implementing projects, which are modest in scale, easily monitored, produce immediate benefits, and where all involved know that corruption will be punished.<ref name=Patrick-Cockburn /><ref>Anheier, H. and Themudo, N. (2002) Organisational forms of global civil society: Implications of going global. In: Anheier, H. Glasius, M. Kaldor, M, ed 2002.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[List of active non-governmental organizations of national minorities, indigenous and diasporas|List of active NGOs of national minorities]]\n* [[:Category:Non-governmental organizations]]\n* [[Advocacy group]] (interest group)\n* [[Charitable organization]]\n* [[Community foundation]]\n* [[Civil Society Organization]]\n* [[International organization]]\n* [[NGO-ization]]\n* [[Non-profit organization]]\n* [[Track II diplomacy]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1354066108089242 Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cReframing NGOs: The Identity of an International Relations Non-Starter.\u201d ''European Journal of International Relations'' 14 (2008) 2: 231\u2013258. ]\n* Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cCivil Society and NGO: Far from Unproblematic Concepts.\u201d ''The Ashgate Research Companion to Non-State Actors''. Bob Reinalda (ed.). Aldershot: Ashgate, 2011. 185\u2013196.\n* Hilton, Matthew et al. eds. ''The Politics of Expertise: How NGOs Shaped Modern Britain'' (2013)\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Watkins | last2 = Cotts | first2 = Susan | last3 = Swidler | first3 = Ann | last4 = Hannan | first4 = Thomas | year = 2012 | title = Outsourcing Social Transformation: Development NGOs as Organizations | journal = Annual Review of Sociology | volume = 38 | issue = | pages = 285\u2013315 | doi=10.1146/annurev-soc-071811-145516}}\n* Davies, T. 2014. NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society. New York: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-938753-3}}.\n* Velusamy M. Non-Governmental Organisation, Dominant Publishers & Distribution Ltd, New Delhi\n* Mark Butler, with Thulani Ndlazi, David Ntseng, Graham Philpott, and Nomusa Sokhela. ''NGO Practice and the Possibility of Freedom'' Church Land Programme, Pietermaritzburg, South Africa 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205081725/http://www.churchland.co.za/upload/files/OccasionalPaperNo3.pdf Churchland.co.za]\n* Olivier Berthoud, ''NGOs: Somewhere between Compassion, Profitability and Solidarity'' [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/1526 Envio.org.ni], PDF [http://www.edinter.net/docs/ONGBOLEN0102.pdf Edinter.net] Envio, Managua, 2001\n* Terje Tvedt, 19982/2003: Angels of Mercy or Development Diplomats. NGOs & Foreign Aid, Oxford: James Currey\n* Steve W. Witt, ed. Changing Roles of NGOs in the Creation, Storage, and Dissemination of Information in Developing Countries (Saur, 2006). {{ISBN|3-598-22030-8}}\n* Cox, P. N. Shams, G. C. Jahn, P. Erickson, and P. Hicks. 2002. Building collaboration between NGOs and agricultural research iNGOs \u2013 Die Gewerkschaften in Guinea w\u00e4hrend der Unruhen 2007'' \u2013 [[European University Center for Peace Studies|EPU]] Research Papers: Issue 03/07, Stadtschlaining 2007 {{in lang|de}}\n* [[Lyal Sunga|Lyal S. Sunga]], \"Dilemmas facing INGOs in coalition-occupied Iraq\", in Ethics in Action: The Ethical Challenges of International Human Rights Nongovernmental Organizations, edited by Daniel A. Bell and Jean-Marc Coicaud, Cambridge Univ. and United Nations Univ. Press, 2007.\n* [[Lyal Sunga|Lyal S. Sunga]], \"NGO Involvement in International Human Rights Monitoring, International Human Rights Law and Non-Governmental Organizations\" (2005) 41\u201369.\n* Werker & Ahmed (2008): What do Non-Governmental Organizations do?\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Charnovitz | first1 = Steve | year = 1997 | title = Two Centuries of Participation: NGOs and International Governance | url = | journal = Michigan Journal of International Law | volume = 18 | issue = | pages = 183\u2013286 }}\n* Abahlali baseMjondolo [https://web.archive.org/web/20100322205607/http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ ''Rethinking Public Participation from Below''], 'Critical Dialogue', 2006\n* Akpan S. M (2010): Establishment of Non-Governmental Organizations (In Press).\n* Edward A. L. Turner (2010) ''[http://escholarship.org/uc/item/97p470sx Why Has the Number of International Non-Governmental Organizations Exploded since 1960?]'', [[Cliodynamics]], 1, (1).\n* Eugene Fram & Vicki Brown, How Using the Corporate Model Makes a Nonprofit Board More Effective & Efficient \u2013 Third Edition (2011), Amazon Books, Create Space Books.\n* David Lewis and Nazneen Kanji (2009): Non-Governmental Organizations and Development. New York: Routledge.\n* Issa G. Shivji (2007): Silence in NGO Discourse: The Role and Future of NGOs in Africa. Nairobi: Fahamu.\n* Jens Steffek and Kristina Hahn (2010): Evaluating Transnational NGOs: Legitimacy, Accountability, Representation. New York: Palgrave, Macmillan.\n* [[Yearbook of International Organizations]], produced by the [[Union of International Associations]].\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.staff.city.ac.uk/p.willetts/CS-NTWKS/NGO-ART.HTM |title=What is a Non-Governmental Organization? |publisher=City University, London}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQwdcSsF0B8 |title=Video speech \u2013 Helen Clark, Administrator of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) on World NGO Day}}\n\n{{Charity}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Non-governmental organizations| 01]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations]]\n[[Category:Types of organization]]\n[[Category:Civil affairs]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1940s]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|NGO}}\n{{short description|Organization independent of any government}}\n{{copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Pekka Haavisto - World NGO Day, Finland.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3| H.E. [[Pekka Haavisto]], Minister for International Development of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs in Finland]] at the first [[World NGO Day]], [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] in 2014]]\n[[File:Europe in a suitcase - UK.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[George Melashvili]], the head of the EGI, addresses the audience at the launch of the project \"''Europe in a Suitcase''\" implemented in cooperation of two NGOs - the [[Europe-Georgia Institute]] and the [[Friedrich Naumann Foundation]] aiming to increase cooperation between European politicians, journalists and representatives of civic sector and academia with their counterparts in [[Georgia (Country)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"egisutcase\">[https://egi.ge/en/archives/5187 Europe in a suitcase: Oliver Wardrop Discussions]</ref>.]]\n[[File:14-08-10-wikimania-gruppenfoto-01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|The group photo at Wikimania 2014 London. [[Wikimania]] is the official annual conference of the [[Wikimedia Foundation]], an [[United States|American]] non-profit and [[charitable organization]] headquartered in [[San Francisco]], [[California]],<ref name=\"Hanson2016\">{{cite book|author=Jarice Hanson|title=The Social Media Revolution: An Economic Encyclopedia of Friending, Following, Texting, and Connecting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ePEZDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA375|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-768-2|page=375}}</ref>  mostly known for participating in the [[Wikimedia movement]]. It owns the internet domain names of most movement projects and hosts sites like [[Wikipedia]].  ]]\n\n[[Organizations]] that are independent of any government's involvement<ref name=\":3\">{{citation|title=NGO|url=http://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/american/ngo|dictionary=Macmillan Dictionary}}</ref> are called '''Non-governmental organizations.''' These organizations are also known as '''NGOs''',<ref name=\":0\">The term ''NGO'' is so common and its expansion so rare that all dictionaries have an entry for the abbreviation, but many do not have one for the expansion, or they even explain it by using the abbreviation, e.g. [https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/nongovernmental-organization Collins English Dictionary]</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Claiborne|first1=N|year=2004|title=Presence of social workers in nongovernment organizations|journal=Soc Work|volume=49|issue=2|pages=207\u2013218|doi=10.1093/sw/49.2.207|pmid=15124961}}</ref> or '''non-government organizations.'''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Horowitz|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/world/europe/migrant-ship-monitor-mediterranean.html|title=Ship Monitoring Rescues of Migrants Refuses to Be Rescued|date=2017-08-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> NGOs are usually [[Nonprofit organization|non-profitable.]]<ref name=\":4\">Because many of the most famous NGOs are [[INGOs|International non-governmental organization]], many people believe NGOs are by definition international, but that is not the way the term is interpreted by NGOs, the media, governments, or international governmental organizations.\n(See the sources at the end of this sentence.)</ref> Many of them are active in the areas of humanitarian or social sciences. However, NGOs can also be [[lobby groups]] for corporations, such as the [[World Economic Forum]]..<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usip.org/glossary/nongovernmental-organization-ngo|title=Nongovernmental Organization (NGO)|website=United States Institute of Peace}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Karns|series=|quote=|pages=|doi=|oclc=|isbn=|id=|location=|volume=|year=|first=Margaret P.|date=|edition=|language=|access-date=|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/nongovernmental-organization|title=Nongovernmental organization|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica|editor-first=|editor-last=|ref=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/ngo|title=NGO - meaning in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Oxford Dictionaries|NGO}}</ref>\n\nNGOs are a subgroup of all organizations founded by citizens, which include clubs and other [[club (organization)|associations]] that provide services, benefits, and premises only to members{{dubious |reason=NGO's usually give aid to other outsiders|date=February 2020}}. Sometimes the term is used as a synonym of \"[[civil society organization]]\" to refer to any association founded by citizens,<ref name=\"usstate\">\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20170122211029/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/fs/2017/266904.htm Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) in the United States]\" (fact sheet). January 20, 2017. Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor. U.S. Department of State. state.gov. Retrieved 2017-09-21.</ref> but this is not how the term is normally used in the media or [[everyday language]], as recorded by major dictionaries. \n\nThe explanation of the term by NGO.org (the non-governmental organizations associated with the [[United Nations]]) is ambivalent: \"[an NGO is] any non-profit, voluntary citizens' group which is organized on a local, national or international level,\" but then goes on to restrict the meaning in the sense used by most English speakers and the media: \"Task-oriented and driven by people with a common interest, NGOs perform a variety of service and humanitarian functions, bring citizen concerns to Governments, advocate and monitor policies and encourage political participation through provision of information.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.ngo.org/ngoinfo/define.html|title = Definition of NGO|website = ngo.org}}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Ref page last updated in 2000|?=yes|date=April 2020}}\n\nNGOs are usually funded by [[Donation|donations]], but some avoid formal funding altogether and are run primarily by [[Volunteering|volunteers]]. NGOs are highly diverse groups of organizations engaged in a wide range of activities, and take different forms in different parts of the world. Some may have charitable status, while others may be registered for tax exemption based on recognition of social purposes. Others may be fronts for political, religious, or other interests. Since the end of [[World War II]], NGOs have had an increasing role in [[international development]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| pages = 74\u201375 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref> particularly in the fields of humanitarian assistance and poverty alleviation.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| page = 74 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref>\n\n[[Russia]] had about 277,000 NGOs in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hobbled NGOs wary of Medvedev |date=May 7, 2008 |work=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-05-07/news/0805060608_1_civil-society-russian-authorities-russian-president-vladimir-putin}}</ref> [[India]] is estimated to have had around 2 million NGOs in 2009, just over one NGO per 600 Indians, and many times the number of primary schools and primary health centres in India.<ref>{{cite journal |title=India: More NGOs, than schools and health centres |website=OneWorld.net |date=July 7, 2010 |url=http://southasia.oneworld.net/todaysheadlines/india-more-ngos-than-schools-and-health-centres |accessdate=2011-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First official estimate: An NGO for every 400 people in India |work=The Indian Express |date=July 7, 2010 |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/first-official-estimate-an-ngo-for-every-400-people-in-india/643302/}}</ref> \n\nThe term \"NGO\" is not always used consistently. In some countries, the term NGO is applied to an organization that in another country would be called an [[Nonprofit organization|NPO]] (a non-profit organization), and vice versa. [[Political party|Political parties]] and [[Trade union|trade unions]] are considered NGOs only in some countries. There are many different classifications of NGOs in use. The most common focus is on \"orientation\" and \"level of operation\". An NGO's orientation refers to the type of activities it takes on. These activities might include human rights, environmental, improving health, or development work. An NGO's level of operation indicates the scale at which an organization works, such as local, regional, national, or international.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vakil |first=Anna |title=Confronting the classification problem: Toward a taxonomy of NGOs |journal=World Development |date=December 1997 |volume=25 |issue=12 |pages=2057\u20132070 |doi=10.1016/S0305-750X(97)00098-3}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"''non-governmental organization''\" was first coined in 1945, when the [[United Nations]] (UN) was created.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas |title=NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-938753-3 |page=3 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/ngos-9780199387533}}</ref> The UN, itself an [[intergovernmental organization]], made it possible for certain approved specialized international non-state agencies \u2014 ''i.e.'', non-governmental organizations \u2014 to be awarded observer status at its assemblies and some of its meetings. Later, the term became used more widely. Today, according to the UN, any kind of private organization that is independent of government control can be termed an \"NGO\", provided it is not-for-profit,  but not simply an opposition [[political party]].<ref>[https://www.apa.org/international/united-nations/acronyms.pdf UNITED NATIONS: DEFINITIONS AND TERMS]</ref>\n\nPublic surveys reveal that NGOs often enjoy a high degree of public trust, which can make them a useful \u2013 but not always sufficient \u2013 proxy for the concerns of society and stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iisd.org/business/ngo/roles.aspx |title=The rise and role of NGOs in sustainable development |publisher=Iisd.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\nNGO types can be understood by their orientation and their level of operation.\n\n=== By orientation ===\n\n* ''Charitable orientation'' often involves a top-down effort with little participation or input by beneficiaries. It includes NGOs with activities directed toward meeting the needs of the disadvantaged people/groups.\n* ''Service orientation'' includes NGOs with activities such as the provision of health, the family planning, or the education services. In these activities, the programme is held by the NGOs, and the people are expected to participate in it and to receive the service.\n* ''Participatory orientation'' is characterized by self-help projects where local people are involved particularly in the implementation of a project by contributing cash, tools, land, materials, labor, etc. In the classical community development project, participation begins with the definition of need and continues to the planning and the implementation stages.\n* ''Empowering orientation'' aims to help poor people develop a clearer understanding of the social, political and economic factors affecting their lives, and to strengthen their awareness of their own potential power to control their lives. There is maximum involvement of the beneficiaries with NGOs acting as facilitators.<ref name=\"Lawry 2009 29-30\">{{cite book |last=Lawry |first=Lynn |title=Guide to Nongovernmental Organizations for the Military |year=2009 |pages=29\u201330 |url=http://www.cdham.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Chapter-4.-NGO-Structure-Authority-and-Standards.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730130926/http://www.cdham.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Chapter-4.-NGO-Structure-Authority-and-Standards.pdf |archivedate=2013-07-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== By level of operation ===\n\n* ''Community-based organizations'' (CBOs) arise out of people's own initiatives. They can be responsible for raising the consciousness of the urban poor, helping them  understand their rights in accessing required services and providing such services.\n* ''City-wide organizations'' include organizations such as chambers of commerce and industry, coalitions of business, ethnic or educational groups, and associations of community organizations.\n*''State NGOs'' include state-level organizations, associations and groups. Some state NGOs also work under the guidance of National and International NGOs.\n* ''National NGOs'' include national organizations such as the [[YMCA]]s/[[YWCA]]s, [[professional association]]s and similar groups. Some have state and city branches and assist local NGOs.\n* ''International NGOs'' range from secular agencies such as [[Save the Children]], to religiously motivated groups. They can be responsible for funding local NGOs, institutions and projects and implementing projects.<ref name=\"Lawry 2009 29-30\" />\n\nApart from \"NGO\", there are alternative or overlapping terms in use, including: [[Voluntary sector|third-sector]] organization (TSO), [[non-profit organization]] (NPO), voluntary organization (VO), [[civil society]] organization (CSO), [[grassroots]] organization (GO), [[social movement organization]] (SMO), private voluntary organization (PVO), [[self-help]] organization (SHO) and [[non-state actors]] (NSAs).\n\nIn Portuguese, Spanish, French, Italian and other [[Romance languages]], the 'mirrored' abbreviation \"ONG\" is in use, which has the same meaning as \"NGO\" (for example ''Organisation non-nongovernmental'' in French, ''Organiza\u00e7\u00e3o N\u00e3o Governmental'' in Portuguese, ''Organizaci\u00f3n no gubernamental'' in Spanish, or ''Organizzazione non governativa'' in Italian).\n\nGovernmental-related organizations / non-governmental organizations are a heterogeneous group. As a result, a long list of additional acronyms has developed, including:\n* BINGO: 'Business-friendly international NGO' or 'Big international NGO'\n* SBO: 'Social Benefit Organization,' a positive, goal-oriented designation as a substitute for the negative, \"Non-\" designations\n* TANGO: 'Technical assistance NGO'\n* TSO: 'third-sector organization'\n* [[GONGO]]: 'government-organized non-governmental organization' or 'government-operated NGOs' (set up by governments to look like NGOs in order to qualify for outside aid or promote the interests of government)\n* DONGO: 'Donor-organized NGO'\n* [[International non-governmental organization|INGO]]: 'International NGO'\n* [[QUANGO]]: 'quasi-autonomous NGO,' or [[QUANGO]] refers to NGOs set up and funded by the government. The term is particularly prevalent within the UK (where there are more than 1,200 of them), the Republic of Ireland, and the Commonwealth. \n* National NGO: A non-governmental organization that exists only in one country. This term is rare due to the globalization of non-governmental organizations, which causes an NGO to exist in more than one country.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\">{{cite web |last=Willetts |first=Peter |title=What is a Non-Governmental Organization? |url=http://www.staff.city.ac.uk/p.willetts/CS-NTWKS/NGO-ART.HTM |encyclopedia=UNESCO Encyclopaedia of Life Support Systems |publisher=City University London |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Civil society|CSO]]: 'Civil Society Organization'\n* [[ENGO]]: 'Environmental NGO,' such as [[Greenpeace]] and [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]\n* NNGO: 'Northern NGO'\n* PANGO: 'Party NGO,' set up by parties and disguised as NGOs to serve their political matters.\n* SNGO: 'Southern NGO'\n* SCO: 'Social change organization'\n* TNGO: 'Transnational NGO.' The term emerged during the 1970s due to the increase of environmental and economic issues in the global community. TNGO includes non-governmental organizations that are not confined to only one country but exist in two or more countries.\n* GSO: [[Grassroots Support Organization]]\n* MANGO: 'Market advocacy NGO'\n* NGDO: 'Non-governmental development organization'\n* PVDO: 'Private voluntary development organisation'<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-governmental organizations and development|last=Lewis|first=David|last2=Kanji|first2=Nazneen|publisher=Routledge|year=2009|isbn=978-0-203-87707-4|location=2 Park Square, Milton Park, Abingdon, Oxon, OX14 4RN|pages=9\u201310|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[USAID]] refers to NGOs as ''private voluntary organizations''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usaid.gov/partnership-opportunities/ngo|title=Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs)|website=www.usaid.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-09-12|date=2017-09-25}}</ref> However, many scholars have argued that this definition is highly problematic as many NGOs are in fact state- or corporate-funded and -managed projects and have professional staff.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}\n\nNGOs exist for a variety of reasons, usually to further the political or social goals of their members or founders. Examples include improving the state of the [[natural environment]], encouraging the observance of [[human rights]], improving the welfare of the disadvantaged, or representing a corporate agenda. However, there are a huge number of such organizations and their goals cover a broad range of political and philosophical positions. This can also easily be applied to private schools and athletic organizations.\n\n=== Track II diplomacy ===\n{{Main article|Track II diplomacy}}\nTrack II dialogue, or Track II diplomacy, is transnational coordination that involves non-official members of the government including [[epistemic community|epistemic communities]] as well as former policy-makers or analysts. Track II diplomacy aims to get policymakers and policy analysts to come to a common solution through discussions by unofficial means. Unlike the Track, I diplomacy where government officials, diplomats, and elected leaders gather to talk about certain issues, Track II diplomacy consists of experts, scientists, professors and other figures that are not involved in government affairs. The members of Track II diplomacy can have more freedom to exchange ideas and come up with compromises on their own.\n\n== Activities ==\nThere are numerous classifications of NGOs. The typology the [[World Bank]] uses divides them into Operational and Advocacy.<ref name=\"definition\">[http://docs.lib.duke.edu/igo/guides/ngo/define.htm World Bank Criteria defining NGO] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621135344/http://docs.lib.duke.edu/igo/guides/ngo/define.htm |date=June 21, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nGenerally, NGOs act as implementers, catalysts, and partners. Firstly, NGOs act as implementers, because they mobilize resources in order to provide goods and services to people who are suffering, due to a man-made disaster or a natural disaster. Secondly, NGOs act as catalysts that drive change. They have the ability to \"''inspire, facilitate, or contribute to improved thinking and action to promote change''\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}. Lastly, NGOs often act as partners alongside other organizations in order to tackle problems and address human needs more effectively.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-Governmental Organizations and Development|last=Lewis|first=David|last2=Kanji|first2=Nazneen|publisher=Routledge|year=2009|isbn=978-0415454308|location=Oxon|pages=12\u201313|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nNGOs vary in their methods. Some act primarily as lobbyists, while others primarily conduct programs and activities. For instance, an NGO such as [[Oxfam]], concerned with poverty alleviation, may provide needy people with the equipment and skills to find food and clean [[drinking water]], whereas an NGO like the [[FFDA]] helps through investigation and documentation of human rights{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} violations and provides legal assistance to victims of human rights abuses. Others, such as the [[Afghanistan Information Management Services]], provide specialized technical products and services to support development activities implemented on the ground by other organizations.\n\n=== Operational ===\nOperational NGOs seek to \"achieve small-scale change directly through projects\".<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> They mobilize financial resources, materials, and volunteers to create localized programs. They hold large-scale [[fundraising]] events and may apply to governments and organizations for grants or contracts to raise money for projects. They often operate in a [[Hierarchy|hierarchical]] structure; the main headquarters being staffed by professionals who plan projects, create budgets, keep accounts, and report and communicate with operational fieldworkers who work directly on projects.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Operational NGOs deal with a wide range of issues but are most often associated with the delivery of services or environmental issues, emergency relief, and public welfare. Operational NGOs can be further categorized by the division into relief-oriented versus development-oriented organizations; according to whether they stress service delivery or participation; whether they are religious or secular; and whether they are more public- or private-oriented. Although operational NGOs can be community-based, many are national or international. The defining activity of operational NGOs is the implementation of projects.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Campaigning ===\nCampaigning NGOs seek to \"''achieve large-scale change promoted indirectly through influence of the political system''\".<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Campaigning NGOs need an efficient and effective group of professional members who are able to keep supporters informed, and motivated. They must plan and host demonstrations and events that will keep their cause in the media. They must maintain a large informed network of supporters who can be mobilized for events to garner media attention and influence policy changes. The defining activity of campaigning NGOs is holding demonstrations.<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" /> Campaigning NGOs often deal with issues relating to human rights, women's rights, and children's rights. The primary purpose of an Advocacy NGO is to defend or promote a specific cause. As opposed to operational project management, these organizations typically try to raise awareness, acceptance, and knowledge by lobbying, press work and activist event.<ref name=\" WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Both operational and campaigning ===\nIt is not uncommon for NGOs to make use of both activities. Many times, operational NGOs will use campaigning techniques if they continually face the same issues in the field that could be remedied through policy changes. At the same time, Campaigning NGOs, like human rights organizations often have programs that assist the individual victims they are trying to help through their advocacy work.<ref name=\"WillettsCS-NTWKS\" />\n\n=== Public relations ===\nNon-governmental organizations need healthy relationships with the public to meet their goals. Foundations and charities use sophisticated public relations campaigns to raise funds and employ standard lobbying techniques with governments. Interest groups may be of political importance because of their ability to influence social and political outcomes. A [[Code of Ethics|code of ethics]] was established in 2002 by The World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wango.org/codeofethics.aspx|title=World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations - Code of Ethics and Conduct for NGOs|website=www.wango.org|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\n=== Project management ===\nThere is an increasing awareness that management techniques are crucial to project success in non-governmental organizations.<ref>[http://www.lse.ac.uk/collections/CCS/pdf/int-work-paper4.pdf 100 <!-- application/pdf, 102909 bytes [[Kibibyte|KiB] --> LSE.ac.uk], Mukasa, Sarah. ''Are expatriate staff necessary in international development NGOs? A case study of an international NGO in Uganda.'' Publication of the Centre for Civil Society at the London School of Economics. 2002, p. 11-13.</ref> Generally, private non-governmental organizations have either a community or environmental focus. They address varieties of issues such as religion, emergency aid, or humanitarian affairs. They mobilize public support and voluntary contributions for aid; they often have strong links with community groups in developing countries, and they often work in areas where government-to-government aid is not possible. NGOs are accepted as a part of the international relations landscape, and while they influence national and multilateral policy-making, increasingly they are more directly involved in local action.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Corporate structure ==\n\n=== Staffing ===\nSome NGOs are highly professionalized and rely mainly on paid staff. Others are based around voluntary labor and are less formalized. Not all people working for non-governmental organizations are [[Volunteering|volunteer]]s.\n\nMany NGOs are associated with the use of international staff working in developing countries, but there are many NGOs around the world that rely on local employees or volunteers. There is some dispute as to whether [[expatriate]]s should be sent to developing countries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Frequently this type of personnel is employed to satisfy a [[Donation|donor]] who wants to see the supported project managed by someone from an [[Developed country|industrialized country]]. However, the expertise of these employees or volunteers may be counterbalanced by a number of factors: the cost of [[Alien (law)|foreigners]] is typically higher, they have no [[grassroots democracy|grass-root connections]] in the country they are sent to, and local expertise is often undervalued.<ref name=\"definition\" />\n\nThe NGO sector is an essential employer in terms of numbers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} For example, by the end of 1995, [[Concern Worldwide|CONCERN worldwide]], an international Northern NGO working against poverty, employed 174 expatriates and just over 5,000 national staff working in ten developing countries in [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], and in [[Haiti]].\n\n=== Funding ===\nMajor sources of NGO funding include membership dues, the sale of [[Product (business)|goods]] and services, grants from international institutions or national governments, and private [[donation]]s. \n\nMany NGOs depend heavily on governments for their funding, even though the term \"non-governmental organization\" implies [[independence]] from governments, <ref name=\"global\" /> A quarter of the US$162 million income in 1998 of the [[Famine relief|famine-relief]] organization [[Oxfam]] was donated by the British government and the EU. The Christian relief and development organization [[World Vision United States]] collected US$55 million worth of goods in 1998 from the American government. Several EU-grants provide funds accessible to NGOs.\n\nGovernment funding of NGOs is controversial since, according to David Rieff, writing in ''[[The New Republic]]'', \"the whole point of humanitarian intervention was precise that NGOs and civil society had both a right and an obligation to respond with acts of aid and solidarity to people in need or being subjected to repression or want by the forces that controlled them, whatever the governments concerned might think about the matter.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tnr.com/article/world/75421/ng-uh-o?page=0,0 |title=NG-Uh-O \u2013 The trouble with humanitarianism |author=David Rieff |date=June 10, 2010 |newspaper=The New Republic}}</ref> Some NGOs, such as [[Greenpeace]] do not accept funding from governments or intergovernmental organizations.<ref name=\"HBS\">{{cite web |author=Sarah Jane Gilbert |url=http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/5797.html |title=Harvard Business School, HBS Cases: The Value of Environmental Activists |publisher=Hbswk.hbs.edu |date=2008-09-08 |accessdate=2011-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"GP Annual report 2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.greenpeace.org/raw/content/international/press/reports/international-annualreport-2008.pdf |title=Greenpeace Annual Report 2008 |publisher=Greenpeace.org |year=2008 |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref>\n\nSome NGOs require sizeable funds to operate. For instance, the budget of the [[American Association of Retired Persons]] (AARP) was over US$540 million in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/12687/edition_id/245/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Poll shows power of AIPAC drops slightly|date=1999-12-19|publisher=Jewish News Weekly of Northern California|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref> Funding large budgets demands significant fundraising efforts on the part of most NGOs. \n\n=== Overhead costs ===\n[[Overhead (business)|Overhead]] is the amount of money that is spent on running an NGO rather than on projects.<ref name=Overhead1>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundsforngos.org/budget-for-ngos/defining-terms-budget/ |title=Defining certain terms in a budget |publisher=Funds for NGOs |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> This includes office expenses,<ref name=Overhead1 /> salaries, banking and bookkeeping costs. What percentage of overall budget is spent on overhead is often used to judge an NGO with less than 4% being viewed as good.<ref name=Overhead1 /> The World Association of Non-Governmental Organizations states that ideally more than 86% should be spent on programs (less than 20% on overhead).<ref>{{cite web |title=Code of Ethics & Conduct for NGOs |url=http://www.wango.org/codeofethics/ComplianceManual.pdf |accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]] has specific guidelines on how high overhead can be to receive funding based on how the money is to be spent with overhead often needing to be less than 5\u20137%<ref>{{cite web |title=National NGOs Serving as PRs Excluded from the Global Fund's Policy on Percentage-Based Overhead Costs |url=http://www.aidspan.org/index.php?issue=174&article=2 |year=2012}}</ref>, while the [[World Bank]] typically allows 37%.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Gibbs | first1=Christopher| last2=Fumo|first2=Claudia |last3=Kuby|first3=Thomas |title=Nongovernmental organizations in World Bank supported projects : a review |year=1999 |publisher=World Bank |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-0-8213-4456-9 |page=21 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=77m7ExDp8DQC&pg=PA21 |edition=2nd}}</ref> A high percentage of overhead to total expenditures can make it more difficult to generate funds.<ref>{{cite book |last=Crowther |first=edited by G\u00fcler Aras, David |title=NGOs and social responsibility |year=2010 |publisher=Emerald |location=Bingley, UK |isbn=978-0-85724-295-2 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T9mgFMJQhCsC&pg=PA121 |edition=1st}}</ref> High overhead costs may also generate criticism with some claiming the certain NGOs with high overhead are being run simply to benefit the people working for them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kassahun |first=Samson |title=Social capital for synergistic partnership : development of poor localities in urban Ethiopia |year=2004 |publisher=Cuvillier |location=G\u00f6ttingen |isbn=978-3-86537-222-2 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TSjsfco0elIC&pg=PA153 |edition=1. Aufl.}}</ref>\n\nWhile overhead costs can be a legitimate concern, a sole focus on them can be counterproductive.<ref>Schmitz, Hans Peter and George E. Mitchell 2010. [http://hausercenter.org/iha/2010/03/09/navigating-effectiveness/ Navigating Effectiveness], Humanitarian&Development NGOs Domain Blog, The Hauser Center for Nonprofit Organizations, Harvard University (March 9)</ref> Research published by the Urban Institute and the Center for Social Innovation at Stanford University have shown how rating agencies create incentives for non-profits to lower and hide overhead costs, which may actually reduce organizational effectiveness by starving organizations of the infrastructure they need to effectively deliver services.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.urban.org/publications/311055.html | title=The Pros and Cons of Financial Efficiency Standards| date=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/the_ratings_game/ | title=The Ratings Game (SSIR)}}</ref> A more meaningful rating system would provide, in addition to financial data, a qualitative evaluation of an organization\u2019s transparency and governance:\n\n(1) an assessment of program effectiveness;\n\n(2) and an evaluation of feedback mechanisms designed for donors and beneficiaries;\n\nand (3) such a rating system would also allow rated organizations to respond to an evaluation done by a rating agency.<ref>Lowell, Stephanie, Brian Trelstad, and Bill Meehan. 2005. [http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/the_ratings_game/ The Ratings Game. Evaluating the three groups that rate the Charities]. Stanford Social Innovation Review: 39\u201345.</ref> More generally, the popular discourse of non-profit evaluation should move away from financial notions of organizational effectiveness and toward a more substantial understanding of programmatic impact.\n\n=== Monitoring and control ===\nIn the March 2000 report on United Nations Reform priorities, former UN Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]] wrote in favor of international humanitarian intervention, arguing that the international community has a \"right to protect\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/preventgenocide/rwanda/about/bgresponsibility.shtml |title=Background Information on the Responsibility to Protect \u2014 Outreach Programme on the Rwanda Genocide and the United Nations |publisher=Un.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> citizens of the world against ethnic cleansing, genocide, and crimes against humanity. Following that report, the Canadian government launched the Responsibility to Protect (R2P)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://responsibilitytoprotect.org/ |title=International Coalition for the Responsibility to Protect (ICRtoP) |publisher=Responsibilitytoprotect.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> project, outlining the issue of humanitarian intervention. While the R2P doctrine has wide applications, among the more controversial has been the Canadian government's use of R2P to justify its intervention and support of the coup in Haiti.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Engler |first1=Fenton |last2=Yves |first2=Anthony |title=Canada in Haiti: Waging War on the Poor Majority |year=2005 |publisher=RED Publishing |location=Vancouver, Winnipeg |isbn=978-1-55266-168-0 |page=120 |url=http://www.fernwoodpublishing.ca/Canada-in-Haiti-Yves-Engler-Anthony-Fenton/ |accessdate=2011-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006154741/http://www.fernwoodpublishing.ca/Canada-in-Haiti-Yves-Engler-Anthony-Fenton/ |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}</ref>\n\nYears after R2P, the [[World Federalist Movement]], an organization that supports \"the creation of democratic global structures accountable to the citizens of the world and call for the division of international authority among separate agencies\", has launched Responsibility to Protect \u2013 Engaging Civil Society (R2PCS). A collaboration between the WFM and the Canadian government, this project aims to bring NGOs into lockstep with the principles outlined under the original R2P project.\n\nThe governments of the countries an NGO works or is registered in may require reporting or other monitoring and oversight. Funders generally require reporting and assessment, such information is not necessarily publicly available. There may also be associations and watchdog organizations that research and publish details on the actions of NGOs working in particular geographic or program areas.{{Citation needed|date=September 2007}}\n\nIn recent years, many large corporations have increased their [[corporate social responsibility]] departments in an attempt to preempt NGO campaigns against certain corporate practices. As the logic goes, if corporations work ''with'' NGOs, NGOs will not work ''against'' corporations. Greater collaboration between corporations and NGOs creates inherent risks of [[Co-option|co-optation]] for the weaker partner, typically the non-profit involved.<ref>{{cite journal |year=2012 |title=Corporations and NGOs: When Accountability Leads to Co-optation |journal=Journal of Business Ethics |volume=106 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201321 |doi=10.1007/s10551-011-1057-9|last1=Baur |first1=Dorothea |last2=Schmitz |first2=Hans Peter |url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/312987/files/10551_2011_Article_1057.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, The United States Department of Defense Assistant Secretary of Defense (Health Affairs) [[S. Ward Casscells]] established an [[International Health]] Division under Force Health Protection & Readiness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ha.osd.mil/FHPR/default.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208135444/http://www.ha.osd.mil/fhpr/default.cfm |archivedate=2006-12-08 }}</ref> Part of International Health's mission is to communicate with NGOs in areas of mutual interest. Department of Defense Directive 3000.05,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/300005p.pdf |title=Department of Defense Directive 3000.05 |publisher=United States Department of Defense |date=September 16, 2009 |accessdate=2013-12-24 }}</ref> in 2005, requires DoD to regard stability-enhancing activities as a mission of importance equal to combat. In compliance with [[Geneva conventions|international law]], DoD has necessarily built a capacity to improve essential services in areas of conflict such as [[Iraq]], where the customary lead agencies ([[State Department]] and [[USAID]]) find it difficult to operate. Unlike the \"co-option\" strategy described for corporations, the OASD(HA) recognizes the neutrality of health as an essential service. International Health cultivates collaborative relationships with NGOs, albeit at arm's length, recognizing their traditional independence, expertise, and honest broker status. While the goals of DoD and NGOs may seem incongruent, the DoD's emphasis on stability and security to reduce and prevent conflict suggests, on careful analysis, important mutual interests.\n\n== History ==\nInternational non-governmental organizations have a history dating back to at least the late 18th century.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas |title=NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-938753-3 |page=23 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/ngos-9780199387533}}</ref><ref>Steve Charnovitz, \"Two Centuries of Participation: NGOs and International Governance, Michigan Journal of International Law, Winter 1997.</ref> It has been estimated that by 1914, there were 1083 NGOs.<ref>{{cite book |title=Subcontracting Peace \u2013 The Challenges of NGO Peacebuilding |editor1=Oliver P. Richmond |editor2=Henry F. Carey |publisher=Ashgate |year=2005 |page=21}}</ref> International NGOs were important in the [[abolitionism|anti-slavery movement]] and the movement for [[women's suffrage]] and reached a peak at the time of the [[World Disarmament Conference]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Thomas Richard |title=The Possibilities of Transnational Activism: the Campaign for Disarmament between the Two World Wars |year=2007 |isbn=978-90-04-16258-7}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref> However, the phrase \"non-governmental organization\" only came into popular use with the establishment of the [[United Nations Organization]] in 1945 with provisions in Article 71 of [[Chapter 10 of the United Nations Charter]]<ref>[https://www.un.org/aboutun/charter/chapt10.htm Charter of the United Nations: Chapter X<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040322180234/http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter/chapt10.htm |date=March 22, 2004 }}</ref> for a consultative role for organizations which are neither governments nor member states\u2014see [[Consultative Status]] <ref>[http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1354066108089242 Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cReframing NGOs: The Identity of an International Relations Non-Starter.\u201d ''European Journal of International Relations'' 14 (2008) 2: 231\u2013258. ]</ref>. The definition of \"international NGO\" (INGO) is first given in resolution 288 (X) of ECOSOC on February 27, 1950: it is defined as \"any international organization that is not founded by an international treaty\". The vital role of NGOs and other \"major groups\" in [[sustainable development]] was recognized in Chapter 27<ref>{{cite web |author=United Nations Conference on Environment and Development |url=http://habitat.igc.org/agenda21/a21-27.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030217095008/http://habitat.igc.org/agenda21/a21-27.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-02-17 |title=Agenda 21 \u2013 Chapter 27: Strengthening the Role of Non-governmental Organizations: Partners for Sustainable Development, Earth Summit, 1992 |publisher=Habitat.igc.org |accessdate=2011-12-20 }}</ref> of [[Agenda 21]], leading to intense arrangements for a consultative relationship between the [[United Nations]] and non-governmental organizations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/documents/ecosoc/res/1996/eres1996-31.htm |title=1996/31. Consultative relationship between the United Nations and non-governmental organizations |publisher=Un.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-20}}</ref> It has been observed that the number of INGOs founded or dissolved matches the general \"state of the world\", rising in periods of growth and declining in periods of crisis.<ref>Boli, J. and Thomas, G. M. (1997) World Culture in the World Polity: A century of International Non-Governmental Organization. American Sociological Review. pp. 177</ref>\n\nThe rapid development of the non-governmental sector occurred in western countries as a result of the processes of restructuring of the [[welfare state]]. Further [[globalization]] of that process occurred after the fall of the communist system and was an important part of the [[Washington consensus]].<ref name=\"global\">Pawel Zaleski ''Global Non-governmental Administrative System: Geosociology of the Third Sector'', [in:] Gawin, Dariusz & Glinski, Piotr [ed.]: \"Civil Society in the Making\", IFiS Publishers, Warszawa 2006</ref>\n\nGlobalization during the 20th century gave rise to the importance of NGOs. Many problems could not be solved within a nation. [[Treaty|International treaties]] and international organizations such as the [[World Trade Organization]] were centred mainly on the interests of capitalist enterprises. In an attempt to counterbalance this trend, NGOs have developed to emphasize [[Humanitarianism|humanitarian issues]], [[developmental aid]], and [[sustainable development]]. A prominent example of this is the [[World Social Forum]], which is a rival convention to the [[World Economic Forum]] held annually in January in [[Davos, Switzerland|Davos]], [[Switzerland]]. The fifth World Social Forum in [[Porto Alegre]], [[Brazil]], in January 2005 was attended by representatives from more than 1,000 NGOs.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bartlett |first=Lauren |title=NGO Update |journal=Human Rights Brief |year=2005 |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> In terms of environmental issues and sustainable development, the [[Earth Summit]] in Rio in 1992 was the first to show the power of international NGOs, when about 2,400 representatives of NGOs came to play a central role in deliberations. Some have argued that in forums like these, NGOs take the place of what should belong to the popular movements of the poor. Whatever the case, NGO transnational networking is now extensive.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stone |first=Diane |title=Transfer Agents and Global Networks in the 'Transnationalisation' of Policy |journal=Journal of European Public Policy.austiniskewl |volume=11 |issue=3 |year=2004 |pages=545\u2013566 |doi=10.1080/13501760410001694291|url=http://wrap.warwick.ac.uk/1742/1/WRAP_Stone_JEPP_Transnational_Transfer.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Legal status ==\nThe legal form of NGOs is diverse and depends upon homegrown variations in each country's laws and practices. However, four main family groups of NGOs can be found worldwide:<ref>{{cite book |first=Grant B. |last=Stillman |year=2007 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=icRqqTdl_EIC |title=Global Standard NGOs: The Essential Elements of Good Practice |publisher=Grant B. Stillman |location=Geneva: Lulu |pages=13\u201314}}</ref>\n* Unincorporated and [[voluntary association]]\n* [[Trusts]], [[charities]], and [[Foundation (nonprofit organization)|foundations]]\n* Companies not just for profit\n* Entities formed or registered under special NGO or [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] laws\n\nThe [[Council of Europe]] in [[Strasbourg]] drafted the [[European Convention on the Recognition of the Legal Personality of International Non-Governmental Organizations]] in 1986, which sets a common legal basis for the existence and work of NGOs in Europe. Article 11 of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] protects the right to freedom of association, which is also a fundamental norm for NGOs.\n\n== Influence of NGOs upon world affairs ==\n\nService-delivery NGOs provide public goods and services that governments from developing countries are unable to provide to society, due to lack of resources. Service-delivery NGOs can serve as contractors or collaborate with democratized government agencies to reduce the cost associated with public goods. Capacity-building NGOs influence global affairs differently, in the sense that the incorporation of accountability measures in Southern NGOs affect \"culture, structure, projects and daily operations\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roberts |first1=Susan G. |last2=Jones III |first2=John P. |last3=Frohling |first3=Oliver |title=NGOs and the Globalization of Managerialism: A Research Framework |year=2005 |publisher=World Development |location=Great Britain |doi=10.1016/j.worldev.2005.07.004|page=1846|doi-broken-date=2020-03-25 }}</ref> Advocacy and public education NGOs affects global affairs in its ability to modify behaviour through the use of ideas. Communication is the weapon of choice used by advocacy and public-education NGOs in order to change people's actions and behaviours. They strategically construct messages to not only shape behaviour, but also socially mobilize communities in promoting social, political, or environmental changes. Movement NGOs mobilize the public and coordinate large-scale collective activities to significantly push forward the activism agenda.<ref>{{cite book|first1 =Jacob Mwathi|last1= Mati|first2= Fengshi|last2 = Wu|first3 = Bob|last3= Edwards|first4 = Sherine N. |last4 =El Taraboulsi|first5= David H. |last5 =Smith|date =2016|chapter =24: Social Movement Associations and Activist-Protest Volunteering|title = The Palgrave Handbook of Volunteering, Civic Participation, and Nonprofit Associations|publisher =Palgrave Macmillan|location = London|pages= 516\u2013538 |doi = 10.1007/978-1-137-26317-9_25|isbn= 978-1-137-26316-2}}</ref>\n\nIn the post-Cold War era, more NGOs based in developed countries have pursued international outreach and became involved in local and national level social resistance and become relevant to domestic policy change in the developing world.<ref>{Keck, Margaret, and Kathryn Sikkink, 1998. Activists beyond borders: Advocacy networks in international politics. Ithaca: Cornell University Press.}</ref> In for the cases where national governments are highly sensitive to external influences via non-state actors, specialized NGOs have been able to find the right partners (e.g., China), building up solid working networks, locating a policy niche and facilitating domestic changes. <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wu | first1 = Fengshi | year = 2005 | title = International Non-Governmental Actors in HIV/AIDS Prevention in China | url = | journal = Cell Research | volume = 15 | issue = 11\u201312| pages = 919\u2013922 | doi=10.1038/sj.cr.7290369| pmid = 16354570 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n==International Day==\n===World NGO Day===\n{{main article|World NGO Day}}\n[[File:World NGO Day Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|World NGO Day 2014 in [[Afghanistan]]|alt=World NGO Day 2014 in Afghanistan]]\n{{Quote box|quoted=true|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|salign=center|width=300px|align=left|quote=Today we celebrate the [[World NGO Day]], we celebrate the key civil society's contribution to public space and their unique ability to give voice to those who would have went [sic] otherwise unheard.|source= [[European Union External Action Service]], Official Statement by the [[Spokesperson]] of HR/VP [[Federica Mogherini]] on the occasion of the [[World NGO Day|WORLD NGO DAY]] 2017.- [[Bruxelles]], 27/02/2017 \u2013 ID: 170227_11 '.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eeas.europa.eu/headquarters/headquarters-homepage_en/21535/Statement%20on%20the%20occasion%20of%20the%20World%20NGO%20Day%202017 |title=Statement on the occasion of the World NGO Day 2017 |website=eeas.europa.eu |accessdate=2017-02-27}}</ref>}}\n[[World NGO Day]] is observed annually on 27 February. It was officially recognised and declared on 17 April 2010 by 12 countries of the IX [[Baltic Sea]] NGO Forum to the 8th Summit of the Baltic Sea States in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.3sektorius.lt/forumas/2010/?lng=en&id=5 | title=3sektorius}}</ref> The World NGO Day was internationally marked and recognised on 28 February 2014 in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] by [[Helen Clark]], Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] ([[UNDP]]) and Former [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] who congratulated with the [[World NGO Day]] and highlighted the importance of NGO sector for the [[UN]] through her speech.<ref name=\"unric.org\">{{cite web|url = http://www.unric.org/en/week-ahead-archives/29049-the-week-ahead-at-the-united-nations-the-european-perspective-0714-17-24-february-2014 |title = THE WEEK AHEAD AT THE UNITED NATIONS: THE EUROPEAN PERSPECTIVE (07/14): 17\u201324 February 2014 |publisher = United Nations|accessdate = 14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.finnbay.com/media/news/world-ngo-day-international-celebration-recognition/ | title=Site Unavailable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQwdcSsF0B8|title=Helen Clark on World NGO Day|last=United Nations Development Programme (UNDP)|date=27 February 2014|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\n[[Issa G. Shivji]] is one of Africa's leading experts on law and development issues as an author and academic. His criticism on NGOs is found in two essays: \"Silences in NGO discourse: The role and future of NGOs in Africa\" and \"Reflections on NGOs in Tanzania: What we are, what we are not and what we ought to be\". Shivji argues that despite the good intentions of NGO leaders and activists, he is critical of the \"objective effects of actions, regardless of their intentions\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Shivji |first=Issa G. |title=Silence in NGO discourse: the role and future of NGOs in Africa |year=2007 |publisher=Fahamu |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-9545637-5-2 |page=84}}</ref> Shivji argues also that the sudden rise of NGOs is part of a [[neoliberal]] paradigm, rather than pure altruistic motivations. He is critical of the current manifestations of NGOs wanting to change the world without understanding it, and that the [[Imperialism|imperial]] relationship continues today with the rise of NGOs.\n\nJames Pfeiffer, in his case study of NGO involvement in Mozambique, speaks to the negative effects that NGOs have had on areas of health within the country. He argues that over the last decade, NGOs in Mozambique have \"fragmented the local health system, undermined local control of health programs, and contributed to growing local social inequality\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nHe notes further that NGOs can be uncoordinated, creating parallel projects among different organizations, that pull health service workers away from their routine duties in order to serve the interests of the NGOs. This ultimately undermines local primary health care efforts and takes away the governments' ability to maintain agency over their own health sector.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | last1 = Pfeiffer | first1 = J | year = 2003 | title = International NGOs and primary health care in Mozambique: the need for a new model of collaboration | url = | journal = Social Science & Medicine | volume = 56 | issue = 4| pages = 725\u2013738 | doi=10.1016/s0277-9536(02)00068-0| pmid = 12560007 }}</ref> Pfeiffer suggested a new model of collaboration between the NGO and the DPS (the Mozambique Provincial Health Directorate). He mentioned the NGO should be 'formally held to standard and adherence within the host country', for example, reduce 'showcase' projects and parallel programs that prove to be unsustainable.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n[[Jessica Mathews]] wrote in [[Foreign Affairs]] in 1997: \"For all their strengths, NGOs are special interests. The best of them \u2026 often suffer from tunnel vision, judging every public act by how it affects their particular interest\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/52644/jessica-t-mathews/power-shift |title=Power Shift |journal=Foreign Affairs |issue=January/February 1997 |date=January\u2013February 1997 |author=Jessica T. Mathews |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Since NGOs do not have to worry about policy trade-offs, the overall impact of their cause might bring more harm to society.<ref>Bond, M. (2000) The Backlash against NGOs. [[Prospect (magazine)]].</ref>\n\n[[Vijay Prashad]] argues that from the 1970s \"The World Bank, under Robert McNamara, championed the NGO as an alternative to the state, leaving intact global and regional relations of power and production.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpa.org.au/amrarch/40vp.html |title=Mother Teresa: A Communist View |accessdate=2008-07-24 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724153535/http://www.cpa.org.au/amrarch/40vp.html |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}, Vijay Prashad, ''Australian Marxist Review'', No. 40 August 1998</ref>\n\nOthers argue that NGOs are often imperialist<ref>[http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ Abahlali baseMjondolo''Rethinking Public Participation from below] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322205607/http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ |date=2010-03-22 }}, 'Critical Dialogue', 2006</ref> in nature, that they sometimes operate in a [[racialized]] manner in [[third world]] countries, and that they fulfill a similar function to that of the clergy during the high colonial era. The philosopher [[Peter Hallward]] argues that they are an aristocratic form of politics.<ref>{{cite book|last = Hallward|first= Peter|title = Damming the Flood: Haiti and the Politics of Containment|date = April 2008|publisher = Verso|location =London |isbn= 9781844672349}}</ref> He also points to the fact that NGOs like [[Action Aid]] and [[Christian Aid]] \"effectively condoned the [2004 US backed] coup\" against an elected government in Haiti and argues that they are the \"humanitarian face of imperialism\".<ref>[http://www.tanbou.com/2011/PeterHallwardRespondsToBbcRadio4Program.htm Peter Hallward responds to BBC Radio 4 program on Haiti], ''Tanbou'', 11/01/2011</ref> Popular movements in the global South such as the [[Western Cape Anti-Eviction Campaign]] in [[South Africa]] have sometimes refused to work with NGOs arguing that this will compromise their autonomy.<ref>[http://abahlali.org/files/Oldfield%20&%20Stokke%20WCAEC%20Research%20Report.pdf Building unity in diversity: Social movement activism in the Western Cape Anti-Eviction Campaign], Sophie Oldfield & Kristian Stokke, 2004</ref><ref>[http://www.poormagazine.org/node/2718 Ashraf Cassiem: South African Resistance Against Evictions], Marlon Crump, ''Poor Magazine'', 2009</ref> It has also been argued that NGOs often disempower people by allowing funders to push for stability over social justice.<ref>[http://www.grocotts.co.za/content/are-ngos-enemies-sas-rural-folk-03-07-2013 Are NGOs enemies of SA's rural folk?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922094058/http://www.grocotts.co.za/content/are-NGOs-enemies-sas-rural-folk-03-07-2013 |date=2013-09-22 }}, Youlendree Appasamy, ''Grocott's Mail'', July 2013</ref>\n\nAnother criticism of NGOs is that they are being designed and used as extensions of the normal foreign-policy instruments of certain Western countries and groups of countries.<ref>[http://www.newleftproject.org/index.php/site/article_comments/ngo_the_guise_of_innocence \u2018NGO\u2019: The Guise of Innocence], by Jenny O'Connor, ''New Left Project'', 2012</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/19/fake-rock-plot-spy-russians |title = Britain admits 'fake rock' plot to spy on Russians|work = The Guardian|date =19 January 2012|last1 = Topping|first1 = Alexandra|last2 = Elder |first2 = Miriam}}</ref> Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] made this accusation at the 43rd [[Munich Conference on Security Policy]] in 2007, concluding that these NGOs \"are formally independent but they are purposefully financed and therefore under control\".<ref>{{cite speech |title=Speech and the Following Discussion at the Munich Conference on Security Policy |first=Vladimir |last=Putin |authorlink=Vladimir Putin |event=43rd Munich Conference on Security Policy |location=[[Munich]], [[Germany]] |date=February 10, 2007 |url=http://archive.kremlin.ru/eng/speeches/2007/02/10/0138_type82912type82914type82917type84779_118123.shtml |accessdate=February 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309232547/https://archive.kremlin.ru/eng/speeches/2007/02/10/0138_type82912type82914type82917type84779_118123.shtml |archivedate=March 9, 2012 }}</ref>\nAlso, Michael Bond wrote \"Most large NGOs, such as Oxfam, the Red Cross, Cafod and Action Aid, are striving to make their aid provision more sustainable. But some, mostly in the US, are still exporting the ideologies of their backers.\"<ref>Bond, Michael. \"The Backlash against NGOs.\" Prospect, April 2000, pp.321. Print.</ref>\n\nNGOs have also been accused of using white lies or misinformed advice to enact their campaigns, i.e., accusations that NGOs have been ignorant about critical issues because, as chief scientist at [[Greenpeace]] Doug Parr said, these organizations appear to have lost their efforts in being truly scientific and now seem to be more self-interested. Rather than operating through science to be rationally and effectively practical, NGOs have been accused of abusing the utilization of science to gain their own advantages. In the beginning, as Parr indicated, there was \"a tendency among our critics to say that science is the only decision-making tool \u2026 but political and commercial interests are using science as a cover for getting their way.\"<ref name = bond323>{{citation|last = Bond|first = Michael|title = The Backlash against NGOs|work = Prospect|date = April 2000|page =323|url = https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/thebacklashagainstngos}}</ref> At the same time, NGOs can appear to not be cooperative with other groups, according to the previous policy-maker for the German branch of [[Friends of the Earth]], Jens Katjek. \"If NGOs want the best for the environment\", he says, \"they have to learn to compromise.\"<ref name = bond323/>\n\nNGOs have also been questioned as being \"too much of a good thing\".<ref name = Werker>{{cite journal | last1 = Werker | first1 = Eric | last2 = Ahmed | first2 = Faisal Z. | year = 2008 | title = What Do Nongovernmental Organizations Do? | url = | journal = Journal of Economic Perspectives | volume = 22 | issue = 2| pages = 73\u201392 | doi=10.1257/jep.22.2.73}}</ref> Eric Werker and Faisal Ahmed bring up three potential critiques of the role of NGOs in developing nations: too many NGOs in a nation\u2014particularly one ruled by a warlord\u2014reduces the NGO's ability to establish a credible threat of removing humanitarian assistance since they can easily be replaced by another NGO; the frequent process of resource allocation and outsourcing to local organizations in international development projects results in high expenses for NGOs and rings into question how much of the resources and money actually goes to the intended beneficiaries at the end of the allocation process; and finally, NGO missions tend to be too paternalistic and expensive, though Werker and Ahmed propose that vouchers are a good way to overcome this obstacle.<ref name = Werker/>\n\n=== Challenges to legitimacy ===\nThe issue of the legitimacy of NGOs raises a series of important questions. Legitimacy is one of the most important assets possessed by an NGO and is gained due to them being perceived as an \"independent voice\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Weber | first1 = N. | last2 = Christopherson | first2 = T. | year = 2002 | title = The influence of non-governmental organizations on the creation of Natura 2000 during the European policy process | url = | journal = Forest Policy and Economics | volume = 4 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201312 | doi=10.1016/s1389-9341(01)00070-3}}</ref><ref name=\"2002aHD\">Edwards, M. and Hulme, D. (2002) NGO Performance and Accountability: Introduction and Overview. \"In Edwards, M. and Hulme, D., ed. 2002.\" The Earthscan Reader on NGO Management. UK: Earthscan Publications Ltd. Chapter 11.</ref> Their representation also emerges as an important question. Who bestows responsibilities to NGOs or INGOs and how do they gain the representation of citizens and civil society is still not scrutinized thoroughly. For instance, in the article, it is stated, \"To put the point starkly: are the citizens of countries of the South and their needs represented in global civil society, or are citizens as well as their needs constructed by practices of representation? And when we realize that INGOs hardly ever come face to face with the people whose interests and problems they represent, or that they are not accountable to the people they represent, matters become even more troublesome.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chandhoke | first1 = Neera | year = 2005 | title = How Global Is Global Civil Society? | url = | journal = Journal of World-Systems Research | volume = 11 | issue = 2| pages = 326\u2013327 | doi = 10.5195/JWSR.2005.388 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe origin of funding can have serious implications for the legitimacy of NGOs. NGOs have increased their numbers and range of activities to a level where they have become increasingly dependent on a limited number of donors.<ref name=\"1996HD\">Edwards, M. and Hulme, D. (1996) Too Close for comfort? The impact of official aid on Non-Governmental Organisations. \"World Development.\" 24(6), pp. 961\u2013973.</ref> Consequently, competition has increased for funding, as have the expectations of the donors, who may add conditions that threaten the independence of NGOs.<ref>, Ebrahim, A. (2003) Accountability in practice: Mechanisms for NGOs. \"World Development.\" 31(5), pp.813\u2013829.</ref> An over-dependence on official aid may dilute \"the willingness of NGOs to speak out on issues which are unpopular with governments\".<ref name=2002aHD /> Some commentators have also argued that the changes in NGO funding sources have ultimately altered their functions.<ref name=2002aHD /><ref>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/05/17/mckibbens-divestment-tour/ Brought to You by Wall Street], CORY MORNINGSTAR, ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2013.05.17</ref><ref>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/03/14/350-orgs-friends-on-wall-street/ The Climate Wealth Opportunists], CORY MORNINGSTAR, ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2014.03.14</ref>\n\nNGOs have also been challenged on the grounds that they do not necessarily represent the needs of the developing world, through diminishing the so-called \u201cSouthern Voice\u201d. Some postulate that the [[North\u2013South divide]] exists in the arena of NGOs.<ref name=\"linden\">Lindenberg, M. and Bryant, C. (2001) Going Global: Transforming Relief and Development NGOs. Bloomfield: Kumarian Press.</ref> They question the equality of the relationships between Northern and Southern parts of the same NGOs as well as the relationships between Southern and Northern NGOs working in partnerships. This suggests a division of labor may develop, with the North taking the lead in advocacy and resource mobilization whilst the South engages in service delivery in the developing world.<ref name=linden /> The potential implications of this may mean the needs of the developing world are not addressed appropriately as Northern NGOs do not properly consult or participate in partnerships, such that they assign unrepresentative priorities.<ref>, Jenkins, R. (2001) Corporate Codes of Conduct: Self-Regulation in a Global Economy. \"Technology, Business and Society Programme Paper Number 2.\" United Nations Research Institute for Social Development.</ref>\n\nNGOs are also said to damage the public sector in target countries, e.g. accusations that NGO mismanagement has resulted in the breakdown of public health care systems. Instead of promoting equity and alleviating poverty, NGOs have been under scrutiny for contributing to socioeconomic inequality and dis-empowering services in the public sector of third world countries.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=Patrick-Cockburn>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2014/03/25/how-ngos-failed-afghanistan/ How NGOs Failed Afghanistan], [[Patrick Cockburn]], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 2014.03.25</ref>\n\nThe scale and variety of activities in which NGOs participate have grown rapidly since 1980, particularly since 1990.<ref>Avina, J. (1993) The Evolutionary Life Cycles if Non-Governmental Development Organisations. \"Public Administration and Development.\" 13(5), pp. 453\u2013474.</ref> This has presented NGOs with a need to balance the pressures of centralization and decentralization. By centralizing NGOs, particularly those that operate at an international level, they can assign a common theme or set of goals. Conversely, it may also be advantageous to decentralize to increase the chances of an NGO responding more flexibly and effectively to localized issues by implementing projects, which are modest in scale, easily monitored, produce immediate benefits, and where all involved know that corruption will be punished.<ref name=Patrick-Cockburn /><ref>Anheier, H. and Themudo, N. (2002) Organisational forms of global civil society: Implications of going global. In: Anheier, H. Glasius, M. Kaldor, M, ed 2002.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[List of active non-governmental organizations of national minorities, indigenous and diasporas|List of active NGOs of national minorities]]\n* [[:Category:Non-governmental organizations]]\n* [[Advocacy group]] (interest group)\n* [[Charitable organization]]\n* [[Community foundation]]\n* [[Civil Society Organization]]\n* [[International organization]]\n* [[NGO-ization]]\n* [[Non-profit organization]]\n* [[Track II diplomacy]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1354066108089242 Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cReframing NGOs: The Identity of an International Relations Non-Starter.\u201d ''European Journal of International Relations'' 14 (2008) 2: 231\u2013258. ]\n* Norbert G\u00f6tz. \u201cCivil Society and NGO: Far from Unproblematic Concepts.\u201d ''The Ashgate Research Companion to Non-State Actors''. Bob Reinalda (ed.). Aldershot: Ashgate, 2011. 185\u2013196.\n* Hilton, Matthew et al. eds. ''The Politics of Expertise: How NGOs Shaped Modern Britain'' (2013)\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Watkins | last2 = Cotts | first2 = Susan | last3 = Swidler | first3 = Ann | last4 = Hannan | first4 = Thomas | year = 2012 | title = Outsourcing Social Transformation: Development NGOs as Organizations | journal = Annual Review of Sociology | volume = 38 | issue = | pages = 285\u2013315 | doi=10.1146/annurev-soc-071811-145516}}\n* Davies, T. 2014. NGOs: A New History of Transnational Civil Society. New York: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-938753-3}}.\n* Velusamy M. Non-Governmental Organisation, Dominant Publishers & Distribution Ltd, New Delhi\n* Mark Butler, with Thulani Ndlazi, David Ntseng, Graham Philpott, and Nomusa Sokhela. ''NGO Practice and the Possibility of Freedom'' Church Land Programme, Pietermaritzburg, South Africa 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205081725/http://www.churchland.co.za/upload/files/OccasionalPaperNo3.pdf Churchland.co.za]\n* Olivier Berthoud, ''NGOs: Somewhere between Compassion, Profitability and Solidarity'' [http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/1526 Envio.org.ni], PDF [http://www.edinter.net/docs/ONGBOLEN0102.pdf Edinter.net] Envio, Managua, 2001\n* Terje Tvedt, 19982/2003: Angels of Mercy or Development Diplomats. NGOs & Foreign Aid, Oxford: James Currey\n* Steve W. Witt, ed. Changing Roles of NGOs in the Creation, Storage, and Dissemination of Information in Developing Countries (Saur, 2006). {{ISBN|3-598-22030-8}}\n* Cox, P. N. Shams, G. C. Jahn, P. Erickson, and P. Hicks. 2002. Building collaboration between NGOs and agricultural research iNGOs \u2013 Die Gewerkschaften in Guinea w\u00e4hrend der Unruhen 2007'' \u2013 [[European University Center for Peace Studies|EPU]] Research Papers: Issue 03/07, Stadtschlaining 2007 {{in lang|de}}\n* [[Lyal Sunga|Lyal S. Sunga]], \"Dilemmas facing INGOs in coalition-occupied Iraq\", in Ethics in Action: The Ethical Challenges of International Human Rights Nongovernmental Organizations, edited by Daniel A. Bell and Jean-Marc Coicaud, Cambridge Univ. and United Nations Univ. Press, 2007.\n* [[Lyal Sunga|Lyal S. Sunga]], \"NGO Involvement in International Human Rights Monitoring, International Human Rights Law and Non-Governmental Organizations\" (2005) 41\u201369.\n* Werker & Ahmed (2008): What do Non-Governmental Organizations do?\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Charnovitz | first1 = Steve | year = 1997 | title = Two Centuries of Participation: NGOs and International Governance | url = | journal = Michigan Journal of International Law | volume = 18 | issue = | pages = 183\u2013286 }}\n* Abahlali baseMjondolo [https://web.archive.org/web/20100322205607/http://antieviction.org.za/related-writing-and-resources/rethinking-public-participation-from-below/ ''Rethinking Public Participation from Below''], 'Critical Dialogue', 2006\n* Akpan S. M (2010): Establishment of Non-Governmental Organizations (In Press).\n* Edward A. L. Turner (2010) ''[http://escholarship.org/uc/item/97p470sx Why Has the Number of International Non-Governmental Organizations Exploded since 1960?]'', [[Cliodynamics]], 1, (1).\n* Eugene Fram & Vicki Brown, How Using the Corporate Model Makes a Nonprofit Board More Effective & Efficient \u2013 Third Edition (2011), Amazon Books, Create Space Books.\n* David Lewis and Nazneen Kanji (2009): Non-Governmental Organizations and Development. New York: Routledge.\n* Issa G. Shivji (2007): Silence in NGO Discourse: The Role and Future of NGOs in Africa. Nairobi: Fahamu.\n* Jens Steffek and Kristina Hahn (2010): Evaluating Transnational NGOs: Legitimacy, Accountability, Representation. New York: Palgrave, Macmillan.\n* [[Yearbook of International Organizations]], produced by the [[Union of International Associations]].\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.staff.city.ac.uk/p.willetts/CS-NTWKS/NGO-ART.HTM |title=What is a Non-Governmental Organization? |publisher=City University, London}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQwdcSsF0B8 |title=Video speech \u2013 Helen Clark, Administrator of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) on World NGO Day}}\n\n{{Charity}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Non-governmental organizations| 01]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations]]\n[[Category:Types of organization]]\n[[Category:Civil affairs]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1940s]]\n", "name_user": "Earthianyogi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-governmental_organization"}
{"title_page": "Tyler Roberts", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tyler Roberts\n| image = TylerRoberts2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Tyler D'Whyte Roberts<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/january-2018.ashx |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/01/2018 and 31/01/2018 |publisher=The Football Association |page=8 |format=PDF |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1999|01|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Gloucester]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.80|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/tyler-roberts/ |title=Tyler Roberts |website=worldfootball.net |language=en |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]], [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]], [[attacking midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| clubnumber = 11\n| youthyears1 = 2006\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n| years1 = 2016\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 14\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2017\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 13\n| goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 17\n| goals4 = 5\n| years5 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs5 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps5 = 41\n| goals5 = 6\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam1 = [[Wales national under-17 football team|Wales U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Wales national under-19 football team|Wales U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Wales national under-20 football team|Wales U20]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 5\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| nationalyears5 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 7\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| club-update = 06:09, 1 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 22:21, 13 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Tyler D'Whyte Roberts''' (born 12 January 1999) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and the [[Wales national football team]].\n\nHe is an academy graduate of [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and made his professional debut for the club in May 2016. [[Loan (sports)|Loan]] spells in [[League One]] with [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]], [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] followed before he joined [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] in January 2018. He also made his senior Wales debut in 2018, having previously represented the nation at various youth levels.\n\nA versatile forward, he can play as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]], [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] or as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]].\n\n==Club career==\n===West Bromwich Albion===\n====Early career====\nHaving spotted him playing for junior side Tredworth Tigers at a Gloucester Festival, [[West Bromwich Albion|West Brom]] decided to sign Roberts for their academy when he was just seven years old.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35312778 |title=Tyler Roberts: West Brom give teenager professional contract |date=14 January 2016 |access-date=25 April 2016 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> Having then gone on to represent the club at age group level, Roberts was named on West Brom's bench for the first time on the final day of the [[2014\u201315 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. However, he did not make it on to the pitch.<ref name=\"WO\">{{Cite news |last=Southcombe |first=Matthew (26 May 2015) |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-tyler-roberts-meet-16-year-old-9330298 |title=Who is Tyler Roberts? Meet the 16-year-old West Brom sensation who has been called up to train with Wales |work=Wales Online |access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref> Following Roberts' inclusion in the squad, he was listed by ''[[Match of the Day]]'' magazine as one of the 20 wonder-kids to look out for in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Suart |first=Paul (7 January 2016) |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/west-broms-tyler-roberts-more-10702084 |title=West Brom's Tyler Roberts: More recognition for Albion's next big prospect |work=Birmingham Mail |access-date=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2016, just two days after his 17th birthday, Roberts signed his first professional contract with West Brom, putting pen to paper on a {{frac|2|1|2}}-year contract.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wba.co.uk/news/article/albion-west-brom-tyler-roberts-professional-contract-2900604.aspx |title=Talented Roberts pens pro deal |date=14 January 2016 |access-date=25 April 2016 |publisher=West Bromwich Albion}}</ref> He made his [[Premier League]] debut for the club on the final day of the [[2015\u201316 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]] in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], coming on as a second-half [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] for fellow Albion academy graduate [[Jonathan Leko]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=White |first=Jim (15 May 2016) |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/05/15/west-brom-1-liverpool-1-forgettable-draw-leaves-liverpools-europ/ |title=West Brom 1 Liverpool 1: Forgettable draw leaves Liverpool's European hopes on the brink |access-date=15 May 2016 |website=Telegraph}}</ref> Shortly after coming on, Roberts was [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)#yellow card (caution)|booked]] for a rash challenge on Liverpool captain [[Jordan Henderson]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/west-bromwich-albion-fc/2016/05/15/west-brom-1-liverpool-1-report/ |title=West Brom 1 Liverpool 1 \u2013 Report and pictures |date=15 May 2016 |access-date=15 May 2016 |website=Albion Express & Star}}</ref> Upon making his debut, Roberts became only the second player born in 1999 to play in the Premier League, following on from teammate Leko who had done so the month before.\n\n====2016\u201317 season: Loans to Oxford United and Shrewsbury Town====\nOn 28 July 2016, Roberts joined [[League One]] side [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on a six-month [[loan (sports)|loan]] deal until January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oufc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/oxford-united-west-brom-roberts-3211933.aspx |title=West Brom youngster joins the U's |date=28 July 2016 |publisher=Oxford United |access-date=28 July 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on the opening day of the [[2016\u201317 Oxford United F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]], coming off the bench for [[Chris Maguire]] in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/chesterfield-fc/oxford-united-1-chesterfield-1-ched-evans-cracker-earns-spireites-a-point-1-8054893 |title=Oxford United 1 Chesterfield 1: Ched Evans cracker earns Spireites a point |date=6 August 2016 |access-date=7 August 2016 |website=The Star}}</ref> His [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] debut came the following week when he entered the field of play as an [[Overtime (sports)|extra-time]] [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] in Oxford's 1\u20130 win over [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/live-football-score/birmingham-city-vs-oxford-united-capital-one-cup-2016-17 |title=Birmingham City vs Oxford United Live Score and Commentary, Capital One Cup 2016\u201317 |date=9 August 2016 |access-date=10 August 2016 |website=Sportskeeda}}</ref> He then scored his first goal for the club, and the first professional goal of his career, in a 4\u20132 victory over [[League Two]] club [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] in the [[2016\u201317 EFL Trophy]] on 30 August.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pritchard |first=David |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/sport/oxfordunited/14713138.Small_Checkatrade_Trophy_gate_at_Oxford_United_cannot_take_gloss_off_Tyler_Roberts_s_first_professional_goal/ |title=Small Checkatrade Trophy gate at Oxford United cannot take gloss off Tyler Roberts's first professional goal |date=30 August 2016 |work=Oxford Mail |access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> On 5 November, Roberts made his [[FA Cup]] debut and scored in a 5\u20130 win over [[Merstham F.C.|Merstham]] of the [[Isthmian League]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Amofa |first=Richard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/11/05/merstham-0-oxford-united-5-clinical-visitors-display-class-on-an/ |title=Merstham 0 Oxford United 5: Clinical visitors display class on and off the pitch |date=5 November 2016 |access-date=6 November 2016 |website=Telegraph}}</ref> A month later, on 6 December, he scored the winning penalty in a shootout against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], after a 1\u20131 draw in the second round of the EFL Trophy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pritchard |first=David |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/sport/oxfordunited/14950749.Tyler_Roberts_holds_his_nerve_as_Oxford_United_make_it_third_time_lucky_with_shoot_out_win_over_Southend/ |title=Tyler Roberts holds his nerve as Oxford United make it third time lucky with shoot-out win over Southend |date=7 December 2016 |work=Oxford Mail |access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Oxford [[Manager (association football)|manager]] [[Michael Appleton]] lodged a request to West Brom to extend Roberts' loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pritchard |first=David |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/sport/14953921.Oxford_United_make_request_to_West_Bromwich_Albion_for_Tyler_Roberts_loan_extension/ |title=Oxford United make request to West Bromwich Albion for Tyler Roberts loan extension |date=8 December 2016 |access-date=13 December 2016 |website=Oxford Mail}}</ref> However, on 17 January 2017, Roberts  joined fellow League One side [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38651116 |title=Tyler Roberts: Shrewsbury Town sign West Bromwich Albion striker on loan |date=17 January 2017 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref> He made his debut for the club four days later, starting in a 1\u20130 league win over [[Oldham Athletic F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/01/21/shrewsbury-town-1-oldham-0-report/ |title=Shrewsbury Town 1 Oldham 0 - Report and pictures |date=21 January 2017 |website=Shropshire Star |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> Roberts scored his first goal for the club, and his first in league football, on 4 February when he netted the opener in a 2\u20131 win over [[Bury F.C.|Bury]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/02/04/paul-hurst-hails-star-shrewsbury-town-striker-tyler-roberts-in-win-over-bury/ |title=Paul Hurst hails star Shrewsbury Town striker Tyler Roberts in win over Bury |date=4 February 2017 |website=Shropshire Star |access-date=5 February 2017}}</ref> On 4 April, Roberts suffered a hamstring injury in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] that saw his stint at Shrewsbury come to an end.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/04/21/shrewsbury-town-may-call-on-injured-tyler-roberts/ |title=Shrewsbury Town may call on injured Tyler Roberts |date=21 April 2017 |website=Shropshire Star |access-date=24 April 2017}}</ref> He ended the campaign with four goals and two [[Assist (football)|assists]] for the club as they narrowly avoided relegation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/05/19/tyler-roberts-will-always-hold-shrewsbury-town-in-his-heart/ |title=Tyler Roberts will always hold Shrewsbury Town in his heart |date=19 May 2017 |website=Shropshire Star |access-date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season: Loan to Walsall====\nOn 25 August 2017, Roberts left West Brom on loan once again, joining League One side [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] for the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41054998 |title=Tyler Roberts: Walsall sign West Bromwich Albion forward on loan |date=25 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> The following day, he scored one goal and [[Assist (football)|assisted]] another on debut against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], helping Walsall come from 3\u20130 down to earn a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40983705 |title=Walsall 3\u20133 Bradford |date=26 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> He went on to score five goals in 17 appearances before being recalled by West Brom at the half-way mark of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/tyler-roberts-contract-west-brom-14219390 |title=Revealed: The latest on Tyler Roberts' West Brom future amid Leeds and Rangers links |last=Suart |first=Paul |date=30 January 2018 |website=Birmingham Mail |access-date=30 January 2018}}</ref> Upon completing his loan spell at [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]], Roberts was linked with a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman]] move to [[Serie A]] side [[AC Milan]] who had been scouting the player.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/soccer-transfers/story/3360606/ac-milansampdoria-and-torino-track-west-brom-striker-tyler-roberts |title=AC Milan, Sampdoria and Torino track West Brom striker Tyler Roberts |date=26 January 2018 |website=ESPN Sport |access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Leeds United===\nRoberts' return to West Brom was short-lived, however, as the arrival of [[Daniel Sturridge]] on loan from Liverpool limited his first team chances further. As a result, on the final day of the January transfer market, he signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side, [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on a four-and-a-half-year deal for an undisclosed fee believed to be around an initial \u00a32.5 million potentially rising to \u00a34 million depending on clauses.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22954/leeds-complete-tyler-roberts-transfer |title=Leeds Complete Tyler Roberts Transfer |access-date=31 January 2018 |publisher=Leeds United FC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11715/11230548/leeds-sign-tyler-roberts-from-west-brom-on-three-and-a-half-year-deal |title=Leeds sign Tyler Roberts from West Brom on three-and-a-half-year deal |access-date=31 January 2018 |publisher=Sky Sports News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-summer-returns-likely-for-injured-whites-pair-1-9094079 |title=Leeds United: Summer returns likely for injured Whites pair |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaving recovered from a minor knock which he arrived at the club with, Roberts looked set to make his debut in the middle of February. However, on 14 February, new club manager [[Paul Heckingbottom]] revealed that he had cracked his shin bone upon his return in training and would be ruled out for several weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/tyler-roberts-set-first-leeds-14282787 |title=Tyler Roberts set for first Leeds United start since signing from West Brom |last=Wollaston |first=Steve |date=13 February 2018 |website=Birmingham Mail |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/23015/tyler-roberts-picks-up-injury |title=Tyler Roberts Picks up Injury |access-date=14 February 2018 |publisher=Leeds United}}</ref> He ultimately missed the remainder of the season through the injury.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Urquhart |first=Joe |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/paul-heckingbottom-reveals-what-tyler-roberts-will-bring-to-leeds-united-1-9151641 |title=Paul Heckingbottom reveals what Tyler Roberts will bring to Leeds United |date=5 May 2018 |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |access-date=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter spending several months on the sidelines, Roberts made his unofficial debut as a second-half substitute during a pre-season friendly against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/southend |title=Southend United Vs Leeds United |date=22 July 2018 |access-date=22 July 2018 |publisher=Leeds United}}</ref> His full debut followed on 14 August when started for Leeds in an [[EFL Cup]] fixture against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/match |title=Leeds United vs Bolton |date=14 August 2018 |access-date=14 August 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814232818/https://www.leedsunited.com/match |archive-date=14 August 2018 |publisher=Leeds United}}</ref> The following month, he made his league debut in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] and scored his first goals for the club three days later, scoring a brace in a 3\u20130 victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45456100 |title=Leeds stay unbeaten with Millwall Draw |date=15 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45479784 |title=Leeds Cruise Past Preston to stay top |date=18 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=18 September 2018}}</ref> On 1 March he assisted [[Patrick Bamford]] twice in a 4\u20130 victory over former club [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], with Roberts receiving the man of the match award playing in an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] position.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/47379196 |title=Relive Leeds' 4-0 win over West Brom |date=2019-02-27 |access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of three players nominated for the clubs end of season awards for Young Player Of The Season alongside [[Jamie Shackleton]] and [[Jack Clarke (footballer, born 2000)|Jack Clarke]], but lost out on the award on 28 April, with Clarke winning the award for Young Player Of The Season at the clubs annual ceremony.<ref name=\"Awards\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/24912/player-of-the-year-2019-winners |title=PLAYER OF THE YEAR 2019 WINNERS |date=28 April 2018 |publisher=Leeds United F.C |access-date=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nRoberts played 32 games scoring 3 goals in all competitions, after Leeds finished the regular season in third place after dropping out of the automatic promotion places with 3 games left after a defeat to 10 man [[Wigan Athletic]] on 19 April,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47904094 |title=Leeds 1 Wigan 2 |date=19 April 2019 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref> Leeds qualified for the playoffs, however Roberts missed the final games of the season due to injury,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/leeds-united-handed-double-injury-2849659 |title=Leeds United handed double injury blow ahead of play-off clash with Derby County |date=9 May 2019 |publisher=Derbyshire Live}}</ref> including missing the semi-final playoffs matches versus sixth-placed [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], as Leeds were beaten on 3\u20134 aggregate over the two legs. Despite taking a 1\u20130 win at Pride Park, to bring into a 1-0 aggregate lead into the home leg at Elland Road, Leeds lost 2\u20134 in an encounter that saw both teams reduced to 10 men and Derby progress to the final against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48196167 |title=Leeds United 2\u20134 Derby County (Derby win 4\u20133 on agg) |date=15 May 2019 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nRoberts ended up missing all the 2019\u201320 pre-season games and the start of the new season after undergoing knee surgery during May 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/leeds-united-s-tyler-roberts-misses-out-on-wales-squad-after-knee-operation-1-9793368 |title=Leeds United's Tyler Roberts misses out on Wales squad after knee operation |date=29 May 2019 |publisher=YEP}}</ref> He returned from injury against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Chartlon Athletic]] on 28 September 2019, before scoring his first goal of the season against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in a 2\u20130 win on 2 November 2019,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/leeds-vs-qpr/409523 |title=Leeds United 2 QPR 0 |date=4 November 2019 |publisher=A=Sky Sports}}</ref> however Roberts picked up an injury against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] on 26 November. He returned from injury as a substitute in Leeds' 4\u20135 win against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 29 December 2019,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50882301 |title=Birmingham City 4-5 Leeds United: Bielsa's men beat Blues |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> but picked up a hamstring injury in the same game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/latest-leeds-united-news/marcelo-bielsa-reveals-four-leeds-united-changes-arsenal-fa-cup-clash-and-issues-whites-injury-update-1355384 |title=Marcelo Bielsa reveals four Leeds United changes for Arsenal FA Cup clash and issues Whites injury update |date=4 January 2020 |website=Yorkshire Evening Post |language=English |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> The injury kept him out of the team until early February and, coming on as a 67th-minute substitute for striker [[Patrick Bamford]] on the 29th of that month, with Leeds two-nil ahead at [[Hull City F.C.|Hull]], Roberts put the game beyond doubt with the two final goals of the game within four minutes of each other \u2013 his first brace of the season and his second in a Leeds shirt.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51547861 |title=Hull 0-4 Leeds |date=29 February 2020 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Welsh national youth teams===\nThough he represented [[England national football team|England]], his country of birth, at schoolboy level, Roberts later elected to play for [[Wales national football team|Wales]] instead, qualifying for selection as two of his grandparents are Welsh.<ref name=\"BM\">{{Cite news |last=Stuart |first=Paul (5 January 2016) |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/tyler-roberts-lowdown-west-broms-10684923 |title=Tyler Roberts: The lowdown on West Brom's next great hope |work=Birmingham Mail |access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he captained the [[Wales national under-16 football team|Wales U16]] side to glory in the [[Victory Shield]], scoring in the final against [[Northern Ireland national under-16 football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref name=\"BBC1\" /> The result was Wales' first outright triumph in the competition since the 1948/49 edition.<ref name=\"FAW\">{{Cite news |url=http://contentfaw.aws-skybrid.co.uk/en/news/wales-beat-n-ireland-be-crowned-2014-victory-shield-champions/ |title=Wales beat N.Ireland to be Crowned 2014 Victory Shield Champions |date=21 November 2014 |access-date=16 May 2016 |website=Wales Football Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Jones |first=Dave  (21 November 2014) |url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/victory-shield-northern-ireland-u16s-8147717 |title=Wales clinch title for the first time since 1948/49 |access-date=16 May 2016 |website=Daily Post}}</ref> Having trained with the senior side in between, he returned to the U16 side in November the following year and was part of the squad which retained the Victory Shield title.<ref name=\"SWA\">{{Cite news |last=Penman |first=Andrew (5 November 2015) |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/13948019.Wales_under_16s_retain_Victory_Shield_in_Newport/ |title=Wales under-16s retain Victory Shield in Newport |access-date=17 May 2016 |website=South Wales Argus}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, following the conclusion of the League One season, he was included in [[Rob Page|Robert Page]]'s squad for the [[2017 Toulon Tournament]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39923634 |title=Toulon Tournament: Wales U20 without Liverpool's Ben Woodburn and Harry Wilson |date=16 May 2017 |website=BBC |access-date=18 May 2017}}</ref> After making his debut for the side in the tournament opener against [[Ivory Coast national under-20 football team|Ivory Coast]], Roberts made one further appearance, against [[France national under-20 football team|France]], as Wales were eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.festival-foot-espoirs.com/direct_festival_foot_uk.php?tournoi_id=15 |title=Wales U20 2\u20132 Cote D'Ivoire |publisher=Foot Espoirs |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601021623/http://www.festival-foot-espoirs.com/direct_festival_foot_uk.php?tournoi_id=15 |archive-date=1 June 2017 |access-date=16 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40100903 |title=Toulon Tournament: France U20 0-0 Wales U20 |date=30 May 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=16 June 2017}}</ref> On 1 September, he made his debut for the [[Wales national under-21 football team|under-21]] side and scored the opening goal in a 3\u20130 victory over [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/09/01/europe/uefa-u21-championship/switzerland-under-21/wales-under-21/2429856/ |title=Switzerland U21 0\u20133 Wales U21 |publisher=Soccerway |access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41131406 |title=Switzerland U21 0\u20133 Wales U21 |date=1 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Senior Wales national team===\nIn May 2015, Roberts, along with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] winger [[Harry Wilson (footballer, born 1997)|Harry Wilson]], was called up by Wales manager [[Chris Coleman (footballer)|Chris Coleman]] to train with the senior squad.<ref name=\"WO\" /><ref name=\"BM\" /> In March 2017 he was named as a stand-by player for Wales' [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group D|World Cup qualifier]] against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39285564 |title=Tyler Roberts: West Brom forward commits international future to Wales |date=21 March 2017 |website=BBC |access-date=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe received his first full call-up in August 2018 when he was named in [[Ryan Giggs]]' squad for the nation's [[UEFA Nations League]] matches against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=O'Callaghan |first=Rory |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12018/11484779/paul-dummett-named-in-wales-squad-to-face-ireland-and-denmark |title=Paul Dummett named in Wales squad to face Ireland and Denmark |date=29 August 2018 |access-date=30 August 2018 |publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> His debut followed against the former on 6 September, coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Gareth Bale]] in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Ger |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/ireland-v-wales-moments-that-mattered-867325.html |title=Ireland v Wales \u2013 Moments that mattered |date=6 September 2018 |work=Irish Examiner |access-date=7 September 2018}}</ref> The following month, on 16 October 2018, Roberts was handed his first Wales start as the Republic of Ireland were again beaten 0\u20131 in [[Dublin]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/16987289.ryan-giggs-wants-wales-to-win-nations-league-group/ |title=Ryan Giggs challenges Wales to finish the job against Denmark |website=South Wales Argus |access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 29 February 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!League!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n|[[2015\u201316 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"15/16 appearances\">{{Soccerbase season|82907|2015|name=Tyler Roberts|access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|1||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] (loan)\n|[[2016\u201317 Oxford United F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"16/17 appearances\">{{Soccerbase season|82907|2016|name=Tyler Roberts|access-date=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|14||0||3||1||2||0||3||1||22||2\n|-\n|[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] (loan)\n|[[2016\u201317 Shrewsbury Tow