eam!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n|2012||1||0\n|-\n|2013||4||1\n|-\n|2014||0||0\n|-\n|2015||3||0\n|-\n|2016||6||0\n|-\n|2017||3||0\n|-\n|2018||5||1\n|-\n|2019||6||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total||28||5\n|}\n\n====International goals====\n:''Scores and results list Colombia's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Final !! Competition\n|-\n|1. || 6 February 2013 || [[Sun Life Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens]], United States || {{fb|GUA}} ||align=center| '''4'''\u20131 ||align=center| 4\u20131 || rowspan=\"5\"| [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n|2. || 23 March 2018 || [[Stade de France]], [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]], France || {{fb|FRA}} ||align=center| '''1'''\u20132 ||align=center| 3\u20132\n|-\n|3. || 3 June 2019 || [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]], [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia || {{fb|PAN}} ||align=center| '''2'''\u20130 ||align=center| 3\u20130\n|-\n|4. || rowspan=\"2\"| 6 September 2019|| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Hard Rock Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens]], United States || rowspan=\"2\"| {{fb|BRA}} ||align=center| '''1'''\u20131 ||rowspan=2 align=center| 2\u20132\n|-\n|5. || align=center| '''2'''\u20131\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===National===\n'''Colombia U20'''\n*[[Toulon Tournament]]: [[2011 Toulon Tournament|2011]]<ref>https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/en/smartphone/festival/detail_actualite.php?id=2939</ref>\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Gran Gal\u00e0 del Calcio#Serie A Best Young Revelation|Serie A Best Young Revelation]]: 2012<ref name=\"ran Gal\u00e0 del Calcio Aic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/2013/01/27-242192/Gran+Gal%C3%A0+del+Calcio+LIVE.+Agnelli%3A+Polemiche+normali|title=Gran Gal\u00e0 del Calcio Aic. E' Pirlo il migliore del 2012|publisher=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=27 January 2013|accessdate=25 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425230250/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/2013/01/27-242192/Gran+Gal%C3%A0+del+Calcio+LIVE.+Agnelli%3A+Polemiche+normali|archivedate=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|luis-fernando-muriel-fruto/83929}}\n*{{BDFutbol|8671}}\n*{{FIFA player|339731}}\n\n{{Atalanta B.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Colombia squads\n|bg         = #FCD116\n|fg         = #003893\n|bordercolor= #CE1126\n|list1=\n{{Colombia squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Colombia squad 2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muriel, Luis}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombian footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Cali footballers]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Granada CF footballers]]\n[[Category:U.S. Lecce players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla FC players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:Atalanta B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:People from Atl\u00e1ntico Department]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours:Cleanup.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luis_Muriel"}
{"title_page": "RIA Novosti", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|Russian state-operated domestic (and former international) news agency}}\n{{Coord|55|44|15.38|N|37|35|24.92|E|region:US_dim:540|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name = [[FSUE]] Russian Agency of International Information \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb<br />([[FSUE]] RAMI \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb)\n|logo = RIA Novosti.png\n|logo_size = 200px\n|type = [[Federal State Unitary Enterprise]]\n|foundation = {{Start date|df=yes|1941|06}} (as [[Soviet Information Bureau|Sovinformburo]])\n|successor = [[Rossiya Segodnya]], [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]], ria.ru\n|defunct = 1 April 2014\n|location = [[Zubovsky Boulevard]] 4, [[Moscow]], Russia\n|key_people = [[Svetlana Mironyuk]]\n|revenue =\n|industry = News media\n|products = [[News agency|Wire service]]\n|owner= [[Rossiya Segodnya]] (which is owned and operated by [[Government of Russia|federal government]] (as [[unitary enterprise]]))\n|operating_income =\n|net_income =\n|num_employees =\n|parent =\n|subsid =\n|footnotes =\n|homepage = {{URL|https://ria.ru}} (Russian version)<br />{{URL|https://sputniknews.com|SputnikNews.com}} (English version)\n}}\n'''RIA Novosti''' ({{lang-ru|\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}), sometimes '''RIA''' ({{lang-ru|\u0420\u0418\u0410}}) for short, was a [[Russia|Russian]] state-operated domestic [[news agency]], which used to be one of Russia's international [[news agencies]] until 2013.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/country_profiles/1102275.stm#media Country profile: Russia \u2013 Media], BBC News, last updated 6 March 2012.</ref> Operating under the purview of the Russian [[Ministry of Communications and Mass Media (Russia)|Ministry of Communications and Mass Media]], RIA Novosti is headquartered in [[Moscow]] and operated about 80 bureaus internationally. On 9 December 2013 [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] [[Decree of the President of Russia|ordered]] RIA Novosti's liquidation and the creation of a Russian international news agency [[Rossiya Segodnya]].<ref name=PutinL>{{cite web|title=\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u043e \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u044d\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u041c\u0418|url=http://www.kremlin.ru/acts/19805|publisher=[[Kremlin.ru]]}}</ref> [[Dmitry Konstantinovich Kiselev|Dmitry Kiselev]], an anchorman of the [[Russia-1 (TV channel)|Russia-1]] channel was appointed to be the first president of the new information agency.<ref name=LentaL>{{cite news|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/12/09/ria/|newspaper=[[Lenta.ru|Lenta]]|date=9 December 2013}}</ref> RIA Novosti was scheduled to be closed down in 2014; starting in March 2014, staff were informed that they had the option of transferring their contracts to Rossiya Segodnya or accepting voluntary redundancy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ria Novosti Preps For Change|url=http://www.sptimes.ru/story/39333?page=1#top|publisher=[[The St. Petersburg Times]]|date=12 March 2014}}</ref> On 10 November 2014, Rossiya Segodnya launched the [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] multimedia platform as the international replacement of RIA Novosti and [[Voice of Russia]]. Within Russia itself, however, Rossiya Segodnya continues to operate its Russian language news service under the name RIA Novosti with its ria.ru website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/204231-sputnik-news-agency-launched/|title=Sputnik launched to news orbit: Russia\u2019s new intl media to offer alternative standpoint|website=RT International}}</ref>\n\nThe agency published news and analysis of social-political, economic, scientific and financial subjects on the Internet and via e-mail in the main European languages, as well as in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[Arabic language|Arabic]].<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|author=11 March 2014 0:18 |url=http://www.rianovosti.com/docs/about/novosti.html |title=The Russian News & Information Agency RIA Novosti |publisher=Rianovosti.com |accessdate=10 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928023413/http://rianovosti.com/docs/about/novosti.html |archivedate=28 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"arabic\">{{cite web|url=http://anbamoscow.com/ |title=RIA Arabic |publisher=Anbamoscow.com |date=14 December 2012 |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> It had a correspondent network in the [[Russian Federation]], [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]] and over 40 non-CIS countries.<ref name=\"about\"/> Its clients include the presidential administration, Russian government, Federation Council, [[State Duma]], leading ministries and government departments, administrations of Russian regions, representatives of Russian and foreign business communities, diplomatic missions, and public organizations.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nRIA Novosti was an award-winning news agency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.rian.ru/agency_news/20121122/177670392.html |title=RIA Novosti wins five Runet awards &#124; Agency News &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date=22 November 2012 |accessdate=10 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119105324/http://en.rian.ru/agency_news/20121122/177670392.html |archive-date=19 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The last editor-in-chief of RIA Novosti was [[Svetlana Mironyuk]],<ref name=\"about\"/> the first woman appointed to the role in the agency's history. According to the organisation's Charter, enterprise's property was federally owned (because federal [[unitary enterprise]]) and was indivisible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fapmc.ru/rospechat/rospechat/lwr/unitar/item130.html |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u044c - \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \"\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u041e\u0412\u041e\u0421\u0422\u0418\" |publisher=Fapmc.ru |date= |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.fapmc.ru/dms-static/affccc2c-7683-4c32-a917-68b82ed8f099.pdf</ref> According to the agency, it was partially government-subsidized (2.7\u20132.9 billion [[Russian rouble|roubles]] in 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ria.ru/economy/20121108/910092565.html |title=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0434\u0443\u043c\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b \u0443\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432 &#124; \u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |publisher=Ria.ru |date= |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>), but maintained full editorial independence.<ref>{{cite web |author=11 March 2014 0:18 |url=http://www.en.rian.ru/docs/about/novosti.html |title=RIA Novosti &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |accessdate=10 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001061437/http://www.en.rian.ru/docs/about/novosti.html |archive-date=1 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIts Russian name was '''[[Federal State Unitary Enterprise]] Russian Agency of International Information \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb''' ({{lang-ru|\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u00ab\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u00bb, Federal'noye Gosudarstvennoye Unitarnoye Predpyatye Rossiyskoye Agentsvo Mezhdunarodnoy Informatsii}}), ''[[Unitary enterprise|FGUP]] RAMI \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb'' ({{lang-ru|\u0424\u0413\u0423\u041f \u0420\u0410\u041c\u0418 \u00ab\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u00bb}}) for short. Its formal English name was '''Russian News & Information Agency \"RIA Novosti\"'''. Early in 1990s it had the name '''state enterprise RIA \u00abNovosti\u00bb''' (named after Soviet ''Press Agency \u00abNovosti\u00bb'' and ''Information Agency \u00abNovosti\u00bb''). ''RIA'' means ''Russian Information Agency'' and ''Novosti'' means ''News'' in Russian. The common abbreviation in Russian is RIA.\n\n==History==\nRIA Novosti's history dates back to 24 June 1941, when by a resolution of the [[Government of the Soviet Union|USSR Council of People's Commissars]] and the Communist Party Central Committee, \"''On the Establishment and Tasks of the Soviet Information Bureau''\", the [[Soviet Information Bureau]] (Sovinformburo) was set up under the USSR Council of People's Commissars and the Central Committee. Its main task was to oversee work to cover international, military events and the events of the country's domestic life in periodicals and on the radio (from 14 October 1941, to 3 March 1942, was based in Kuibyshev \u2013 modern-day Samara).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe bureau's main task was to compile reports on the situation on the frontline of the war, work on the home front, and the partisan movement for the radio, newspapers and magazines. Sovinformburo directed the activity of the All-Slavonic Committee, Anti-Nazi Committee of Soviet Women, Anti-Nazi Committee of the Soviet Youth, Anti-Nazi Committee of Soviet Scientists, and the Jewish Anti-Nazi Committee. In 1944, a special bureau on propaganda for foreign countries was set up as part of Sovinformburo.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThrough 1,171 newspapers, 523 magazines and 18 radio stations in 23 countries, Soviet embassies abroad, friendship societies, trade unions, women's, youth and scientific organizations, Sovinformburo informed readers and listeners about the struggle of the Soviet people against Nazism and in the post-war years about the main areas of Soviet domestic and foreign policies.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nSovinformburo heads included [[Aleksandr Shcherbakov (politician)|A.S. Shcherbakov]] (1941\u201345), [[Solomon Lozovsky|S. A. Lozovsky]] (1945\u201348) and Y.S. Khavinson, D.A. Polikarpov.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n[[File:Newspaper stall and women in East Berlin, with person in wheelchair, 1984.jpg|thumb|right|Novosti operated this East Berlin [[news stall]] in 1984.]]\nIn 1961, the Novosti Press Agency (APN) succeeded Sovinformburo. It became the leading information and press body of [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] public organizations. The constituent conference was held on 21 February 1961. The conference of representatives of Soviet public organizations adopted a decision to create a press agency of public organizations named Novosti. The agency's guiding body was the Council of the Agency's Founders.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe APN founders were the USSR Journalists Union, USSR Writers Union, Union of Soviet Societies of Friendship and Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, and the Znaniye Society. On 3 April 1961, the Agency charter was adopted. Under its charter, APN's aim was \"to contribute to mutual understanding, trust and friendship among peoples in every possible way by broadly publishing accurate information about the USSR abroad and familiarizing the Soviet public with the life of the peoples of foreign countries.\" APN's motto was \"Information for Peace, for the Friendship of Nations\". APN had bureaus in over 120 countries. The Agency published 60 illustrated newspapers and magazines in 45 languages with a one-time circulation of 4.3 million copies. With the Union of Soviet Friendship Societies, APN published the newspaper, ''Moscow News'', which in September 1990 became an independent publication. APN Publishing House put out over 200 books and booklets with a total annual circulation of 20 million copies. In 1989, a TV center opened in APN. Later, it was transformed into the TV-Novosti TV company.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe APN heads included Boris Burkov (1961\u201370), Ivan Udaltsov (1970\u201375), Lev Tolkunov (1975\u201383), Pavel Naumov (1983\u201386), [[Valentin Falin]] (1986\u201388), Albert Vlasov (1988\u201390).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n[[Image:Newsroom RIA Novosti, Moscow 2.jpg|right|thumb|240px|The newsroom of the agency, 2008]]\nBy a decree of USSR President Mikhail Gorbachev, \"On the Establishment of the Information Agency Novosti,\" the Information Agency Novosti (IAN) succeeded APN on 27 July 1990. \"To provide information support for the USSR's state domestic and foreign policies and proceeding from the interests of the democratization of the mass media,\" the Novosti Press Agency was renamed the Information Agency Novosti (IAN). IAN's tasks remained the same \u2013 preparing and publishing printed, TV and radio materials in the USSR and abroad; studying public opinion on Soviet foreign and domestic policies in the USSR and abroad.\" A computer databank was created in the Agency. Initially, it contained over 250,000 documents. In 1991, the Infonews hotline started operating in the Agency. IAN had bureaus in 120 countries. It published 13 illustrated magazines and newspapers. The chairman of the IAN Board was Albert Ivanovich Vlasov.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n===Russian Federation===\n\n[[File:Information Office - Embassy of Russia in Washington, D.C.JPG|thumb|240px|RIA Novosti bureau in Washington DC]]\nThe Russian Information Agency Novosti was created in September 1991 on the basis of IAN and the Russian Information Agency. By a [[Decree of the President of Russia|Presidential decree]] of the Russian president dated 22 August 1991, RIA Novosti was placed within the competence of the Press and Information Ministry. RIA Novosti had about 80 bureaus and news offices abroad, over 1,500 subscribers in CIS countries and about a hundred in non-CIS countries. A Presidential decree of the [[President of Russia|Russian president]] of 15 September 1993 \"''On the Russian Information Agency Novosti''\", transformed RIA Novosti to a state news-analytical agency. RIA Novosti's radio channel \u2013 RIA-Radio worked in 1996. In August 1997, the TV channel Kultura was set up on the basis of the RIA TV channel under the sponsorship of the [[VGTRK]] TV and radio broadcasting company. By a decree of the Russian president, \"On Improving the Work of the State Electronic Media,\" the VGTRK information holding was created in May 1998, which RIA Novosti joined.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nIn May 1998, the agency was renamed the Russian Information Agency Vesti. As a mass media body, it retained the name of RIA Novosti.<ref name=\"about\"/> In 2005, RIA Novosti launched [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (originally Russia Today) a global multilingual television news network, which is a government-funded but autonomous, [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]]. RIA Novosti asserts that it \"merely participated in establishing the channel\" which retained \"complete legal, editorial and operational independence.\"<ref>Nikolaus von Twickel. [http://rbth.ru/articles/2010/03/23/230310_rt.html Russia Today courts viewers with controversy]. ''[[The Moscow Times]]''. 23 March 2010.</ref>\n\n===Closing===\nOn 9 December 2013 Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] signed the liquidation of RIA Novosti and merging it with the international radio service [[Voice of Russia]] to create [[Rossiya Segodnya]].<ref name=PutinL/> [[Dmitry Kiselyov]], a former anchorman of the [[Channel One Russia]] is appointed as the president of the new information agency.<ref name=LentaL/><ref>{{cite news|title=RIA Novosti to Be Liquidated in State-Owned Media Overhaul|url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20131209/185390572/Russia-Announces-State-Owned-Media-Overhaul.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=RIA Novosti|date=9 December 2013}}</ref> According to her interview, the editor-in-chief of the TV network RT, [[Margarita Simonyan]] was completely unaware about the reorganization of the information agency and got the information from listening to competitor radio station [[Kommersant|Kommersant-FM]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043d\u044c\u044f\u043d \u0443\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f\" \u0438\u0437 \u0421\u041c\u0418|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/12/09/simonyan/|publisher=[[Lenta.ru|Lenta]]}}</ref> However, Rossiya Segodnya will not in any way be related to the television channel [[RT (TV network)|RT]], which was known as Russia Today before its rebranding in 2009.<ref name=RT>{{cite news|title=Putin orders overhaul of top state news agency|url=http://rt.com/news/ria-novosti-overhaul-putin-960/|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=RT|date=9 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable journalists==\n* [[Vsevolod Kukushkin]], ice hockey and sports correspondent (22 years)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chitaem-vmeste.ru/zvyozdy/interviews/vsevolod-kukushkin-u-kazhdogo-igroka-est-svoe-mesto-v-istorii-hokkeya|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434 \u041a\u0443\u043a\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d: \"\u0423 \u043a\u0430\u0436\u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0433\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0445\u043e\u043a\u043a\u0435\u044f\"|date=1 March 2018|website=chitaem-vmeste.ru|language=ru|access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]]\n* [[Russian Industrial Leaders Index]]\n* [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.rian.ru/ }} {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/en.rian.ru RIA Novosti {{in lang|en}}]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060913092839/http://rusnews.cn/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|zh}}]\n* [http://fr.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|fr}}]\n* [http://de.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|de}}]\n* [http://sp.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|es}}]\n* [http://ar.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|ar}}]\n* [http://pe.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|fa}}]\n* [http://www.fapmc.ru/rospechat/rospechat/lwr/unitar/item130.html RIA Novosti Charter] on [[Federal Agency on Press and Mass Communications of the Russian Federation]] website\n\n{{News agencies}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Russia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:News agencies based in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian news websites]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Eastern Bloc media]]\n[[Category:1941 establishments in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1941]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Media in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:Federal State Unitary Enterprises of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|Russian state-operated domestic (and former international) news agency}}\n{{Coord|55|44|15.38|N|37|35|24.92|E|region:US_dim:540|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name = [[FSUE]] Russian Agency of International Information \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb<br />([[FSUE]] RAMI \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb)\n|logo = RIA Novosti.png\n|logo_size = 200px\n|type = [[Federal State Unitary Enterprise]]\n|foundation = {{Start date|df=yes|1941|06}} (as [[Soviet Information Bureau|Sovinformburo]])\n|successor = [[Rossiya Segodnya]], [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]], ria.ru\n|defunct = 1 April 2014\n|location = [[Zubovsky Boulevard]] 4, [[Moscow]], Russia\n|key_people = [[Svetlana Mironyuk]]\n|revenue =\n|industry = News media\n|products = [[News agency|Wire service]]\n|owner= [[Rossiya Segodnya]] (which is owned and operated by [[Government of Russia|federal government]] (as [[unitary enterprise]]))\n|operating_income =\n|net_income =\n|num_employees =\n|parent =\n|subsid =\n|footnotes =\n|homepage = {{URL|https://ria.ru}} (Russian version)<br />{{URL|https://sputniknews.com|SputnikNews.com}} (English version)\n}}\n'''RIA Novosti''' ({{lang-ru|\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}), sometimes '''RIA''' ({{lang-ru|\u0420\u0418\u0410}}) for short, was a [[Russian]] state-operated domestic [[news agency]], which used to be one of Russia's international [[news agencies]] until 2013.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/country_profiles/1102275.stm#media Country profile: Russia \u2013 Media], BBC News, last updated 6 March 2012.</ref> Operating under the purview of the Russian [[Ministry of Communications and Mass Media (Russia)|Ministry of Communications and Mass Media]], RIA Novosti is headquartered in [[Moscow]] and operated about 80 bureaus internationally. On 9 December 2013 [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] [[Decree of the President of Russia|ordered]] RIA Novosti's liquidation and the creation of a Russian international news agency [[Rossiya Segodnya]].<ref name=PutinL>{{cite web|title=\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u043e \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u044d\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u041c\u0418|url=http://www.kremlin.ru/acts/19805|publisher=[[Kremlin.ru]]}}</ref> [[Dmitry Konstantinovich Kiselev|Dmitry Kiselev]], an anchorman of the [[Russia-1 (TV channel)|Russia-1]] channel was appointed to be the first president of the new information agency.<ref name=LentaL>{{cite news|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/12/09/ria/|newspaper=[[Lenta.ru|Lenta]]|date=9 December 2013}}</ref> RIA Novosti was scheduled to be closed down in 2014; starting in March 2014, staff were informed that they had the option of transferring their contracts to Rossiya Segodnya or accepting voluntary redundancy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ria Novosti Preps For Change|url=http://www.sptimes.ru/story/39333?page=1#top|publisher=[[The St. Petersburg Times]]|date=12 March 2014}}</ref> On 10 November 2014, Rossiya Segodnya launched the [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] multimedia platform as the international replacement of RIA Novosti and [[Voice of Russia]]. Within Russia itself, however, Rossiya Segodnya continues to operate its Russian language news service under the name RIA Novosti with its ria.ru website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/204231-sputnik-news-agency-launched/|title=Sputnik launched to news orbit: Russia\u2019s new intl media to offer alternative standpoint|website=RT International}}</ref>\n\nThe agency published news and analysis of social-political, economic, scientific and financial subjects on the Internet and via e-mail in the main European languages, as well as in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[Arabic language|Arabic]].<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|author=11 March 2014 0:18 |url=http://www.rianovosti.com/docs/about/novosti.html |title=The Russian News & Information Agency RIA Novosti |publisher=Rianovosti.com |accessdate=10 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928023413/http://rianovosti.com/docs/about/novosti.html |archivedate=28 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"arabic\">{{cite web|url=http://anbamoscow.com/ |title=RIA Arabic |publisher=Anbamoscow.com |date=14 December 2012 |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> It had a correspondent network in the [[Russian Federation]], [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]] and over 40 non-CIS countries.<ref name=\"about\"/> Its clients include the presidential administration, Russian government, Federation Council, [[State Duma]], leading ministries and government departments, administrations of Russian regions, representatives of Russian and foreign business communities, diplomatic missions, and public organizations.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nRIA Novosti was an award-winning news agency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.rian.ru/agency_news/20121122/177670392.html |title=RIA Novosti wins five Runet awards &#124; Agency News &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date=22 November 2012 |accessdate=10 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119105324/http://en.rian.ru/agency_news/20121122/177670392.html |archive-date=19 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The last editor-in-chief of RIA Novosti was [[Svetlana Mironyuk]],<ref name=\"about\"/> the first woman appointed to the role in the agency's history. According to the organisation's Charter, enterprise's property was federally owned (because federal [[unitary enterprise]]) and was indivisible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fapmc.ru/rospechat/rospechat/lwr/unitar/item130.html |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u044c - \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \"\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u041e\u0412\u041e\u0421\u0422\u0418\" |publisher=Fapmc.ru |date= |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.fapmc.ru/dms-static/affccc2c-7683-4c32-a917-68b82ed8f099.pdf</ref> According to the agency, it was partially government-subsidized (2.7\u20132.9 billion [[Russian rouble|roubles]] in 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ria.ru/economy/20121108/910092565.html |title=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0434\u0443\u043c\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b \u0443\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432 &#124; \u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |publisher=Ria.ru |date= |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>), but maintained full editorial independence.<ref>{{cite web |author=11 March 2014 0:18 |url=http://www.en.rian.ru/docs/about/novosti.html |title=RIA Novosti &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |accessdate=10 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001061437/http://www.en.rian.ru/docs/about/novosti.html |archive-date=1 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIts Russian name was '''[[Federal State Unitary Enterprise]] Russian Agency of International Information \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb''' ({{lang-ru|\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u00ab\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u00bb, Federal'noye Gosudarstvennoye Unitarnoye Predpyatye Rossiyskoye Agentsvo Mezhdunarodnoy Informatsii}}), ''[[Unitary enterprise|FGUP]] RAMI \u00abRIA Novosti\u00bb'' ({{lang-ru|\u0424\u0413\u0423\u041f \u0420\u0410\u041c\u0418 \u00ab\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u00bb}}) for short. Its formal English name was '''Russian News & Information Agency \"RIA Novosti\"'''. Early in 1990s it had the name '''state enterprise RIA \u00abNovosti\u00bb''' (named after Soviet ''Press Agency \u00abNovosti\u00bb'' and ''Information Agency \u00abNovosti\u00bb''). ''RIA'' means ''Russian Information Agency'' and ''Novosti'' means ''News'' in Russian. The common abbreviation in Russian is RIA.\n\n==History==\nRIA Novosti's history dates back to 24 June 1941, when by a resolution of the [[Government of the Soviet Union|USSR Council of People's Commissars]] and the Communist Party Central Committee, \"''On the Establishment and Tasks of the Soviet Information Bureau''\", the [[Soviet Information Bureau]] (Sovinformburo) was set up under the USSR Council of People's Commissars and the Central Committee. Its main task was to oversee work to cover international, military events and the events of the country's domestic life in periodicals and on the radio (from 14 October 1941, to 3 March 1942, was based in Kuibyshev \u2013 modern-day Samara).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe bureau's main task was to compile reports on the situation on the frontline of the war, work on the home front, and the partisan movement for the radio, newspapers and magazines. Sovinformburo directed the activity of the All-Slavonic Committee, Anti-Nazi Committee of Soviet Women, Anti-Nazi Committee of the Soviet Youth, Anti-Nazi Committee of Soviet Scientists, and the Jewish Anti-Nazi Committee. In 1944, a special bureau on propaganda for foreign countries was set up as part of Sovinformburo.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThrough 1,171 newspapers, 523 magazines and 18 radio stations in 23 countries, Soviet embassies abroad, friendship societies, trade unions, women's, youth and scientific organizations, Sovinformburo informed readers and listeners about the struggle of the Soviet people against Nazism and in the post-war years about the main areas of Soviet domestic and foreign policies.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nSovinformburo heads included [[Aleksandr Shcherbakov (politician)|A.S. Shcherbakov]] (1941\u201345), [[Solomon Lozovsky|S. A. Lozovsky]] (1945\u201348) and Y.S. Khavinson, D.A. Polikarpov.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n[[File:Newspaper stall and women in East Berlin, with person in wheelchair, 1984.jpg|thumb|right|Novosti operated this East Berlin [[news stall]] in 1984.]]\nIn 1961, the Novosti Press Agency (APN) succeeded Sovinformburo. It became the leading information and press body of [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] public organizations. The constituent conference was held on 21 February 1961. The conference of representatives of Soviet public organizations adopted a decision to create a press agency of public organizations named Novosti. The agency's guiding body was the Council of the Agency's Founders.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe APN founders were the USSR Journalists Union, USSR Writers Union, Union of Soviet Societies of Friendship and Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, and the Znaniye Society. On 3 April 1961, the Agency charter was adopted. Under its charter, APN's aim was \"to contribute to mutual understanding, trust and friendship among peoples in every possible way by broadly publishing accurate information about the USSR abroad and familiarizing the Soviet public with the life of the peoples of foreign countries.\" APN's motto was \"Information for Peace, for the Friendship of Nations\". APN had bureaus in over 120 countries. The Agency published 60 illustrated newspapers and magazines in 45 languages with a one-time circulation of 4.3 million copies. With the Union of Soviet Friendship Societies, APN published the newspaper, ''Moscow News'', which in September 1990 became an independent publication. APN Publishing House put out over 200 books and booklets with a total annual circulation of 20 million copies. In 1989, a TV center opened in APN. Later, it was transformed into the TV-Novosti TV company.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe APN heads included Boris Burkov (1961\u201370), Ivan Udaltsov (1970\u201375), Lev Tolkunov (1975\u201383), Pavel Naumov (1983\u201386), [[Valentin Falin]] (1986\u201388), Albert Vlasov (1988\u201390).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n[[Image:Newsroom RIA Novosti, Moscow 2.jpg|right|thumb|240px|The newsroom of the agency, 2008]]\nBy a decree of USSR President Mikhail Gorbachev, \"On the Establishment of the Information Agency Novosti,\" the Information Agency Novosti (IAN) succeeded APN on 27 July 1990. \"To provide information support for the USSR's state domestic and foreign policies and proceeding from the interests of the democratization of the mass media,\" the Novosti Press Agency was renamed the Information Agency Novosti (IAN). IAN's tasks remained the same \u2013 preparing and publishing printed, TV and radio materials in the USSR and abroad; studying public opinion on Soviet foreign and domestic policies in the USSR and abroad.\" A computer databank was created in the Agency. Initially, it contained over 250,000 documents. In 1991, the Infonews hotline started operating in the Agency. IAN had bureaus in 120 countries. It published 13 illustrated magazines and newspapers. The chairman of the IAN Board was Albert Ivanovich Vlasov.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n===Russian Federation===\n\n[[File:Information Office - Embassy of Russia in Washington, D.C.JPG|thumb|240px|RIA Novosti bureau in Washington DC]]\nThe Russian Information Agency Novosti was created in September 1991 on the basis of IAN and the Russian Information Agency. By a [[Decree of the President of Russia|Presidential decree]] of the Russian president dated 22 August 1991, RIA Novosti was placed within the competence of the Press and Information Ministry. RIA Novosti had about 80 bureaus and news offices abroad, over 1,500 subscribers in CIS countries and about a hundred in non-CIS countries. A Presidential decree of the [[President of Russia|Russian president]] of 15 September 1993 \"''On the Russian Information Agency Novosti''\", transformed RIA Novosti to a state news-analytical agency. RIA Novosti's radio channel \u2013 RIA-Radio worked in 1996. In August 1997, the TV channel Kultura was set up on the basis of the RIA TV channel under the sponsorship of the [[VGTRK]] TV and radio broadcasting company. By a decree of the Russian president, \"On Improving the Work of the State Electronic Media,\" the VGTRK information holding was created in May 1998, which RIA Novosti joined.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nIn May 1998, the agency was renamed the Russian Information Agency Vesti. As a mass media body, it retained the name of RIA Novosti.<ref name=\"about\"/> In 2005, RIA Novosti launched [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (originally Russia Today) a global multilingual television news network, which is a government-funded but autonomous, [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]]. RIA Novosti asserts that it \"merely participated in establishing the channel\" which retained \"complete legal, editorial and operational independence.\"<ref>Nikolaus von Twickel. [http://rbth.ru/articles/2010/03/23/230310_rt.html Russia Today courts viewers with controversy]. ''[[The Moscow Times]]''. 23 March 2010.</ref>\n\n===Closing===\nOn 9 December 2013 Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] signed the liquidation of RIA Novosti and merging it with the international radio service [[Voice of Russia]] to create [[Rossiya Segodnya]].<ref name=PutinL/> [[Dmitry Kiselyov]], a former anchorman of the [[Channel One Russia]] is appointed as the president of the new information agency.<ref name=LentaL/><ref>{{cite news|title=RIA Novosti to Be Liquidated in State-Owned Media Overhaul|url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20131209/185390572/Russia-Announces-State-Owned-Media-Overhaul.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=RIA Novosti|date=9 December 2013}}</ref> According to her interview, the editor-in-chief of the TV network RT, [[Margarita Simonyan]] was completely unaware about the reorganization of the information agency and got the information from listening to competitor radio station [[Kommersant|Kommersant-FM]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043d\u044c\u044f\u043d \u0443\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f\" \u0438\u0437 \u0421\u041c\u0418|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/12/09/simonyan/|publisher=[[Lenta.ru|Lenta]]}}</ref> However, Rossiya Segodnya will not in any way be related to the television channel [[RT (TV network)|RT]], which was known as Russia Today before its rebranding in 2009.<ref name=RT>{{cite news|title=Putin orders overhaul of top state news agency|url=http://rt.com/news/ria-novosti-overhaul-putin-960/|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=RT|date=9 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable journalists==\n* [[Vsevolod Kukushkin]], ice hockey and sports correspondent (22 years)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chitaem-vmeste.ru/zvyozdy/interviews/vsevolod-kukushkin-u-kazhdogo-igroka-est-svoe-mesto-v-istorii-hokkeya|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434 \u041a\u0443\u043a\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d: \"\u0423 \u043a\u0430\u0436\u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0433\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0445\u043e\u043a\u043a\u0435\u044f\"|date=1 March 2018|website=chitaem-vmeste.ru|language=ru|access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]]\n* [[Russian Industrial Leaders Index]]\n* [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.rian.ru/ }} {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/en.rian.ru RIA Novosti {{in lang|en}}]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060913092839/http://rusnews.cn/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|zh}}]\n* [http://fr.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|fr}}]\n* [http://de.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|de}}]\n* [http://sp.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|es}}]\n* [http://ar.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|ar}}]\n* [http://pe.rian.ru/ RIA Novosti {{in lang|fa}}]\n* [http://www.fapmc.ru/rospechat/rospechat/lwr/unitar/item130.html RIA Novosti Charter] on [[Federal Agency on Press and Mass Communications of the Russian Federation]] website\n\n{{News agencies}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Russia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:News agencies based in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian news websites]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Eastern Bloc media]]\n[[Category:1941 establishments in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1941]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Media in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:Federal State Unitary Enterprises of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n", "name_user": "LittleWink", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRussian(link changed toRussia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RIA_Novosti"}
