ehndawal 16.26% of the population is under 6 years of age.<ref name=\"census\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sant Kabir Nagar district}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Sant Kabir Nagar district]]\n\n{{SantKabirNagar-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shailu raj1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mehdawal"}
{"title_page": "Kori caste", "text_new": "{{Short description|Indian caste}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n'''Kori''' (also called ''[[Koli people|Koli]]'' or ''Koliyar''), is an [[Indian caste]], who were traditionally weavers.<ref>{{cite book |author=M. P. S. Chandel |title=Democratic Transformation of a Social Class |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ao5tlGH2sFQC&pg=PA49 |year=1991 |publisher=Mittal Publications |isbn=978-81-7099-314-8 |page=49 }}</ref> Other names for this caste include Koli, Kamal, Kamalvansi, Dhiman, Aharwar, and Sankhawar.<ref>{{cite book |author=Badri Narayan |title=Women Heroes and Dalit Assertion in North India: Culture, Identity and Politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7feHAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA119 |year=2006 |publisher=SAGE |isbn=978-81-321-0280-9 |page=119 }}</ref>\n\nThe Koris are classified as a [[Scheduled Caste]] in the states of [[Himachal Pradesh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admis.hp.nic.in/himachal/hpscstdc/CastesEng(sc).htm|title=List of Scheduled Castes|publisher=[[Government of Himachal Pradesh]]|accessdate=25 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619073947/http://admis.hp.nic.in/himachal/hpscstdc/CastesEng(sc).htm|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/UP-government-has-clarified-that-kori-caste-is-considered-as-scheduled-caste-and-certificates-are-being-issued-to-the-people-belonging-to-the-particular-caste-The-government-spokesman-denied-allegation-of-oposition-parties-that-koris-have-been-dropped-from-the-list-of-scheduled-castes-/articleshow/7527196.cms |title=UP government has clarified that kori caste is considered as scheduled caste |author=Ashish Tripathi |date=19 February 2011 |newspaper=The Times of India }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttarpradesh.pdf |title=Scheduled castes of Uttar Pradesh |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315115455/http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttarpradesh.pdf |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Uttarakhand]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttaranchal.pdf |title=Scheduled castes of Uttarakhand |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315101341/http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttaranchal.pdf |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The name \"Kori\" derives from the word \"kora\" (clean cloth), which refers to their traditional occupation.<ref>{{cite book |title=India's Communities |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g9MVAQAAMAAJ |author=K. S. Singh |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-563354-2 |page=1822 }}</ref> Some Koris claim descent from [[Kabir]].<ref>{{cite book |author=B. V. Bhanu |title=People of India: Maharashtra |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BsBEgVa804IC&pg=PA1118 |year=2004 |publisher=Popular Prakashan |isbn=978-81-7991-101-3 |page=1118 }}</ref> The word 'koli' also means spider or a weaver of web, alluding to their occupation of weaving.<ref>{{cite book|title=Feeding the City: Work and Food Culture of the Mumbai Dabbawalas|url=https://archive.org/details/Feeding_the_City|author=Sara Roncaglia|publisher=Open Book Publishers |year=2013|page=7}}</ref>\n\n[[Harold A. Gould |Harold Gould]] noted in his research of the [[jajmani system|Jajmani System]] in Uttar Pradesh that by the 1960s, all of the Koris in the villages studied by him had adopted roles as agricultural labourers, ploughmen because industrialisation had made their traditional occupation as weavers redundant.<ref>{{cite journal |title=A Jajmani System of North India: Its Structure, Magnitude, and Meaning |first=Harold A. |last=Gould |authorlink=Harold A. Gould |journal=Ethnology |volume=3 |issue=1 |date=January 1964 |pages=12-41 |jstor=4617554}}</ref> The Kori scheduled caste population in Uttar Pradesh at the [[2011 census of India]] was 2,293,937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/SC_ST/PCA-A10/SC-0900-PCA-A-10-ddw.xlsx |title= A-10 Individual Scheduled Caste Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix - Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=2017-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{India-ethno-stub}}\n[[Category:Weaving communities of South Asia]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Castes of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Castes of Uttarakhand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Indian caste}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n'''Kori''', also known as [[Koli people|Koli]] and Koliyar, is an [[Indian caste]], who were traditionally weavers.<ref>{{cite book |author=M. P. S. Chandel |title=Democratic Transformation of a Social Class |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ao5tlGH2sFQC&pg=PA49 |year=1991 |publisher=Mittal Publications |isbn=978-81-7099-314-8 |page=49 }}</ref> Other names for this caste include Koli, Kamal, Kamalvansi, Dhiman, Aharwar, and Sankhawar.<ref>{{cite book |author=Badri Narayan |title=Women Heroes and Dalit Assertion in North India: Culture, Identity and Politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7feHAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA119 |year=2006 |publisher=SAGE |isbn=978-81-321-0280-9 |page=119 }}</ref>\n\nThe Koris are classified as a [[Scheduled Caste]] in the states of [[Himachal Pradesh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admis.hp.nic.in/himachal/hpscstdc/CastesEng(sc).htm|title=List of Scheduled Castes|publisher=[[Government of Himachal Pradesh]]|accessdate=25 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619073947/http://admis.hp.nic.in/himachal/hpscstdc/CastesEng(sc).htm|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/UP-government-has-clarified-that-kori-caste-is-considered-as-scheduled-caste-and-certificates-are-being-issued-to-the-people-belonging-to-the-particular-caste-The-government-spokesman-denied-allegation-of-oposition-parties-that-koris-have-been-dropped-from-the-list-of-scheduled-castes-/articleshow/7527196.cms |title=UP government has clarified that kori caste is considered as scheduled caste |author=Ashish Tripathi |date=19 February 2011 |newspaper=The Times of India }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttarpradesh.pdf |title=Scheduled castes of Uttar Pradesh |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315115455/http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttarpradesh.pdf |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Uttarakhand]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttaranchal.pdf |title=Scheduled castes of Uttarakhand |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315101341/http://socialjustice.gov.in/pdf/scorderuttaranchal.pdf |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The name \"Kori\" derives from the word \"kora\" (clean cloth), which refers to their traditional occupation.<ref>{{cite book |title=India's Communities |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g9MVAQAAMAAJ |author=K. S. Singh |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-563354-2 |page=1822 }}</ref> Some Koris claim descent from [[Kabir]].<ref>{{cite book |author=B. V. Bhanu |title=People of India: Maharashtra |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BsBEgVa804IC&pg=PA1118 |year=2004 |publisher=Popular Prakashan |isbn=978-81-7991-101-3 |page=1118 }}</ref> The word 'koli' also means spider or a weaver of web, alluding to their occupation of weaving.<ref>{{cite book|title=Feeding the City: Work and Food Culture of the Mumbai Dabbawalas|url=https://archive.org/details/Feeding_the_City|author=Sara Roncaglia|publisher=Open Book Publishers |year=2013|page=7}}</ref>\n\n[[Harold A. Gould |Harold Gould]] noted in his research of the [[jajmani system|Jajmani System]] in Uttar Pradesh that by the 1960s, all of the Koris in the villages studied by him had adopted roles as agricultural labourers, ploughmen because industrialisation had made their traditional occupation as weavers redundant.<ref>{{cite journal |title=A Jajmani System of North India: Its Structure, Magnitude, and Meaning |first=Harold A. |last=Gould |authorlink=Harold A. Gould |journal=Ethnology |volume=3 |issue=1 |date=January 1964 |pages=12-41 |jstor=4617554}}</ref> The Kori scheduled caste population in Uttar Pradesh at the [[2011 census of India]] was 2,293,937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/SC_ST/PCA-A10/SC-0900-PCA-A-10-ddw.xlsx |title= A-10 Individual Scheduled Caste Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix - Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=2017-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{India-ethno-stub}}\n[[Category:Weaving communities of South Asia]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Castes of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Castes of Uttarakhand]]\n", "name_user": "Nittawinoda", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kori_caste"}
